<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 300 Little Caesars To Get Makeovers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The abrupt closure of 300 Little Caesars pizzerias does not mean  
the Detroit-based company can't stand the heat and is getting out 
of the kitchen as it battles to keep its shrinking market share. 
</P>
<P>
	Just the opposite, Harsha Agadi , president of Little Caesars  
Enterprises Inc., said in an interview Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's No. 3 pizza restaurant is beginning a multimillion  
dollar overhaul to make its stores more appetizing, especially to 
teen-agers, and to appeal to convenience-minded consumers with 
features like drive-thrus, Agadi said. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision last week leaves Dallas, Pittsburgh and  
Indianapolis without any freestanding Little Caesar pizza outlets 
for the time being. Stores were also closed in Houston, Denver and 
other cities but the franchises in those areas remain open. 
</P>
<P>
	All 300 closed stores will either be remodeled or relocated  
sometime in the next 12 months as part of a ``triple-digit'' 
multimillion dollar makeover, Agadi said. He did not know how many 
employees were affected by the recent closings, but said they were 
informed of the company's decision the same day the stores were 
closed. 
</P>
<P>
	Agadi declined to discuss the privately held company's finances,  
other than to say its debt is among the lowest in the industry and 
its owners, Detroit sports magnates Michael and Marian Ilitch, 
remain committed to its future. 
</P>
<P>
	But last year, some franchise owners complained the fast-food  
chain was doing a poor job and that its ``2-for-1'' pizza deals 
make it hard to make money. There were also layoffs at Little 
Caesars corporate headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	And Ron Paul of Technomic Inc., a Chicago consulting firm, says  
Little Caesars is losing market share at the expense of No. 4 Papa 
John's International Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul estimates Little Caesar's sales fell 7 percent to $1.76  
billion last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody slipped a little bit last year,'' Paul said. ``But  
it appears (Papa John's) took a bigger bite out of Little 
Caesars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Paul said Papa John's is also affecting sales and market share  
of the No. 1 and No. 2 pizza restaurants: Tricon Global Restaurants 
Inc.'s Pizza Hut and Bain Capital Inc.'s Domino's Pizza Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The 300 shuttered Little Caesar stores represent more than a  
quarter of the 1,100 pizza outlets owned by Little Caesars 
nationwide. There are another 3,300 franchise operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Agadi said all the company-owned stores will undergo ``Image  
2000'' remodeling in the next five years, although they probably 
won't close their doors because they are in more profitable 
locations. 
</P>
<P>
	Franchise owners are also being urged to remodel.  
</P>
<P>
	Agadi said the new stores will emphasize quality and  
convenience, two key components of the company's expansion 
strategy. In addition to drive-thrus, there also may be some new 
menu items. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to make it so customer-friendly with drive-through  
units ... and kids are going to love it,'' said Agadi, who is also 
the chain's chief operating officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Little Caesars, which already has outlets overseas, will also  
open stores later this year in Iceland, Bahrain, Qatar and 
Guatemala. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
