<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MIT Said To Pull Graduate's Diploma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The Massachusetts Institute of Technology has  
taken back the diploma of a 23-year man accused of providing 
alcohol at a 1997 fraternity party that left a freshman dead from 
alcohol poisoning, his lawyer says. 
</P>
<P>
	The school's decision was made Wednesday, after Charles Yoo and  
attorney Timothy Burke attended a hearing before the MIT Committee 
on Discipline, Burke said. Yoo now works as a stockbroker in 
Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	Yoo, 23, who graduated in 1998, will sue MIT, Burke said. School  
officials declined to comment on the decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said Scott Krueger died in September 1997 after he was  
forced to drink huge quantities of liquor as part of a pledge 
contest at the Phi Gamma Delta fraternity house. Krueger's blood 
alcohol level of .401 was five times the legal limit. 
</P>
<P>
	Yoo was the pledge trainer at the fraternity and provided  
freshman -- including Krueger -- with whiskey and beer, authorities 
say. 
</P>
<P>
	Burke said MIT's punishment of Yoo was too harsh, and could cost  
Yoo his job. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that the student who gave Krueger a bottle of rum was  
only suspended for a semester. 
</P>
<P>
	``MIT needed to scapegoat someone,'' Burke said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
