<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Officials Enforce Ignored Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- No blood, no foul? Not this summer.  
</P>
<P>
	Whistles are blowing and players are grumbling in the NBA's  
summer leagues, where officials are using a by-the-book approach to 
experimental rules aimed at boosting offense. Long-ignored rules 
are being enforced. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're calling the rules very literally. That's their job  
right now,'' said Portland coach Mike Dunleavy, watching his team 
of rookies and regular-season bench-warmers at the Rocky Mountain 
Revue. 
</P>
<P>
	A defender who uses a hand check or a forearm is immediately  
whistled for a foul. Likewise, an offensive player who moves while 
setting a screen will get tagged with a foul. 
</P>
<P>
	Another experimental rule bars defenders from impeding offensive  
players cutting through the lane. 
</P>
<P>
	Try guarding Shaquille O'Neal in the low post without a forearm  
in his back, or stop Allen Iverson off the dribble without a hand 
check. 
</P>
<P>
	``Players are used to putting their hands on people and moving  
them around,'' Sacramento coach Rick Adelman said. ``If they're not 
allowed to do that, it's going to make it much harder to guard 
people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One rule seeks to make illegal defense guidelines more  
understandable. Another sets the shot clock at 14 seconds after 
fouls or out-of-bounds plays in the frontcourt, rather than the 
usual 24 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	NBA director of officiating Ed Rush said the changes are  
intended to reinvigorate the plodding offenses of the 1990s, 
returning the league to the 100-point games that were the norm in 
earlier decades. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have the best athletes in the world,'' Rush said from the  
NBA offices in New York. ``Quickness and pure athleticism are big 
parts of basketball. We want to make sure our athletes have the 
chance to showcase their talents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But it backfired last week as play during some Salt Lake City  
games was agonizingly slow. 
</P>
<P>
	The Utah Jazz summer team had 49 fouls in one 40-minute game,  
the typical total in an NBA game for both teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Rush stressed no decision has been made on using the rules in  
the regular season. A 16-member committee of past and present 
players, coaches and front-office officials will meet before the 
season to evaluate the experiment. 
</P>
<P>
	``Will it make a difference if they call it like this during the  
regular season?'' Antonio Daniels of the San Antonio Spurs asked. 
``Without question. I think you'll see a lot of guys in foul 
trouble. A lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Daniels found a silver lining.  
</P>
<P>
	``On defense, you have to play with your feet and do more than  
using your hands,'' he said. ``Offensively, if you're quicker than 
somebody who's guarding you, it gives you a huge advantage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coaches and players at the Rocky Mountain Revue were reluctant  
to publicly criticize the experiment, but most agreed there's been 
plenty of griping in the locker room. 
</P>
<P>
	``Better to try it out here than in the regular season,''  
Adelman said. ``Everybody's going to complain. Players and coaches 
just have to adjust.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Daniels agrees players will have to deal with any changes.  
</P>
<P>
	``This takes you back to the fundamental way basketball is  
supposed to be played,'' Daniels said. ``Whether you like it or not 
is irrelevant. If they change the rules, you deal with it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
