<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Va. Steelworkers End Shipyard Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWPORT NEWS, Va. (AP) -- Steelworkers at Newport News  
Shipbuilding ended their 16 1/2-week strike Friday, approving a 
58-month contract with the nation's only builder of aircraft 
carriers. 
</P>
<P>
	Union members voted 2,724 to 1,696 to approve a contract that  
provides a pay raise averaging $3.10 an hour over 58 months and 
improves the pension plan for longtime workers, said union 
spokesman John Duray. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's time to put down the picket signs, pick up the tools and  
go back with our heads held high,'' said Arnold Outlaw, president 
of Local 8888 of the United Steelworkers of America, which 
represents 9,200 workers at the yard, about half its work force. 
</P>
<P>
	``This agreement comes after much hard work and important  
compromises by both sides,'' said shipyard spokesman Mike Hatfield. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the union hall, members remained divided.  
</P>
<P>
	William McGlone Jr., 40, of Hampton, a welder with 20 years  
experience at the yard, said the contract is two years too long. 
``Those last two years are going to be a long two years,'' he said. 
He said he would vote against the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Outlaw said he did not like the length of the contract either,  
``but we have to give a little to gain a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Union members will begin returning to work next week. The  
company reserved the right to take as long as 28 days to recall 
workers, because of work schedules and because some workers may 
need to be retrained. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
