<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 23:30:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Dems Condemn GOP Reductions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democrats are on the attack as House  
Republicans carve money out of social programs and use the funds to 
boost veterans, space and other items. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll meet the obligations of the country, but in a  
conservative way,'' Rep. James Walsh, R-N.Y., said Friday as the 
House Appropriations Committee approved by voice vote a $92 billion 
measure financing veterans, housing, space and environment programs 
for the coming fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	Walsh was the bill's chief architect. The Senate hasn't written  
its version of the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	To bolster the legislation's chance of House passage next week,  
Walsh and his GOP colleagues increased its funds for NASA and 
veterans. To do so, they killed the Americorps national service 
program, cut disaster response funds, and transferred $4 billion 
out of a separate measure providing $300 billion for health, 
education and labor programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The changes were approved by voice vote.  
</P>
<P>
	Facing tight, legally required spending caps, Republicans have  
spent months shifting billions among the 13 annual spending bills 
for fiscal 2000, which starts Oct. 1. Committee Chairman Bill 
Young, R-Fla., said Friday's actions would be ``the last time we 
rob Peter to pay Paul.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Democrats condemned the reductions, saying they would result  
in huge cuts in medical research, job training, school aid and 
other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're looking at a long and tortured fall,'' said Rep.  
David Obey of Wisconsin, top Democrat on the committee, referring 
to inevitable bargaining between Congress and the White House over 
several of the spending bills. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter, White House budget chief Jacob Lew said the cut in  
the labor-education bill would be ``irresponsible'' and would show 
that overall GOP spending plans are ``simply unworkable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The committee added $400 million to NASA's 2000 budget, bringing  
it to about $12.7 billion. That remains $1 billion below this 
year's budget and $900 million short of Clinton's request. 
</P>
<P>
	``I appeal to members of Congress to fully restore the  
president's budget,'' NASA Administrator Daniel Goldin said in a 
written statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The added NASA money would go to projects including Mars  
exploration and a planned orbiting infrared telescope, which an 
earlier version of the bill had cut. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA officials, who earlier had said the agency's Jet Propulsion  
Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif., and Goddard Space Flight Center in 
Greenbelt, Md., might be in jeopardy of closing, said they did not 
yet know whether the threat remains with the new numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel boosted spending for veterans' health care by $700  
million, responding to pressure from veterans' groups. That would 
bring the program's total to $19 billion, $700 million more than 
Clinton has proposed. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee also removed controversial emergency designations  
for $5.5 billion worth of spending for veterans and disaster 
relief. The emergency label lets Congress ignore required spending 
limits and pay for items with the anticipated federal budget 
surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	The labor, health and education measure -- the biggest of all 13  
annual spending bills, and the last to be written -- won't begin 
moving through committee until September. The $4 billion shifted 
out of it Friday left the measure almost $17 billion below this 
year's levels and $20 billion short of what Clinton wants. 
</P>
<P>
	But Republicans are looking to add money back to it, and are  
considering several budget gimmicks to accomplish that. 
</P>
<P>
	In the latest, they would delay some federal Medicaid payments  
to the states from late September 2000 into early October, said 
aides, who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	That timing shift would push the expenditure out of the books  
for fiscal year 2000 and into 2001. That would allow Republicans to 
claim savings next year of several billion dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, the committee used successive party-line votes to hold  
fast to its prior decision to label the $4.5 billion cost of the 
2000 census an emergency. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans said unless they did so, FBI agents would have to be  
laid off and 80 U.S. embassies closed. Democratic efforts first to 
remove the emergency label for the entire $4.5 billion, and then 
for a portion of it, lost by 30-26 and 32-26. 
</P>
<P>
	That fight came as the panel used a voice vote to approve a  
$37.7 billion measure financing the departments of justice, state 
and commerce for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	White House advisers have threatened a veto because the  
legislation cuts Clinton's requests for hiring police officers, 
legal aid for the poor, U.S. participation in international 
organizations and other programs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
