<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grain Futures Up on Hot Weather / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
        CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain futures prices were higher Friday on  
the Chicago Board of Trade as the Midwest continued to bake under stifling 
heat and humidity. 
</P>
<P>
        Grains started higher on follow-through from Thursday's strong  
showing, and mostly maintained the gains through the close. 
</P>
<P>
        Both corn and wheat posted gains, shaking off news that more  
favorable weather may be in store for heat-addled growing regions. 
September and December wheat contracts hit their highest levels of 
the month. 
</P>
<P>
        ``This week we went through a critical time frame with corn,  
'' said Don Roose, president of Iowa-based U.S. Commodities Inc. ``For 
the areas that didn't get the rain, this heat really took a toll.'' 
</P>
<P>
        The heat, which reached the high 90s and triple digits in key  
growing states Friday, could bake parched crops and reduce yields. 
</P>
<P>
        Gains were limited by the more favorable weather forecasts  
for this weekend and next week. Forecasters are calling for rain and 
cooler temperatures throughout the region. 
</P>
<P>
        Soybean prices were mixed Friday.  
</P>
<P>
        ``The soybeans can withstand the heat a lot better than the  
corn,'' Roose said. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat for December delivery rose 6 1/4 cents to $2.79 3/4 a  
bushel; December corn rose 3 1/4 cents to $2.14 1/2 a bushel; December 
oats fell 4 3/4 cents to $1.11 3/4 a bushel; November soybeans fell 
1/4 cent to $4.33 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
        Beef futures were mixed and pork higher Friday on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
        August live cattle fell .10 cent to 64.22 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose .17 cent to 76.87 cents a pound; August lean hogs 
rose .67 cents to 48.27 cents a pound; August pork bellies rose 3.0 
cents to 52.12 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
