<DOCNO> APW19990730.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 17:30:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Braves Observe Moment of Silence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Atlanta Braves observed a minute of silence  
before the start of Friday night's game in memory of people killed 
in a shooting rampage in the city. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark O. Barton, a chemist turned day stock-trader, walked into  
two brokerage firms where he traded and fired randomly Thursday. 
Nine died and 13 were wounded. His wife, son and daughter were 
later found bludgeoned to death in the family home. 
</P>
<P>
	Barton killed himself a few hours later when police closed in on  
him at a gas station. 
</P>
<P>
	Turner Broadcasting System, which owns the Braves, said that  
while the company and team shared the city's ``profound sorrow,'' 
they felt they could best serve the community by playing the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our hearts go out to the families who lost loved ones and we  
wish a full, rapid recovery for those who were injured,'' the TBS 
statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	Braves general manager John Schuerholz said: ``The important  
thing for us to do is focus on the families and the awful 
circumstances they're having to deal with. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never been in a situation like this. It's horrible for  
everyone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta pitcher Tom Glavine wants the team to wear a special  
patch on its uniforms for the rest of the year. The Braves wore 
nothing Friday night in honor of the victims and their plans were 
not immediately clear. 
</P>
<P>
	``What happened is a situation that makes us all open our eyes.  
One, that there's a lot of crazy things going on out there, and 
two, that you can't take for granted what you have,'' Glavine said 
before the game against the Philadelphia Phillies. 
</P>
<P>
	Right fielder Brian Jordan admitted he's often fearful of crowds  
of any size. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's going on in our society?'' Jordan asked. ``It's scary.  
You just never know when something could happen to you in your job. 
Guys go crazy and shoot people for no reason. It really makes you 
think.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In April, three of Denver's professional sports teams canceled  
games after a shooting spree at suburban Columbine High School left 
15 people dead and 23 wounded. 
</P>
<P>
	The Denver Nuggets postponed a game that was scheduled to start  
about eight hours after the rampage began. The Colorado Rockies 
postponed two games, and the Colorado Avalanche postponed two 
playoff games. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillies first baseman Rico Brogna said he believed the Braves  
would have postponed the game if it had been scheduled on the day 
of the shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	``We played the first game after the Columbine shootings, and I  
think the people there were ready for some kind of normalcy to 
return to the community,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
