<DOCNO> APW19990730.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 15:10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Promoter May Stop Races at Charlotte </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- The promoter of the speedway where three  
spectators were killed during an Indy Racing League event in May is 
leaning toward not bringing the series back to the track. 
</P>
<P>
	Speedway Motorsports Inc. is concerned about how questions of  
fan safety, declining attendance and car design could affect the 
IRL's future at Lowe's Motor Speedway at Charlotte, company 
president H.A. ``Humpy'' Wheeler told The Associated Press on 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're really taking a hard look at Charlotte,'' Wheeler said.  
``The IRL people are good people. We don't want to drop them. But 
at the same time, we've got shareholders we've got to appease. So 
we're going to continue to study this thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wheeler said officials of Concord-based SMI have until  
mid-October to make a final decision on whether to bring the IRL 
back next year to the 1.5-mile, high-banked superspeedway in the 
north Charlotte suburbs. 
</P>
<P>
	IRL officials, who first came to the heart of stock car racing  
country three years ago, said they were not giving up hope of 
competing again at Charlotte. 
</P>
<P>
	``A promoter has to do what's best for their facility, and I  
think a promoter ultimately would have the best sense of that,'' 
IRL spokesman Ron Green said by telephone from Dover, Del., where 
the circuit has a race scheduled Sunday. ``Our teams love competing 
in Charlotte and would love the opportunity to race there again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Five of the 11 races on this year's IRL schedule are run at  
facilities operated by Concord-based SMI. Wheeler said the company 
is leaning toward retaining the rest of its IRL races for next 
year, which means the circuit could still run events in 2000 at SMI 
properties in Atlanta, Dallas and Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheeler said SMI's long-term relationship with the circuit could  
depend on what changes, if any, the IRL makes in car design. 
Wheeler said SMI favors larger cars that are safer and more visible 
and identifiable to spectators. The company also would favor the 
IRL incorporating some sort of fender covers to its wheels, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRL, which has slowed its cars and made their wheel  
assemblies more durable since the Charlotte accident, is studying 
additional changes for 2000 but is not yet ready to commit to any. 
</P>
<P>
	``League officials, with the cooperation of car designers, are  
doing everything to address safety issues even as we move forward 
with the year 2000 car design,'' Green said. ``They're trying to do 
this yet still maintain the league's open-wheel heritage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A three-car accident early in the VisionAire 500 on May 1 at  
Charlotte sent a wheel assembly and suspension parts rocketing over 
a catch fence and into the fourth-turn grandstands. Three 
spectators were killed instantly and eight were injured. 
</P>
<P>
	They were the first spectator fatalities in the history of the  
speedway, which opened in 1960 and has long been considered the 
home track by most NASCAR Winston Cup drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	``What happened here was extremely traumatic for everybody  
involved,'' Wheeler said. ``We have to live with this every day. 
It's a situation where you tell yourself in the back of your head 
that this could happen, but you're also saying it probably won't 
while you're alive. But it did. 
</P>
<P>
	``So you've got to think about everything you can do to keep  
that from happening again. So certainly that tramautic event has 
had a very, very negative effect on my personal feelings about this 
whole thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even before the accident, there were signs the IRL was having  
troubles in Charlotte. The inaugural race in 1997 drew more than 
70,000, but that number dropped to about 50,000 in 1998 and to less 
than 40,000 for this year's race, which was canceled after the 
crash. 
</P>
<P>
	``The public votes every time you have an event on whether they  
like it or not,'' Wheeler said. ``And when they don't come, they're 
voting that what you're presenting to them, they don't like, never 
will like or maybe would like if you changed some things. And I 
think that's where the answer is. I think some strong changes need 
to be made.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 19:31:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Jags' Coach Focuses on Mental Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- No sunglasses. No kneeling. No sitting  
on your helmet. All those rules are passe compared to the newest 
directive at Camp Coughlin 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	No laterals.  
</P>
<P>
	Any player who laterals the ball during Jaguars training camp  
will be fined. It's one way coach Tom Coughlin is trying to send 
the message that mental mistakes, like the one that crippled 
Jacksonville in its playoff game at New York last season, will not 
be tolerated. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's going to be more attention to detail at this camp than  
ever before,'' Coughlin said. ``More attention paid to assignments, 
assignment errors, penalties, that sort of thing. As far as 
pressure for people to perform well, we will never let up from a 
mental standpoint.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While offsides penalties and missed assignments can slowly chip  
away at a team's effectiveness, the kind of mistake the Jaguars 
made in last year's 34-24 playoff loss to the Jets can end a 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Midway through the second quarter, safety Chris Hudson, who is  
no longer with the team, intercepted and returned the ball into 
Jets territory. 
</P>
<P>
	Inexplicably, he tried to lateral to a teammate. The ball  
bounded around and was recovered by the Jets. New York stayed on 
offense, drove for a touchdown and controlled the ball for more 
than 14 minutes of that decisive second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mental errors are one reason we haven't been able to get to  
the next level,'' Coughlin said. ``More players are aware of that. 
They have to work among themselves and put peer pressure on people 
in order to not be a mistake or error guy. The more that happens, 
the better off we're going to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By moving some of the focus to the mental side, several players  
have noticed a subtle downshift in the amount of physical toil they 
endure in Coughlin's camp, once known as the toughest in the 
league. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, the team won't practice in full pads until next  
Monday, letting four practices go by in shells and shorts. Coughlin 
isn't as stringent about a rules list that bordered on ridiculous 
five years ago, when discipline was the best way to find out who 
could play for his first-year expansion team. 
</P>
<P>
	And Coughlin hasn't totally dismissed shortening some practices  
if the temperatures, which have been in the high 90s for two weeks, 
don't let up. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's real surprising,'' said cornerback Dave Thomas, who has  
been present for all five Jaguars camps. ``The first year we 
started, we're in Wisconsin, it's 103 degrees out and we're in full 
pads every day. I'd say there's a big contrast from then to now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quarterback Mark Brunell says he's noticed a difference, too.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if easy is the word,'' Brunell said. ``But I'd  
say we're being smart the first two days. We're not going to go 
right out there and kill ourselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Any slackening on the field is being made up for in the meeting  
rooms. Coughlin said the Jaguars faced too many 2nd-and-12 
situations last year for a team with 11 victories. He wants to 
eliminate the illegal procedure penalties that cause them. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the defense has to learn a new system with new  
terminology under coordinator Dom Capers. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, Coughlin wants to give the players plenty to work on.  
And he doesn't think the new structure will diminish his reputation 
as a drill sergeant. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a gentler Tom,'' Coughlin said. ``I don't know who  
came up with that one. We've just adjusted accordingly. The mental 
part of camp will be just as tough as any camp, just as demanding 
as any camp we've had.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 19:31:01 </DATE_TIME>
