<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giants' Snow Signs for 4 Years, $24M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- First baseman J.T. Snow agreed to a $24  
million, four-year contract extension Friday as the San Francisco 
Giants locked up the middle of their batting order into the next 
century. 
</P>
<P>
	In an unusual move, the Giants also exercised options on Barry  
Bonds and Jeff Kent, extending their contracts for one more year. 
Bonds now is under contract through 2001 and Kent through 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's important for us not only to satisfy the players but also  
to show the Bay area and our fans that we're serious about our 
future, too,'' general manager Brian Sabean said. ``While we're 
focused on winning now, it was the right timing to do something 
like this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The moves came one week after the Giants traded two minor league  
pitchers to Florida for starter Livan Hernandez to improve their 
chances of making the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Snow, 31, could have been a free agent after this season. The  
four-time Gold Glove winner makes $3 million this season, the 
option year of a deal he agreed to in March 1996. His new contract 
also includes an option for a fifth year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sabean said an agreement was reached with less than 24 hours of  
negotiation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to give the Giants credit. They handled this  
professionally,'' Snow told reporters before a game against the 
Cincinnati Reds. ``They didn't take any cheap shots through the 
media.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds' option pays him $10.3 million in 2001. Kent's option pays  
him $6 million in 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	It's unusual for a team to exercise a contract option so far in  
advance because an injury could diminish the player's value. 
</P>
<P>
	``It really is out of character in baseball,'' Sabean said.  
``It's a great leap of faith. You usually don't do those things 
unless you're up against them. 
</P>
<P>
	``While it is a vote of confidence, it is the right investment  
because you're talking about special people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Snow leads NL first basemen with a .997 fielding percentage and  
84 assists, committing only three errors in 874 chances. He leads 
the Giants this season with 68 RBIs and 57 walks. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds, 35, was recently selected player of the decade by The  
Sporting News. He's an eight-time All-Star, has seven Gold Gloves 
and is one of only eight players to have won three Most Valuable 
Player awards. He's the only player in history to have 400 home 
runs and 400 steals. 
</P>
<P>
	Kent currently is batting .291 with 13 home runs, 63 RBI and 12  
stolen bases. 
</P>
<P>
	Sabean is still looking at improving his pitching staff, but  
said the chances he'll make another deal are ``20 percent or 
less.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
