<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Move Higher / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybeans futures prices opened higher  
today on the Chicago Board of Trade, mirroring Thursday's strong 
showing. 
</P>
<P>
	Grains were higher, following up from Thursday, as well as  
concerns over the continued heat wave across the Midwest. The heat, 
reaching the high 90s and triple digits in key growing states, 
could bake parched crops and reduce yields. 
</P>
<P>
	While brutal weather was forecast today for most of the Midwest,  
and the rest of the country for that matter, market participants 
say much of that news has already been factored in. 
</P>
<P>
	Gains were also limited by favorable weather forecasts for  
Midwestern growing states for this weekend and next week. 
Forecasters are calling for rain and cooler temperatures throughout 
the region. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's advances in corn and soybean prices ended days of  
sharp declines. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 3 1/2 cents to $2.77 a bushel;  
December corn rose 2 1/4 cents to $2.13 1/2 a bushel; December oats rose 
3/4 cent to $1.17 1/4 a bushel; November soybeans rose 2 1/2 cents to $4.36 
a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef and pork futures were mixed today on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle fell .10 cent to 64.22 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .05 cent to 76.65 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs rose .15 cents to 47.75 cents a pound; August pork bellies 
fell .07 cent to 49.05 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
