<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stations Said To Rent Donor Lists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The chairman of a House telecommunications  
panel said Friday that several public broadcasting stations rented 
donor lists from the Clinton-Gore election campaign, violating a 
law that prohibits nonprofit groups from participating in political 
activities. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., head of the House Commerce Committee's  
subcommittee on telecommunications, released a list he said he had 
obtained from the Corporation for Public Broadcasting of stations 
that responded to a survey on donor list-swapping. 
</P>
<P>
	At least three stations -- WCNY in central New York State, WBGU  
in Bowling Green, Ohio, and WCET in Cincinnati -- got the lists from 
a commercial list broker, the survey said. Other stations also 
acquired the lists, but the survey left their source unclear. 
</P>
<P>
	The practice ``shakes the foundation of public broadcasting and  
undermines the integrity of PBS,'' said Tauzin spokesman Ken 
Johnson, adding that it also ``raises serious questions about PBS' 
objectivity and fairness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A counsel for Clinton-Gore did not return telephone calls  
seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Epstein, a PBS vice president, said public television  
stations that exchanged or rented lists did so with both political 
parties in accordance with their non-profit tax status. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Dole '96 campaign, for instance, did business with several  
public television stations,'' he said. ``IRS regulations indicate 
that if lists were available to all political parties, there would 
be no violation of the law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tauzin, who supports public broadcasting, is considering  
legislation that would reduce federal funding to those stations in 
response to reports that they swapped donor lists with political 
parties. Nonprofit groups are prohibited from engaging in political 
activities. 
</P>
<P>
	The CPB, which distributes federal funding to public  
broadcasters, issued rules Friday that would withhold grants from 
stations that do not take specific steps to ensure the privacy of 
their donors. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new guidelines, stations seeking grants must inform  
their members periodically that lists containing their names might 
be sold, rented or exchanged and offer members a way to ask that 
their names not be released. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many people will see this as an unprecedented step, and sadly,  
they will be right,'' CPB President and CEO Robert T. Coonrod said 
in a statement. ``Our goal is to restore the public's trust in the 
work public broadcasting does every day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, PBS disclosed that at least two dozen public  
television stations exchanged membership lists with political 
groups. Some Republican lawmakers responded by renewing calls to 
strip public broadcasting of its $250 million government subsidy. 
</P>
<P>
	Stu Kantor, PBS director of corporate communications, called the  
new guidelines ``a vital and much-needed positive step to restore 
the trust relationship that public television and public radio have 
relied upon with the American people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tauzin's list was first reported by The Washington Times.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
