<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Limits `Three Strikes' Reach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The California Supreme Court has limited  
the reach of the ``three strikes'' sentencing law, ruling that a 
residential burglary conviction in juvenile court cannot be counted 
as a strike. 
</P>
<P>
	By a unanimous vote Thursday, the court threw out an eight-year  
prison term for Edwin Garcia of San Diego, whose sentence was 
doubled under the three-strikes law because he had a juvenile court 
burglary conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	His lawyer, Gary Nichols, said the ruling could affect  
``potentially thousands of cases throughout the state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia has already served more than four years in prison.  
Nichols said he will immediately seek Garcia's release, and that 
his office would challenge the sentences of dozens of other people 
as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Burglary is one of the most common juvenile offenses. Minors  
account for 40 percent of all burglaries, according to FBI 
statistics. 
</P>
<P>
	The court appears to be backing off its previous strict  
interpretation of the law, said Frank Zimring, a criminal law 
professor at Berkeley's Boalt Hall School of Law. ``I think they're 
more comfortable in the current political culture, so they don't 
have to look over their shoulder,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The three strikes law was signed by Gov. Pete Wilson in 1994  
amid outrage over the murder of Polly Klaas in Petaluma. 
</P>
<P>
	Only adults can be prosecuted under the law. A defendant with  
two prior convictions for a serious or violent felony can receive 
25 years to life if convicted of any third felony. A felon with one 
prior can receive double the normal sentence. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
