<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spacecraft Camera Misses Asteroid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- NASA scientists sounded philosophical after a  
camera flub on the Deep Space 1 probe left them with no images of 
its brush with an asteroid. 
</P>
<P>
	After all, they said, the spacecraft's use of 12 new  
technologies to forge more than 117 million miles from Earth was no 
small feat. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no secret we wanted to get neat pictures,'' deputy  
mission manager Marc Rayman said on Thursday. ``But it's a very 
small disappointment at the end of a very successful and important 
mission.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The probe is estimated to have flown within 10 miles of the  
Asteroid Braille late Wednesday, the closest flyby ever of an 
asteroid. But pictures it sent back from the encounter show only 
empty space, said Robert Nelson, a mission scientist at NASA's Jet 
Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	The barrel-shaped, 8-foot spacecraft, launched in October and  
designed primarily to test new forms of technology for future 
deep-space flights, otherwise accomplished all of the objectives of 
the $152 million mission, NASA said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This whole asteroid encounter was pure bonus,'' Rayman said.  
</P>
<P>
	One of the technologies, the Autonomous Navigation system, lost  
the target asteroid about 20 minutes before the 35,000-mph 
encounter. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on data that was still arriving from the spacecraft  
Thursday, scientists believe the probe's camera missed the pass. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just haven't gotten enough data down yet to determine where  
the broken link is,'' Rayman said. ``AutoNav had already 
successfully guided the spacecraft for many, many months and worked 
extremely well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the other technologies aboard is an ion propulsion engine  
that moves the spacecraft by sending out a stream of high-speed 
particles. 
</P>
<P>
	The engines are considered preferable for future spacecraft  
because they deliver 10 times more thrust than a conventional 
engine for a given amount of fuel, allowing spacecraft to be 
smaller, lighter and less expensive. 
</P>
<P>
	An instrument that analyzes ions appeared to operate normally  
during the flyby, and its data could help researchers figure out 
the rock's composition, the scientists said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the lack of images is disappointing to scientists given  
how little is known about the thousands of asteroids that 
irregularly orbit the sun, sometimes colliding with planets. An 
asteroid impact on Earth 65 million years ago is believed to be 
responsible for the extinction of the dinosaurs. 
</P>
<P>
	Deep Space 1 will remain functional when its prime mission  
officially ends Sept. 18, but could fly by two comets in 2001 if an 
extended mission is funded. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
