<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aviators' Quest Locates 1948 Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- For years, Marc Millican and Kevin  
McGregor have been fascinated with Northwest Airlines Flight 4422, 
which long ago plowed into a mountain peak, killing all 30 aboard. 
</P>
<P>
	The two pilots made it to the wreckage of the 1948 disaster on  
Saturday, reaching debris nestled in a remote valley buttressed by 
avalanche-prone walls and tucked under a glacier about 200 miles 
east of Anchorage. 
</P>
<P>
	They found not only bits of the flight's twisted propeller and  
shredded fuselage but human remains long preserved by ice and snow. 
</P>
<P>
	Alaska state troopers on Wednesday retrieved a human arm and  
hand from the wreckage, which Millican and McGregor found scattered 
about 10 miles inside Wrangell-St. Elias National Park and 
Preserve. The hand may be in good enough condition to be 
fingerprinted, said patrol spokesman Greg Wilkinson. 
</P>
<P>
	The wreckage for years had been too remote to reach safely. But  
a glacier has since pulled it down from its original 8,000-foot 
resting place on Mount Sanford, and it can be hiked to. 
</P>
<P>
	The DC-4 is believed to have collided with a near-vertical wall  
along the mountain's 16,237-foot peak on March 12, 1948. 
</P>
<P>
	The crash killed six crew members and 24 passengers, most of  
whom were members of the U.S. Merchant Marines who were returning 
from delivering a cargo ship to Shanghai. The flight was bound for 
Edmonton, Canada, and New York City. 
</P>
<P>
	More than the disaster's location has sat unresolved. Aviators  
still don't completely understand why a flight piloted by two 
veteran Alaska fliers airborne for just an hour would crash into a 
mountain in good weather, having sounded no distress report. 
</P>
<P>
	Only the aurora borealis has been blamed; it was shining that  
night like ``the headlights of a car,'' a pilot who searched for 
the ill-fated flight told McGregor. Perhaps the pilots were blinded 
by the northern lights reflecting off a thin cloud layer atop Mount 
Sanford, investigators said at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	A few years ago, McGregor and Millican, both commercial pilots,  
began probing the debris' location after discovering their mutual 
interest in the disaster while attending an Air Force reunion. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we got more and more into it, I got more and more  
intrigued,'' Millican said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prior expeditions, some lured by rumors of gold aboard, had  
declared the wreckage too dangerous to approach. The pair located 
it only after repeatedly flying and hiking through the area. 
</P>
<P>
	``We took literally thousands of pictures, but we never saw  
it,'' Millican said. 
</P>
<P>
	The longtime friends said they discovered the wreckage in 1997  
but waited to inspect it until receiving government clearance and 
unanimous consent from victims' families. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a reopening,'' said Dorothy Denman of Anchorage, whose  
uncle, August Koistinen, was a passenger. ``I've been crying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Millican, 42 and McGregor, 44, have been deliberately vague  
about the debris' location to safeguard it from the curious. They 
say they hope some wreckage they brought back -- a twisted table 
knife with the old Northwest logo, an engine plate, a scrap of 
aluminum -- can be displayed in a museum, or used in a memorial to 
the crash victims. 
</P>
<P>
	National Park Service officials have declared the area closed  
for two months while they decide how to handle any other visiting 
requests. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want treasure hunters in there out of respect for the  
families,'' said Jane Tranel, a National Park Service spokeswoman. 
``We consider it a burial site -- a resting place for those souls on 
board.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
