<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Firm To Pay $28M in Ageism Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An insurance brokerage and employee benefits  
firm will pay $28 million to settle a lawsuit that alleged it 
practiced age discrimination by requiring members of its board of 
directors to retire at age 62. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission announced the  
consent judgment Thursday, saying Johnson and Higgins Inc. would 
make the payout to settle a 1993 lawsuit filed by the federal 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson and Higgins, which had 7,000 workers nationwide,  
allegedly enforced a mandatory retirement policy before it was 
acquired by Marsh &AMP; McLennan Companies Inc. two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Barbara Perlmutter, vice president of public affairs for Marsh &AMP;  
McLennan, said the company was ``pleased to have this matter behind 
us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It related to the policy of a privately owned firm that we  
acquired in 1997,'' she said. Ms. Perlmutter added that there was 
no such policy at Marsh &AMP; McLennan, which employs 50,000 people in 
more than 100 countries worldwide in insurance services, investment 
management and consulting. 
</P>
<P>
	The EEOC had accused Johnson and Higgins of requiring its  
directors to retire at the end of the year in which they turned 62 
or at the end of the year in which they reached age 60 with 15 
years completed on the board. 
</P>
<P>
	``This case demonstrates that companies cannot arbitrarily  
impose age-based requirements for employees even if they place them 
on their board,'' said James Lee, the EEOC's New York District 
regional attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	A consent judgment filed in U.S. District Court in Manhattan  
said the $28 million settlement resulted from extensive 
negotiations. The deal also required the company to pay the EEOC 
$100,000 for the costs of the lawsuit. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
