<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. Football Fans Still Have Hope </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Prospective NFL owner Ed Roski Jr. insisted  
there is no public money available to sweeten a deal to bring an 
expansion NFL franchise to Los Angeles, but he was hopeful that a 
compromise could be reached. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes the deal tougher, but not impossible,'' Roski said,  
The Orange County Register reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	During a meeting Wednesday in Chicago, NFL owners did not commit  
to a proposal submitted by Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL has remained tight-lipped about whether the city will be  
a pro football town again. City officials are optimistic, but some 
aren't sure if they can satisfy the league's demands. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL is seeking more public contributions instead of settling  
for $150 million in bonds proposed by Bill Chadwick, chosen by Gov. 
Gray Davis to negotiate with the league to return a team to Los 
Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL also said there would be no set franchise fee and that  
it would take bids from the two Los Angeles groups vying for 
ownership. Those groups joined forces on a stadium proposal after 
the NFL said it wanted the team to play at the Coliseum, but 
ownership is still up for grabs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really don't think there's any public money available,''  
Roski said. ``It's hard to imagine that the state or someone else 
would give money to help build a football stadium.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chadwick was confident going into the meeting that the owners  
would sign off on the stadium proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know whether what the NFL wants is possible,''  
Chadwick said Thursday. ``I'm not sure how to feel, but I'm not 
quitting. ... I learned quite a bit while I was in Chicago. Based 
on what I learned, I have to re-evaluate the possibilities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Fabiani, adviser to an investor group led by Hollywood  
agent Michael Ovitz, said Thursday that they would continue to work 
to reach an agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have worked very hard to make it happen for almost four  
years. We are not giving up,'' Fabiani said. 
</P>
<P>
	If Los Angeles doesn't come up with a proposal that satisfies  
the owners by Sept. 15, the NFL will likely turn to Houston, which 
has a plan largely embraced by the owners. Houston initially came 
in second to Los Angeles only because of its size. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am concerned that we have a lot to do in a relatively short  
amount of time,'' City Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas said. ``We 
can't afford to waste one day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue has said the September deadline  
won't be pushed back under any circumstances. 
</P>
<P>
	The two Los Angeles groups -- one led by Ovitz and billionaire  
Ron Burkle, the other by Broad and Roski -- presented a unified 
stadium plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``The issue now is how to pay for all of the improvements'' to  
the Coliseum and the area around Exposition Park, Fabiani said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Chicago, Chadwick presented league owners with plans to raise  
$150 million from bonds for 15,000 additional parking spaces. He 
also called on the NFL to contribute up to $150 million for 
development of the stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal also calls for the team owner to pay the state an  
annual rent of $5 million, subject to increases every five years. 
Many NFL teams play in rent-free stadiums. 
</P>
<P>
	Chadwick thought the NFL would sign off on his proposal before  
he left Chicago, but Tagliabue called it a work in progress. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need further negotiations. ... There are a number of  
economic issues that need to be improved in order for the team to 
be successful,'' Tagliabue said. 
</P>
<P>
	Broad has said it will take about $900 million to ensure a team  
for Los Angeles, including the stadium and franchise fee. He also 
believes a team would generate a profit of $25 million to $28 
million a year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
