<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pitchers Sought As Deadline Looms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Chuck Finley to the Indians? Kevin Appier to the Red Sox? Jesse  
Orosco back to the New York Mets? 
</P>
<P>
	Those possible deals, plus several others involving the New York  
Yankees, were shaping up as baseball approached its nonwaiver 
trading deadline at Saturday midnight EDT. 
</P>
<P>
	As usual, most teams were on the prowl for pitching.  
</P>
<P>
	Andy Pettitte of the Yankees, Rolando Arrojo and Roberto  
Hernandez of Tampa Bay, Brad Radke and Mike Trombley of Minnesota, 
Arthur Rhodes and Orosco of Baltimore and Darryl Kile of Colorado 
were said to be available. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would be shocked if we don't do something,'' Cleveland  
general manager John Hart said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland, looking at a potential playoff matchup with the  
Yankees, hoped to close a deal with Anaheim for Finley, 16-9 
lifetime against New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees also eyed Finley, along with Arrojo and Hernandez.  
Pettitte, who has struggled all season, seemed the most likely 
player to depart the World Series champions, with Houston, 
Philadelphia and Seattle interested. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had things presented to us, we've had offers made to  
us,'' Yankees general manager Brian Cashman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Certainly, the AL East-leading Yankees had enough prospects to  
swing a deal. Especially if it meant heading off the AL 
Central-leading Indians. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the Yankees, you do things short-term, anyway,'' manager  
Joe Torre said. ``You always want to win now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kansas City was fielding a lot of offers for Appier, its  
longtime ace. 
</P>
<P>
	``In all likelihood, we will make a trade before Saturday  
night,'' Royals general manager Herk Robinson said. ``I can't tell 
you who it's going to be with. It's whoever wants him the most, I 
guess.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A few deals have been made already.  
</P>
<P>
	In the last week, San Francisco got former World Series MVP  
Livan Hernandez from Florida, the Mets acquired Kenny Rogers from 
Oakland and Toronto got first baseman David Segui from Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	Late Thursday night, the Athletics tried to boost their  
wild-card chances by getting infielder Randy Velarde and pitcher 
Omar Olivares from Anaheim for three minor leaguers. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you compare apples to apples, just by numbers Omar was  
having a better year than Kenny,'' Oakland general manager Billy 
Beane said. ``Omar was on a wish list. We were trying to prepare 
ourselves for him in the week since we traded Kenny. We knew he was 
going to be moved, but we weren't sure when.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, there was a flurry of activity on July 31 with more  
than 10 trades. 
</P>
<P>
	In the big deal, the Astros acquired Randy Johnson from Seattle.  
The Big Unit helped pitch Houston into the playoffs, but went 0-2 -- 
despite a 1.93 ERA -- against San Diego in the division series. 
</P>
<P>
	Also last season, Texas got Todd Stottlemyre, Royce Clayton and  
Todd Zeile in separate trades with St. Louis and Florida, Los 
Angeles got Mark Grudzielanek and Carlos Perez, San Francisco got 
Ellis Burks and Baltimore got Juan Guzman. 
</P>
<P>
	Usually, these late deals are made for minor leaguers or young  
major leaguers. And while such trades may seem one-sided at the 
time, often they look a lot different a year later. Consider the 
Cardinals' acquisition of powerful Fernando Tatis, along with 
Darren Oliver, from Texas for Stottlemyre, now in Arizona, and 
Clayton. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting Sunday, trades can still be made. But from that point,  
players must pass through waivers, a tricky proposition at this 
time of year. With so many teams in contention, it's more and more 
unlikely a club would let a key player slip through to a rival. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Aug. 31, the last day a team can acquire a player and have  
him eligible for the postseason, San Diego got utilityman John 
Vander Wal from Colorado and Cleveland acquired infielder Joey Cora 
from Seattle for David Bell. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets were said to be looking at Orosco, the bullpen ace from  
their 1986 World Series team, and Rhodes. There was also a chance 
they might make a lesser move, perhaps trading someone like 
middleman Greg McMichael, to set a up a bigger deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Rhodes, a hard-throwing lefty, was receiving plenty of interest.  
Earlier this week, he heard he might be going to Cleveland. On 
Thursday, he talked with Orioles owner Peter Angelos. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told him I'd love to stay in Baltimore,'' Rhodes said. ``He  
said he'd love to keep me, too.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
