<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  U.S. Women Top Argentina in Hoops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Only the outcome brought any  
satisfaction for the U.S. women's basketball team in its Pan 
American Games opener. 
</P>
<P>
	In a game long on effort but short on style, reserves Amy Herrig  
and Michelle Marciniak gave Team USA the lift it needed to get past 
Argentina 63-55 Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just OK,'' said Marciniak, a former Tennessee standout.  
``It was by no means acceptable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The young Americans, most of whom have little international  
experience, shot only 39 percent and committed 24 turnovers. They 
trailed by a point at halftime and led by only three midway through 
the second half before finally grinding down the Argentines. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just not playing good basketball right now,'' said coach  
Nell Fortner, who had just 13 days to get her team ready and 
substituted constantly trying to find the right combination. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to start executing better, we've got to play smarter  
defense,'' she said. ``I think we will, but we've got to start 
doing it soon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Herrig made 11 of 12 free throws while scoring 15 points and  
grabbing nine rebounds. Marciniak scored 13 points and made her 
presence felt early. Entering the game at 15:46 of the first half, 
Marciniak twice grabbed a rebound and drove the length of the court 
for baskets to inject some life into a struggling offense. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a lot of pent-up energy,'' Marciniak said. ``I get  
really anxious sitting on the bench, so when I get in there, I want 
to make something happen. Sometimes it's good, sometimes it's 
bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Far more satisfied with their effort were the American men in  
water polo. By beating Cuba 11-7, they earned the only available 
berth in the 2000 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Humbert of Lodi, Calif., scored five goals.  
</P>
<P>
	Canada beat the U.S. women 8-6 for the gold medal, building a  
3-0 lead and holding on. It was the third straight loss to Canada 
for the Americans. Waneek Horn-Miller scored a hat trick for the 
hosts. 
</P>
<P>
	Michele Smith had a perfect game into the seventh inning for the  
U.S. women's softball team. But she couldn't match teammate 
Danielle Henderson's perfecto of Thursday, yielding a hit to the 
Netherlands Antilles in a 5-0 win. 
</P>
<P>
	Things were bad at the track, on the hockey field and on the  
volleyball court for the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	No American won on the final night of track and field, while  
Cubans took five of the 10 events. High jumper Javier Sotomayor won 
his fourth Pan Ams gold. 
</P>
<P>
	``Spectacular ... fantastic,'' Sotomayor said. ``This is  
great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not so great were U.S. relay teams, which were blanked. Jamaica  
had the year's fastest time in the men's 1,600 and women's 400 
relays. 
</P>
<P>
	When Argentina's men beat the United States 4-1 in field hockey,  
it ended any chances of the Americans qualifying for the Olympics. 
And there'll be no medal for the men's volleyball team, which was 
knocked out when it lost to Venezuela 25-21, 28-26, 25-22. The U.S. 
women could win a bronze, but their shot at gold ended with a 
three-set sweep by Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	Things went better in the ring on the opening night of boxing.  
</P>
<P>
	Flyweight Jose Navarro of Los Angeles started off with a 14-4  
decision over Carlos Valcarcel of Puerto Rico in the new format of 
four two-minute rounds. Welterweight LeChaunce Shepherd of 
Milwaukee, Wis., dominated Isaac Caballero of Nicaragua, stopping 
him in the first round. Caballero received three standing-8 counts 
to end the bout. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first bout is always the hardest,'' Shepherd said. ``I was  
a little anxious.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Americans did win the premier rowing event, the men's eight with  
cox. The U.S. team took control at 500 meters and won by nearly 
three seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	``We made a big move about three minutes into the race and that  
sealed it,'' said Nick Anderson of Omaha, Neb. 
</P>
<P>
	An official from the International Baseball Association told  
several reporters that two Cuban baseball players had defected. But 
Canadian immigration officials and sources close to the Cuban team 
said the official was wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball continues Saturday with the quarterfinals. The United  
States plays Panama and needs to win that game and its semifinal 
match to secure a berth in the 2000 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	The other baseball quarterfinals are Canada vs. Guatemala, Cuba  
vs. the Dominican Republic, and Nigaragua vs. Mexico. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 15:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Firm Won't Appeal Paula Jones Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The lead law firm for Paula Jones said  
Friday it will not appeal a federal judge's order awarding it 
$79,999 from President Clinton for costs incurred because of his 
false testimony about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision by the Dallas-based firm of Rader, Campbell, Fisher  
&AMP; Pyke all but wraps up Mrs. Jones' dispute with Clinton, who has 
said he is willing to comply with the court order issued Thursday 
by U.S. District Judge Susan Webber Wright. 
</P>
<P>
	``We thought that more attorneys fees were caused by his lying,  
but Judge Wright didn't see it that way and so it's over,'' said 
lawyer Wes Holmes of the Dallas firm. ``There's really nothing to 
appeal. It was totally discretionary by her. She made a decision, 
and we're going to live with that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The head of The Rutherford Institute, a Virginia-based  
conservative group that also worked for Mrs. Jones, said he likely 
would decide next week whether to appeal the institute's $9,485 
award, but would prefer to let the case end. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're weighing the money, the attorney time, the chance factor  
with the court and then probably as big of a factor: Do we want to 
be in this case for another year?'' said Rutherford President John 
W. Whitehead. ``We all want this to end if we can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas firm had sought $437,825 and The Rutherford Institute  
had sought $58,533 -- about six times what it received. 
</P>
<P>
	Legal experts who have tracked Mrs. Jones' sexual harassment  
suit said her attorneys would be wise not to appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	``They run the risk of losing it all, and there's very little  
chance of increasing their take,'' said Georgetown University law 
professor Paul Rothstein. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's attorneys have said the president will not appeal the  
$90,686 payment ordered to compensate for legal costs related to 
what the judge called his ``false, misleading and evasive answers'' 
in his January 1998 deposition. 
</P>
<P>
	But if The Rutherford Institute appealed, Clinton's lawyers  
could raise broad objections. For example, legal experts said 
Clinton could argue that Wright should not have determined the 
contempt award because her office is also being compensated for 
costs -- $1,202 to cover her trip to Washington to preside over 
Clinton's deposition. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's denials of a sexual relationship with Ms. Lewinsky led  
to his impeachment by the House. The Senate acquitted him after a 
trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright dismissed Mrs. Jones' lawsuit April 1, 1998, but Clinton  
agreed to an $850,000 settlement after Mrs. Jones appealed the 
dismissal. Clinton admitted no wrongdoing. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 02:00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBC Overhauling Shows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- NBC is putting more ethnic diversity in  
its new and returning series, partly in response to criticism of 
the major broadcast networks for a nearly all-white slate of new 
fall shows. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be totally disingenuous to stand up here and say we  
did this totally on our own,'' NBC West Coast President Scott Sassa 
said Thursday, acknowledging the effect of complaints from the 
NAACP and others. 
</P>
<P>
	The network said it is working with actor-writer Keenen Ivory  
Wayans and producer Yvette Lee Bowser (``Living Single'') to 
develop a pair of sitcoms that will feature black characters. 
</P>
<P>
	Wayans' show was described as ``Not the Bradys,'' featuring an  
interracial marriage and the resulting merged family. 
</P>
<P>
	Several planned cast additions involve minority actors: Sherri  
Shepherd on ``Suddenly Susan''; Jesse L. Martin on ``Law &AMP; Order'' 
and Michelle Hurd on its spinoff, ``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims 
Unit''; Darryl Theirse on ``Jesse'' and Michael Michele and Ming-Na 
Wen on ``ER.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Michele (``Homicide: Life on the Street'') will play a  
second-year resident, while Ms. Wen is reprising her role from the 
medical drama's first season as Dr. Deb Chen. Joining them will be 
Maura Tierney (``NewsRadio'') and Goran Visnjic. 
</P>
<P>
	Alan Alda (``M-A-S-H'') and Rebecca DeMornay (``Risky  
Business'') will guest star in several ``ER'' episodes, while 
recurring character Dr. Romano (Paul McCrane) is now a regular. The 
series returns Thursday, Sept. 30. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC, more vulnerable since losing ``Seinfeld,'' also is  
overhauling shows to improve ratings and try to maintain its 
top-ranked position. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with Ms. Shepherd, ``Suddenly Susan'' will add Eric Idle  
(``Monty Python''), Rob Estes (``Melrose Place'') and Currie Graham 
as the magazine the characters work for becomes a sports 
publication. 
</P>
<P>
	``Veronica's Closet'' is losing Ron Silver and bringing aboard a  
new adversary for Veronica (Kirstie Alley): Silver's young widow. 
The series, which has failed to capitalize on its stellar Thursday 
slot behind ``ER,'' is moving to Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Both ``Veronica's Closet'' and ``Jesse'' are getting new  
producers. The latter also is adding Kevin Rahhm (``Everything's 
Relative'') as a cast member. 
</P>
<P>
	``West Wing,'' a new series set in the White House and  
criticized as having an unrealistically all-white cast, will add a 
black actor in a recurring role, said NBC Entertainment President 
Garth Ancier. 
</P>
<P>
	Sassa said the network ``should have done a better job'' in  
creating racially diverse shows. Diversity is good business for the 
network, he said, because NBC-owned stations in big cities draw 
more ethnic viewers. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC's new schedule will debut the week of Sept. 20.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0035 </DOCNO>
