<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stock, Futures To Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Hong Kong's stock exchange and futures exchange  
have agreed to a merger plan, a cornerstone of the government's 
market reform program. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stock Exchange of Hong Kong will hold 70 percent of the  
merged entity, while the Hong Kong Futures Exchange will own 30 
percent, acting Financial Secretary Rafael Hui said. 
</P>
<P>
	A feud over how much each exchange would own had threatened the  
plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Shareholders will vote on the deal in September, while  
legislation will be taken up in the legislature by year's end, 
paving the way for completion of the merger in early 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Hui said he expected shareholders to pass the plan, but the  
government would pursue merger and reform through ``other means'' 
if they voted it down. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Asian financial crisis dealt a severe blow to Hong  
Kong's financial markets and exposed some of their noncompetitive 
problems last year, Financial Secretary Donald Tsang announced in 
March that the two exchanges and several associated entities would 
merge to create a more open market. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 15:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Fall for a Second Day / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices fell for a second session Friday  
after a key report revealed that inflationary pressures intensified 
in the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond dropped 13/32  
point, or $4.06 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, a key 
influence on borrowing costs, rose to 6.10 percent from late 
Thursday's 6.07 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
fell by 1/32 point to 3/32 point, while intermediate-term Treasurys 
fell by 3/32 point to 7/32 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a 
financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices plunged Thursday after the Labor Department reported  
that employment costs -- which typically account for two-thirds of a 
product's price -- rose 1.1 percent from April through June. That 
was the biggest quarterly change since the second-quarter of 1991, 
when wages and benefits increased 1.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The data convinced many investors that the Federal Reserve will  
push its key lending rates higher again to slow the economy -- 
possibly weakening the job market so that workers would have less 
leverage with their employers. Rising inflation and interest rates 
make the fixed payoff on bonds less appealing. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills rose 4.74 percent while the  
discount rate rose to 4.62 percent, an increase of 0.03 percentage 
point on both. 
</P>
<P>
	Six-month yields rose to 4.83 percent and the discount to 4.65  
percent, up 0.01 percentage point. One-year yields rose to 5.09 
percent as the discount increased to 4.84 percent, up 0.01 
percentage point. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, was unchanged from late Thursday's 5.13 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 1/4 point to 117 24/32. The average yield 
to maturity rose to 5.59 percent, up from 5.58 percent on Thursday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
