<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> American, Brit Airways Try New Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Transportation Department is dismissing a  
3-year-old application by American Airlines and British Airways for 
special government permission to form an alliance. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.S. government official said the department would make the  
dismissal today because British Airways had reached a stalemate 
with the United Kingdom's Office of Fair Trade over surrendering 
landing and takeoff slots at London's popular Heathrow Airport. 
</P>
<P>
	British Airways long has fought to retain its hundreds of  
takeoff or landing spots at the airport, contending it would suffer 
as a result of increased competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has been a lack of progress on the underlying issues and  
it is in the best interests of all that the petition be dismissed 
without prejudice,'' a Transportation Department official said, 
speaking on the condition of anonymity. ``This will allow the 
airlines to resubmit the petition should progress be made.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In anticipation of the announcement, the two airlines issued a  
joint statement Thursday saying they planned to expand their 
existing marketing relationship in ways that would not require 
government approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Don Carty, chairman of American Airlines, said: ``While our  
alliance may now evolve somewhat differently than originally 
proposed, it will still be a beneficial one for our customers, 
shareholders and employees.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The collapse of the quasi-merger should not affect passengers.  
For example, the airlines' existing exchange of some frequent-flier 
benefits through their ``oneworld'' marketing partnership is not 
expected to dissolve. The airlines and their shareholders, though, 
may be upset at the missed chance to operate more efficiently under 
an alliance. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are real advantages to (a formal alliance), but the fact  
they you do not have it is not a deal-breaker,'' said Darryl 
Jenkins, an airline specialist and head of the Institute of Tourism 
Studies at George Washington University. 
</P>
<P>
	The two carriers had applied to the Transportation Department  
for antitrust immunity. It would have allowed them to discuss 
pricing and seat inventory, and let them share revenues from 
passenger and cargo service. Such cooperation is prohibited without 
a waiver. 
</P>
<P>
	Virgin Atlantic Airways, a British carrier, and various U.S.  
airlines contended the alliance would give two huge airlines a 
stranglehold on transatlantic travel -- especially into Heathrow 
Airport. It is a gateway to Europe, Africa and the Middle East and 
is frequented by high-paying business travelers. 
</P>
<P>
	Access to Heathrow also has been a sticking point in  
U.S.-British negotiations over a new aviation agreement. The 
current treaty allows only two U.S. carriers -- now American and 
United Airlines -- access to Heathrow. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials want more access for other carriers with the aim  
of reducing airfares. The United States already has 30 such ``open 
skies'' agreements around the world. British officials have balked; 
they have sought, in exchange, a drop in current prohibitions 
against foreigners owning U.S. airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Transportation Department has firmly stated that it  
would not approve the airline alliance without the concession of 
better access to Heathrow. Some U.S. airlines have accused the 
British government of protecting British Airways, a former state 
airline. 
</P>
<P>
	Jenkins said the dismissal of the application may simplify the  
issues in the aviation negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think what will happen is this will make it easier for the  
British government and U.S. government to reach an open skies 
agreement, and after that happens they both can reapply for 
antitrust immunity,'' he said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
