<HEADLINE> Packers' Freeman Becomes Holdout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- The Green Bay Packers welcomed their  
veteran players to training camp practices Friday, but were still 
without their key passing combination. 
</P>
<P>
	Wide receiver Antonio Freeman officially became a holdout and  
quarterback Brett Favre was with his wife and newborn daughter. 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman, an unrestricted free agent before the Packers  
designated him their franchise player, is still hammering out terms 
of a new contract with the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'd love for Antonio to be in camp,'' coach Ray Rhodes said.  
``But as we all know, when you're doing contracts, sometimes that 
stuff takes time. But I'm certain Antonio is working hard and 
preparing himself to come to training camp, and I hope it will be 
solved very shortly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Favre is expected to join the team Saturday. The veterans who  
did arrive were ready to go, Rhodes said. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the most part, the veterans are in good shape,'' Rhodes  
said. ``The guys are going to be a little rusty, but I saw some 
good things. I was very pleased with the way they reported.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rhodes said physical testing went well when the veterans arrived  
Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in the best shape we've been in for some time,'' he  
said. ``It will take a couple of days before we get the timing 
down.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
