<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 76ers Ready To Sign Snow, Lynch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Philadelphia 76ers are ready to sign two  
of their own free agents, Eric Snow and George Lynch, when the 
NBA's moratorium on trades and signings is lifted Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sixers planned a conference call for 1:30 p.m. EDT Sunday in  
which general manager Billy King is expected to announce the 
signings, a source close to the negotiations told The Associated 
Press Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The source, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said Snow  
and Lynch were expected to be on the conference call. A one-month 
ban on trades and free-agent signings ends Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Snow, who went from being the fourth guard in Seattle to the  
starting point guard in Philadelphia, is expected to get a 
seven-year deal worth about $29 million. During a recent summer 
camp, Snow said he turned down a better offer from the Toronto 
Raptors. 
</P>
<P>
	``On paper they were probably offering more,'' Snow said. ``But  
looking at where it is and the tax aspect, it probably didn't add 
up. ... It was an easy decision to stay.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Snow, who made $840,000 last season, will make about $3 million  
in the first year of the deal. He would fall under the so-called 
Larry Bird exception that allows for maximum raises of 12.5 percent 
a year for free agents resigning with their teams. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sixers plan to use their $2 million ``middle class''  
exception to sign Lynch, who made the five-year veteran's minimum 
of $537,500 last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Philadelphia, which made the playoffs for the first time since  
1991 last season, still has to decide whether to re-sign free 
agents Harvey Grant, Jerald Honeycutt, Rick Mahorn and Doug 
Overton. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sixers also are interested in several other free agents, but  
would have to do sign-and-trade deals to get them because they're 
already over the salary cap. Free agents who could be good fits for 
the Sixers include Rodney Rogers and Eric Piatkowski of the 
Clippers, Detlef Schrempf of Seattle and Sam Mack of Houston. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
