<HEADLINE> Veriato Leads Utah Showdown  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARK CITY, Utah (AP) -- Little-known Steve Veriato tamed the Park  
Meadows Golf Club with an 8-under-par 64 Friday to seize the 
first-round lead in the $1.35 million Senior PGA Tour Utah 
Showdown. 
</P>
<P>
	Veriato's first round was simply a continuation of his torrid  
play here. He qualified for a spot in the field with a 63 on 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Former winner Tom Shaw, long-hitting John Jacobs and Leonard  
Thompson shot 65s on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	At 6-under were Dave Eichelberger and Terry Dill, followed at 67  
by Alberto Giannone, Fred Gibson, Hale Irwin, Dave Stockton and 
Simon Hobday. Defending champion Gil Morgan was at 6-under on No. 
17 when rain halted play. 
</P>
<P>
	Veriato, whose best finish this year was 29th in the U.S. Senior  
Open, had three birdies on the front nine and five on the back in a 
bogey-free round. 
</P>
<P>
	``This course suits my game,'' Veriato said. ``But I think my  
talent has something to do with it. Everything seemed to gel today 
and I was very patient, especially at the start when I wasn't 
making anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All of Vertiao's birdie putts came within 15 feet. He was the  
first player off the tee and avoided a lightning delay early in the 
afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	``This course is in excellent shape and you can't help but make  
a few putts,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacobs shot a front-nine 31 and seemed poised to charge into the  
lead, only to have weather interfere. 
</P>
<P>
	``I came back out on the 13th hole and my tempo wasn't there,''  
Jacobs said. ``Of course, anything can happen here. A player can be 
behind five or six shots on Sunday and still make a run at it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After a bogey on the par-5 15th, Jacobs managed to pull his game  
together for the final three holes, making birdie putts of 30, 10 
and 6 feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaw, the 1989 Utah Showdown winner, had eight birdies and a  
lone bogey. 
</P>
<P>
	``The delay didn't bother me at all,'' Shaw said. ``I just  
picked up right where I left off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The threesome of Jack Nicklaus, Lee Trevino and Arnold Palmer  
drew a gallery of over 20,000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
