<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 16:50:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> State Dep't Denies Impeding Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department denied Friday that its  
officials impeded U.S. law enforcement agents from apprehending two 
suspects being held by Sudanese authorities in the 1998 U.S. 
embassy bombings. 
</P>
<P>
	According to MSNBC, which first reported the story, and The New  
York Times, Sudanese officials last Aug. 8 arrested two men who 
were believed linked to the bombings, which occurred the day before 
in Kenya and Tanzania. The bombings killed more than 250 people, 
including 12 Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times account said White House and State Department  
officials were adamantly opposed to reopening relations with Sudan 
because of its alleged terrorist links and ``this reticence 
prompted them last August to discount the Sudanese offer of 
assistance in the investigation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	MSNBC said the State Department ``refused to allow an FBI team  
to travel to the Sudanese capital to discuss apprehending the 
suspects.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Times said Sudan released the two suspects after American  
cruise missiles struck a pharmaceutical plant in Sudan two weeks 
after the bombing. The plant was suspected of involvement in the 
efforts of Osama bin Laden, a reputed Saudi exile terrorist, to 
produce the deadly nerve gas VX. The owner of the plant has denied 
it was involved in any effort to produce nerve gas. 
</P>
<P>
	David Leavy, a White House spokesman, said ``no one at the White  
House knows anything'' about the FBI being blocked by another 
government agency in its efforts to investigate. 
</P>
<P>
	At the State Department, spokesman Philip Reeker said the news  
accounts were ``fundamentally inaccurate'' and added that the State 
Department and the FBI have had a cooperative relationship on the 
issue all along. 
</P>
<P>
	Efforts to reach the Sudanese Embassy for comment were  
unsuccessful. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0048 </DOCNO>
