<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Leyritz May Go Back To Yankees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Jim Leyritz is on the verge of going back to  
the New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Leyritz, who's hit clutch postseason home runs for both the  
Yankees and the San Diego Padres, could be dealt from San Diego to 
New York by Saturday night's deadline, several people familiar with 
the talks said Friday night on the condition they not be 
identified. The Padres would probably get a prospect or two in 
return. 
</P>
<P>
	Padres general manager Kevin Towers would say only that trading  
Leyritz remained a possibility. Sources said Leyritz apparently 
asked the Padres to send him to New York, where he played from 
1990-96. 
</P>
<P>
	In a move that could be a precursor to a Leyritz trade and maybe  
a deal for a third baseman, the Padres activated Leyritz from the 
15-day disabled list Friday night and designated third baseman 
George Arias for assignment. 
</P>
<P>
	It's been known practically all season that the Padres would  
consider trading Leyritz, who loves the postseason spotlight, to a 
contender for prospects, and possibly re-signing him as a free 
agent after the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a very good possibility,'' Leyritz said before Friday  
night's game. ``Even if something does happen, I've got no 
bitterness. What they've done for me here is great. From a family 
standpoint I'd love to stay here, but I understand it's a 
business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leyritz has 12 career postseason hits, and seven are homers. He  
helped change the course of the 1996 World Series with a three-run 
shot off Atlanta's Mark Wohlers in Game 4. 
</P>
<P>
	Leyritz hit four homers in the playoffs last year, three against  
Houston in the division series and one against Atlanta as the 
Padres won the NL pennant. The Yankees swept the Padres in the 
World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	Leyritz broke a bone in his left hand at Los Angeles on June 23,  
clearing the way for the Padres to promote rookie Ben Davis, their 
top non-pitching prospect. Davis has been impressive not only with 
his defense, but brought a .324 average into Friday night's game. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time Leyritz was hurt, the Padres were in the midst of a  
14-game winning streak that got them back into contention. But 
after losing seven straight games, they went into Friday night's 
game seven games behind NL West leader Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	The Padres traded catcher Greg Myers to Atlanta on Monday for a  
minor league pitcher. 
</P>
<P>
	The Padres want to upgrade at third. Arias struggled in his  
second chance as a big league starter. He took over at third after 
Ken Caminiti returned to the Houston Astros as a free agent after 
last season. 
</P>
<P>
	He missed 24 of the first 27 games due to a thumb injury and  
struggled at the plate. He was batting .244 with seven homers and 
20 RBIs in 55 games. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
