<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Astronomer May Be Buried on Moon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Colleagues of a late researcher noted for his  
expertise on outer-space collisions came up with an astronomical 
way to honor his memory. 
</P>
<P>
	Assuming all goes to plan, a vial carrying an ounce of Eugene  
Shoemaker's ashes will slam into a moon crater at 3,800 mph early 
Saturday, riding shotgun along NASA's Lunar Prospector science 
craft. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is the very first human inhabitant of Earth to be laid to  
rest on another celestial body,'' said Carolyn Porco, a University 
of Arizona professor and Shoemaker's college on NASA's Voyager 
expeditions. ``That's very significant because it says we have 
arrived at our place in the solar system, the solar system is our 
own and it's beckoning us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was Ms. Porco who spearheaded the tribute effort and designed  
an epigraph that accompanies the ashes of Shoemaker, who died two 
years ago in a car crash while crater-hunting in Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	Credited along with his wife for the discovery of about 20  
comets and 800 asteroids, Shoemaker gained worldwide fame as a 
co-discoverer of comet Shoemaker-Levy 9 that slammed into Jupiter 
in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Lunar Prospector was expected to hit the moon at 5:52 a.m. EDT.  
</P>
<P>
	David Morse, spokesman for NASA's Ames Research Center, called  
the memorial ``a special honor for a special human being.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shoemaker, a geologist by training, applied to be an astronaut  
in the 1960s but was rejected because of a medical problem. He 
later worked on several U.S. space missions, including the Apollo 
missions to the moon. He taught Apollo astronauts about craters. 
</P>
<P>
	Shoemaker said shortly before his death the biggest  
disappointment in his life was ``not going to the moon and banging 
on it with my own hammer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Grown men have told me they've been moved to tears when they  
heard this story, of the man who wanted so badly to go to the 
moon,'' Ms. Porco said. ``Through no fault of his own he was taken 
out of the running. Thirty years later, he finally will get 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NASA officials expect the polycarbonate vial containing  
Shoemaker's remains to pulverize on impact with the wall of the 
crater. 
</P>
<P>
	``If all goes well, it may literally be buried,'' said Lisa  
Chu-Thielbar, Prospector outreach coordinator. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of Shoemaker's ashes may rise in a cloud of soil and,  
perhaps, water vapor -- the focus of the Lunar Prospector's 
swan-song experiment. NASA will use the Hubble Space Telescope to 
try to detect water from lunar ice in the plume created by 
Prospector's impact. 
</P>
<P>
	The cylindrical container that carries Shoemaker's remains was  
manufactured by Celestis Inc., a Houston company that has used 
commercial rockets to launch into space the cremated remains of 55 
people, including Star Trek creator Gene Roddenberry and 1960s drug 
guru Timothy Leary. 
</P>
<P>
	Shoemaker's wife, Carolyn, attended the launch of Prospector on  
Jan. 6, 1998, with her children and grandchildren. At the time, she 
said her husband would have been thrilled about having his ashes 
rest forever on the moon. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's going to be the man in the moon to us,'' Mrs. Shoemaker  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Porco's epigraph, a laser-etched piece of brass foil, is  
wrapped around the vial containing Shoemaker's remains. It depicts 
Meteor Crater near his home in Flagstaff, Ariz., and the Hale-Bopp 
comet. 
</P>
<P>
	It also has these lines from Shakespeare's Romeo and Juliet:  
</P>
<P>
	``And, when he shall die,  
</P>
<P>
	Take him and cut him out in little stars,  
</P>
<P>
	And he will make the face of heaven so fine  
</P>
<P>
	That all the world will be in love with night,  
</P>
<P>
	And pay no worship to the garish sun.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
