<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Says 9 Dead in Airstrikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- U.S. and British warplanes attacked several  
sites in northern and southern Iraq on Friday, killing nine people 
and wounding 23 others, the Iraqi armed forces said. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.S. military statement confirmed the strikes in the north,  
saying U.S. warplanes bombed Iraqi anti-aircraft artillery sites in 
response to anti-aircraft fire. There was no independent 
confirmation of the reported strikes in the south. 
</P>
<P>
	The official Iraqi News Agency quoted the Iraqi military as  
saying that 11 enemy formations carried out 24 sorties over the 
northern provinces of Dohuk, Irbil and Mosul, striking ``civil and 
service installations.'' It said six people were killed and 21 were 
injured. 
</P>
<P>
	INA quoted the military as saying in a statement that allied  
planes also attacked a number of ``our civil and service 
installations'' in the southern province of Najaf, 105 miles south 
of Baghdad, killing three people and injuring two. 
</P>
<P>
	The warplanes, confronted by Iraqi air defenses, were ``forced  
to flee our skies'' to their bases in Turkey, Kuwait and Saudi 
Arabia, the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the third time in two weeks that Iraq has reported  
fatalities in airstrikes by allied planes patrolling no-fly zones 
in northern and southern Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	The government reported 14 deaths on July 18 and eight deaths on  
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The zone in the north was established shortly after the 1991  
Persian Gulf War to protect the rebelling Kurdish minority from 
government air raids. The no-fly zone in the south was set up in 
1992 to protect Shiite Muslims who defied President Saddam 
Hussein's rule. 
</P>
<P>
	Iraq does not recognize the zones and has challenged the allied  
planes patrolling them since Dec. 28. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
