<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Carter Now Does Tackling for Falcons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) -- Marty Carter has made more than 1,000  
tackles in his NFL career. The one he remembers most of all doesn't 
count on his resume. 
</P>
<P>
	The year was 1991. Carter was an unknown rookie safety for the  
Tampa Bay Buccaneers, getting a chance to start for the first time 
in an exhibition game against the Atlanta Falcons at old Fulton 
County Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Deion Sanders, beginning his tenure as a two-way star, lined up  
at receiver for the Falcons. Surely he's just a decoy, Carter 
muttered to himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Suddenly, he was facing one of the most dreaded moments for a  
defensive back: Neon Deion grabbed a pass, broke free in the 
secondary and seemingly had a clear path to the end zone. 
</P>
<P>
	``Deion started to do his strut, and I collared him from behind  
at the 2-yard line,'' Carter said Friday, relishing the moment 
again nearly eight years later. ``I like to say I ran him down. 
I've still got a tape of that play. My son watches it almost every 
day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This season, the 29-year-old Carter will get a chance to make  
those kind of plays for the Falcons instead of against them. He 
signed as a free agent after establishing himself as a sure-handed 
tackler during four years in Tampa Bay and the last four with 
Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	``That guy's a headhunter,'' Falcons cornerback Ray Buchanan  
said. ``Me, I hit when I have to. He goes around looking for 
someone to hit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This is a homecoming for Carter, who played at LaGrange High  
School -- a.k.a. The Cradle of Defensive Backs -- and now lives in 
the Atlanta suburb of Marietta. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was happier when Carter signed a five-year deal with the  
Falcons than his mother, Ellen Dunlap, who still lives in LaGrange. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I told her, I could hear a thump on the other end of the  
phone line,'' Carter recalled, chuckling. ``I said, `What 
happened?' She said, `I just fell off the sofa.''' 
</P>
<P>
	His mother was hesitant to make the long trip to Chicago, and  
she downright refused to attend games on frigid winter days at 
Soldier Field. 
</P>
<P>
	``She would just stay in the apartment and fix dinner for me  
when I got home,'' Carter said, knowing his mother plans to be on 
hand for every game at the always-72-degrees Georgia Dome, located 
about an hour's drive from LaGrange. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter is one of at least four defensive backs from LaGrange  
High who've made it to the NFL. Tony Stargill came before him, 
Tyrone Poole and Walt Harris followed. A fifth, rookie Jason Bray, 
is getting a free-agent tryout with the New England Patriots. 
</P>
<P>
	``In LaGrange, it was kind of instilled in us at a young age  
that you've got to play football around here,'' Carter remembered. 
``We had a better weight program than most colleges at that time. 
When Tony made it and then I made it, it kind of gave the guys 
under us some incentive that it can be done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-1, 210-pound Carter has been one of the NFL's  
fiercest tackles, a de facto linebacker who's averaged almost 160 
stops in each of the last four seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he wants to make it clear than he can also handle the  
coverage duties required of a strong safety. The Falcons aren't 
convinced yet, pulling Carter off the field during passing 
situations in the opening days of training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``Early on, I had to come up to play the run a lot and I got  
labeled as a run defender,'' Carter said. ``I don't shy away from 
contact. I like to play the run. But it's not a one-dimensional 
thing. I like to do all the things a deep defensive back needs to 
do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That includes talking. Carter was a vocal leader in Chicago and  
he's trying to make himself heard in the Falcons secondary, though 
that's not an easy task with teammates like Buchanan and Eugene 
Robinson, two of the NFL's all-star chatterboxes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We play a style of defense where the safety on the right side  
has to control his side,'' Carter said. ``So I get in a couple of 
words when I can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During Friday's practice, he barked out commands to his  
teammates several times, drawing a compliment from Buchanan for his 
vocal skills. 
</P>
<P>
	``Communication is big in the secondary,'' Buchanan said. ``He's  
doing a great job with a new team.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
