<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Found Guilty of Killing Baby </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCKVILLE, Md. (AP) -- A Maryland man was convicted of murdering  
his infant son 12 years ago in a case that was first believed to be 
Sudden Infant Death Syndrome. 
</P>
<P>
	Garrett Eldred Wilson, 43, a former piano salesman, has been  
charged with killing two of his children to collect $190,000 in 
life insurance money and is scheduled to stand trial later this 
summer for the suffocation death of a daughter. 
</P>
<P>
	He was found guilty Thursday of the 1987 smothering death of his  
5-month-old son and faces possible life in prison with no chance of 
parole when he's sentenced Sept. 3. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the verdict came, he was heaving. It was almost like  
someone hit you in the stomach and took your breath away,'' said 
defense attorney Barry Helfand. He said an appeal is likely. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson received $150,000 in life insurance benefits after his  
son's death. 
</P>
<P>
	The death of Garrett Michael Wilson was ruled a case of SIDS  
until the child's mother went to the police in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope this has helped the nation realize what's happening to  
children,'' said Mary ``Missy'' Anastasi, the dead child's mother, 
who was Wilson's third wife. 
</P>
<P>
	Anastasi, 45, first expressed her suspicions that her former  
husband killed their son on the morning the boy was pronounced 
dead. In 1994, she persuaded Montgomery County police to 
investigate the case. 
</P>
<P>
	During the 9-day trial, jurors reviewed evidence from the death  
of Garrett Michael and the death six years earlier of Wilson's baby 
daughter from a previous marriage. They heard from nearly 30 
witnesses, including five forensic pathologists. 
</P>
<P>
	``They understood that SIDS is not genetic, and they rendered a  
proper verdict in two hours,'' said Montgomery County State's 
Attorney Douglas Gansler. The deaths of both babies were originally 
considered cases of SIDS. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson faces trial Sept. 14 in Prince George's County, Md., for  
the 1981 death of Brandi Jean Wilson, his daughter from his second 
marriage. If Wilson is sentenced to life in prison with no chance 
of parole for the murder of his son, Prince George's prosecutors 
could elect to not try the second case. 
</P>
<P>
	The death of the 2-month-old girl was reclassified in 1998 as  
probable suffocation by undetermined means. Prosecutors said Wilson 
received $40,000 from life-insurance policies he purchased from two 
different companies within six weeks of her birth. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
