<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel Eases Proposed NASA Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House Appropriations Committee voted  
Friday to ease proposed cuts in NASA's budget but left the space 
agency well short of what President Clinton wants for next year. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA's extra $400 million was part of an effort by majority  
Republicans to bolster support for a massive $92 billion measure 
financing veterans, housing, space and environment programs for the 
coming fiscal year. The panel also boosted spending for veterans' 
health care by $700 million, responding to pressure from veterans' 
groups. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is one step in the process,'' said Rep. James Walsh,  
R-N.Y., alluding to even bigger spending increases expected to 
emerge from budget bargaining this fall with Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, the overall bill, which passed by voice vote, faces an  
administration veto threat for its reductions in space, housing and 
other programs. Though the added funds would bring NASA's 2000 
budget to about $12.7 billion, that remains $1 billion below this 
year's budget and $900 million short of Clinton's request. 
</P>
<P>
	``I appeal to members of Congress to fully restore the  
president's budget,'' NASA administrator Daniel Goldin said in a 
written statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The added NASA money would go to projects including Mars  
exploration and a planned orbiting infrared telescope, which an 
earlier version of the bill had cut. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA officials, who earlier had said the agency's Jet Propulsion  
Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif., and Goddard Space Flight Center in 
Greenbelt, Md., might be in jeopardy of closing, said they did not 
yet know whether the threat remains with the new numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	To pay for the space and veterans increases, the committee voted  
by voice to kill the Americorps national service program, cut 
disaster relief funds and shift money from a separate $300 billion 
bill financing labor, health and education programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee also removed controversial emergency designations  
for $5.5 billion worth of spending for veterans and disaster 
relief. The emergency label lets Congress ignore required spending 
limits and pay for items with the anticipated federal budget 
surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	The labor, health and education measure --the biggest of all 13  
annual spending bills, and the last to be written -- won't begin 
moving through committee until September. The $4 billion shifted 
out of it Friday left the measure almost $20 billion short of what 
Clinton wants for those social programs and only intensified 
Democratic opposition. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're taking it from kids in Head Start,'' said Rep. Steny  
Hoyer, D-Md. 
</P>
<P>
	But Walsh, chief author of the space and veterans' bill, said,  
``We'll meet the obligations of the country, but in a conservative 
way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To help pay for the labor, health and education bill,  
Republicans are considering another budget gimmick. 
</P>
<P>
	They would delay some federal Medicaid payments to the states  
from late September 2000 into early October, said aides speaking on 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	That timing shift would push the expenditure out of the books  
for fiscal year 2000 and into 2001, which begins Oct. 1. That would 
allow Republicans to claim savings next year of several billion 
dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours earlier, the committee used successive party-line votes to  
hold fast to its prior decision to label the $4.5 billion cost of 
the 2000 census an emergency. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans said unless they did so, FBI agents would have to be  
laid off and 80 U.S. embassies closed. Democratic efforts first to 
remove the emergency label for the entire $4.5 billion, and then 
for a portion of it, lost by 30-26 and 32-26. 
</P>
<P>
	That fight came as the panel used a voice vote to approve a  
$37.7 billion measure financing the departments of justice, state 
and commerce for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	White House advisers have threatened a veto because the  
legislation cuts Clinton's requests for hiring police officers, 
legal aid for the poor, U.S. participation in international 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
