<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 12:06:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Cowboys Give Spellman Second Chance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WICHITA FALLS, Texas (AP) -- Alonzo Spellman convinced the Dallas  
Cowboys he's overcome a horrible stretch during which he lost his 
job, his marriage and, at times, his battle with a mental illness. 
</P>
<P>
	Now he's got to prove it.  
</P>
<P>
	Spellman participated in his first workout with the Cowboys  
today and said afterward that he is excited about the chance to 
play again. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great opportunity for me to come back and do some good  
things on the field,'' he said. ``I can't wait to get started. It 
feels great to get back on the field. I'm just ready to keep on 
going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cowboys on Thursday signed Spellman, a defensive end who  
missed all of last season, to a one-year, $400,000 contract with 
another $450,000 in incentives. He did not receive a signing bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	``He represented to me that he would do anything and everything  
it takes to be a productive player on our team,'' team owner Jerry 
Jones said. ``We've represented to him he has a genuine shot of 
making our team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-4, 292-pound Spellman was a first-round pick by the  
Chicago Bears in 1992 and an anchor on their defensive line for 
several seasons before being limited by injuries in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, from March to September 1998, he lost his job and his  
marriage as he struggled to control bipolar disorder, a mental 
disorder that is treatable by medication but can lead to manic 
behavior if pills aren't taken. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cowboys have been talking to Spellman since October. Jones  
said the team conducted an extensive background check and he 
personally did a lot of research before deciding to sign him. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're confident this will work,'' Jones said.  
</P>
<P>
	Dallas has a lack of depth and experience on its defensive line,  
especially with tackle Leon Lett indefinitely suspend for drug 
problems. The only way for Jones to bring in someone of Spellman's 
caliber for such a cheap price is by taking what many would 
consider a big risk. 
</P>
<P>
	``You weigh the positives and negatives of any player that's out  
there right now that could possibly come to your team, whether it's 
Alonzo Spellman or anybody else,'' coach Chan Gailey said. ``I 
don't think we're down to the bare necessities, grabbing at 
anything that might show up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gailey, a devout man, said he believes second chances ``are part  
of life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm much more interested in the present and the future of a  
person than condemning somebody forever for the past,'' Gailey 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Spellman's problems began when he barricaded himself for eight  
hours inside the home of his publicist. SWAT negotiators couldn't 
talk him into coming out, but former Bears star Mike Singletary 
did. 
</P>
<P>
	Spellman was hospitalized that night, but the next day he walked  
out of the building into freezing weather without wearing a shirt 
or shoes. 
</P>
<P>
	Other incidents included:  
</P>
<P>
	--Detroit police using pepper spray to subdue him from attacking  
hotel security guards who were trying to break up a fight between 
two women who were with Spellman. 
</P>
<P>
	--The Bears releasing him two years into a four-year, $11.6  
million contract. 
</P>
<P>
	--Getting pulled over for erratic driving, which led to his  
arrest for having in the car a semiautomatic handgun and a bullet 
in a gun case and a half-empty wine bottle, and for driving with a 
revoked license. 
</P>
<P>
	--Getting evicted from his home.  
</P>
<P>
	--Being awaken by police from a nap in his car in the fast lane  
on an interstate highway. Officers said that when they woke him, he 
didn't seem to know where he was. 
</P>
<P>
	Remnants of that ruinous period remain. He faces an Aug. 19  
court date in Michigan for a felony charge of carrying a concealed 
weapon and misdemeanor charges for having open alcohol in a vehicle 
and driving without a license. If convicted, he faces up to five 
years in prison on the weapon charge and up to 90 days in jail on 
the misdemeanor charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 12:06:00 </DATE_TIME>
