<HEADLINE> Virgnia Steelworkers Cast Ballots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWPORT NEWS, Va. (AP) -- Steelworkers began casting ballots this  
morning on a proposed contract that would end a 16-week strike at 
Newport News Shipbuilding, the nation's only builder of aircraft 
carriers. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of Local 8888 of the United Steelworkers of America  
began voting at 6 a.m. Results were expected later this evening. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote will either end the strike or send the union and  
company back to the bargaining table to try again. 
</P>
<P>
	If a simple majority of those voting support the contract, union  
members will begin returning to work next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The tentative agreement was reached last week during federally  
mediated talks. Some union members said they were disappointed with 
the proposed raise and the length of the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract provides a pay raise averaging $3.10 an hour over  
58 months and improves the pension plan for workers who retire at 
62 with at least 30 years experience. 
</P>
<P>
	The union represents 9,200 production and maintenance workers.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
