<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chairman of China Everbright Quits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- The China Everbright Group, one of the  
country's largest corporate groups, announced Friday that its 
chairman resigned. 
</P>
<P>
	But company officials denied reports that he was under  
investigation for alleged ``economic irregularities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zhu Xiaohua, who resigned, was one of China's most prominent  
executives and a protege of Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji. He was 
replaced by Liu Mingkang, a deputy governor of China's central 
bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Liu said he also took over Zhu's position as chairman of China  
Everbright Bank, one of China's most profitable and innovative 
commerical banks, as well as its listed units in Hong Kong. 
</P>
<P>
	China Everbright Group is controlled by China's State Council,  
or the cabinet. 
</P>
<P>
	Liu insisted it was a ``normal transfer,'' denying widespread  
but unconfirmed media reports that Zhu was fired and under criminal 
investigation for bad deals costing more than $200 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as I'm concerned, this is part of normal operations,  
nothing more, nothing less,'' said Liu. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong newspapers reported on Friday that Chinese President  
Jiang Zemin personally ordered Zhu's return to Beijing. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
