<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brawl Marred Phillies-Braves Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- After the Phillies-Braves game was delayed 16  
minutes by a power outage, Atlanta manager Bobby Cox and two of his 
players -- pitcher John Smoltz and catcher Eddie Perez -- were 
ejected in separate incidents Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Perez was thrown out in the top of the fourth inning for shoving  
and then throwing a punch at Phillies pitcher Paul Byrd, who had 
hit Perez with a pitch the previous inning. 
</P>
<P>
	Both benches emptied and a melee ensued, with players on both  
sides shoving each other. When order was restored, Perez was 
ejected and replaced by Greg Myers. 
</P>
<P>
	The bad blood between Perez and Byrd, former Braves teammates,  
started Sunday in Philadelphia when Byrd -- who leads the majors 
with 13 hit batters -- plunked Perez with a pitch in Atlanta's 5-4, 
10-inning win. 
</P>
<P>
	In the bottom of the third Friday, Byrd hit Perez again with a  
pitch. Perez motioned to Byrd and both benches emptied but there 
there were no physical altercations at that time. 
</P>
<P>
	The lights went out in the bottom of the third on a night when  
the heat index reached 100 degrees. The outage, which also affected 
other areas in north Georgia, was caused by an equipment failure at 
a Georgia Power substation and the heavy strain on the electric 
system due to the hot weather. 
</P>
<P>
	When play began 16 minutes later, Perez was called out for  
interference on a grounder by Smoltz. 
</P>
<P>
	Following the double play, Cox ran onto the field and argued  
with second-base umpire Larry Poncino. After a few minutes, Poncino 
ejected Cox. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoltz, Atlanta's starting pitcher, was ejected in the top of  
the fourth by plate umpire Jerry Meals after hitting Alex Arias 
with a pitch. Smoltz charged towards Meals, apparently upset that 
he got no warning before getting tossed. 
</P>
<P>
	Russ Springer then replaced Smoltz. Two batters later, Byrd came  
to the plate with Arias on first and two outs. Byrd said something 
to Perez -- apparently telling the catcher he didn't mean to hit him 
the previous inning -- but Perez then attacked Byrd. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
