<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 49ers' Young Says It'll All Work Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STOCKTON, Calif. (AP) -- A slew of questions came at Steve Young.  
</P>
<P>
	How much longer would he play? How would the San Francisco 49ers  
handle the loss of Garrison Hearst? Would his line hold up? Would 
the team survive its ownership tumult. How would Lawrence Phillips 
and Charlie Garner fit in? 
</P>
<P>
	``Have you guys seen `Shakespeare in Love?''' Young said after  
taking part in San Francisco's first full-team workout Friday. ``In 
the movie, the guy would be like, `I don't know how it works, but 
it all works out in the end,' and that's the way it's been here. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every year, there's a litany of things that are going on.  
There's a lot of doubts and a lot of changes. But there's a point 
where the 49ers heritage kicks in and somehow we just kind of put 
it together. I don't think that's Pollyana.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Young, 37, is in his 15th season and ninth since succeeding Joe  
Montana as the 49ers' quarterback. A two-time MVP who led the 49ers 
to their fifth Super Bowl title in 1994, Young is coming off one of 
his best years, passing for a team-record 4,170 yards while leading 
the league's top-ranked offense. 
</P>
<P>
	``Physically, I don't feel any different,'' said Young, who  
turns 38 in October but proved durable last season, playing all but 
one game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't notice the years. Mentally, you're almost a better  
player in a way because you've calmed down a lot. You take things a 
little slower. You handle things better. I'm at a point where 
there's kind of golden years and your mind's mature and your body 
is still good. I'm enjoying those right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said coach Steve Mariucci: ``As far as his throwing, being in  
sync with his receivers, and his knowledge of the system, he's on 
top of his game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Young said he's aware San Francisco is trying reassert itself  
after finishing second last season to Atlanta in the NFC West and 
then losing to the Falcons in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	San Francisco also was confronted by organizational tumult that  
saw its entire front office turn over in the past year and siblings 
Eddie DeBartolo and his sister Denise DeBartolo York feud over 
control of the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Young said Bill Walsh's return -- the Hall of Fame coach was  
brought in as general manager last January -- had a stabilizing 
impact and helped the 49ers keep their competitive footing. 
</P>
<P>
	``He took over really a kind of messy situation. It really feels  
cohesive,'' Young said. ``You can tell he had a plan and he went 
out and did it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the field, the 49ers are trying to overcome a severe blow  
stemming from the loss of Hearst, who rushed for a club-record 
1,570 yards last year. 
</P>
<P>
	He broke his left ankle in the postseason loss at Atlanta and  
circulatory complications have stagnated his recovery to the point 
where he's not expected back until December. Their best defensive 
player, Bryant Young, also is coming off a serious leg injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Young, though, said the 49ers' offense will still be a  
formidable because Walsh was able to keep San Francisco's triple 
threat at wide receiver intact, re-signing J.J. Stokes and Terrell 
Owens to go with Jerry Rice. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was like, `Wow, that was fortuitous,' because we're going  
to need those weapons,'' Young said. ``In the NFL, if you don't 
line up, if you don't have the game kind of in your favor when you 
warm up by who comes out of the locker room, you're in trouble.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To replace Hearst, the 49ers signed Lawrence Phillips, gambling  
the Rams' top pick from 1996 has put his off-field problems behind 
him. They also added from Philadelphia running back Charlie Garner. 
</P>
<P>
	``Charlie Garner is a guy that can step in as a player in this  
offense because he knows the system already there's no question 
Lawrence, once he learns it will be a force,'' said Young, who gave 
Phillips a hug and personally welcomed him at the team's meeting 
Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we were sitting here and really didn't have any threats  
running the ball, then I'd be like, `Geez, I don't know what we 
would do.' 
</P>
<P>
	``But at this point, I feel like we have threats and we're the  
best at bringing new guys in, and indoctrinating them into our way 
and making them great players. So let's go for it. This might 
evolve into something that makes us even more explosive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Young said he doesn't believe the 49ers' image has been  
tarnished by the signing of Phillips, who twice was convicted in 
assaults on women. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the image is intact because the people that carry it  
are the ones that have carried the torch for a lot of years and 
demand it,'' said Young. ``So now if you add people, they have to 
join and accept the challenge of being a 49er.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
