<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Noon EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Police Reveal Atlanta Shooting Note  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- In a chilling suicide note, the investor who  
killed his family and nine people at two brokerage firms vowed to 
kill ``the people that greedily sought my destruction,'' police 
said today. Mark O. Barton left the note in his family's apartment 
in suburban Stockbridge, describing how he killed his wife and two 
children Tuesday and Wednesday, the Henry County police chief said. 
Barton wrote that he killed his children to spare them the pain of 
living without parents. Using a hammer ``just seemed like a polite 
way to kill and a relatively painless way to die,'' he wrote. 
``There was little pain. All of them were dead in less than five 
minutes.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Gore Offers Plan for Cutting Taxes  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Calling the Republicans' broader tax cuts  
``kind of crazy'' Vice President Al Gore today proposed new, but 
narrow, tax breaks of his own. Gore said in prepared remarks at the 
Minneapolis Community and Technical College that the GOP would undo 
today's prosperity by ``repeating the trickle-down tragedies of the 
past.'' Gore proposed a new ``401(j)'' program that would allow 
families and employers to contribute up to $2,500 a year that can 
be saved and withdrawn tax-free for educational expenses. To 
address the so-called ``marriage penalty,'' Gore proposed doubling 
the standard deduction for all joint filers. 

</P>
<P>
	NTSB: No JFK Jr. Plane Fire  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The wreckage of John F. Kennedy Jr.'s plane  
showed no signs of in-flight breakup or fire, and the engine 
appeared to have been working when the aircraft plunged into the 
ocean, a federal safety panel said today. The National 
Transportation Safety Board also said that 75 percent of the plane 
was recovered from the waters off Martha's Vineyard, Mass. The 
safety board also said that Kennedy had received a weather forecast 
via the Internet for his flight. The report, issued about two hours 
before takeoff, was for good visual-flight-rules conditions, with 
six to eight miles visibility. 

</P>
<P>
	Heat Wave Death Toll Climbs to 78  
</P>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- This summer's unrelenting heat has been  
sapping energy from outdoor workers, drying up crops and turning 
forests into kindling across the nation. At least 78 deaths in 14 
states have been blamed on the heat wave that has gripped much of 
country since July 19, as temperatures linger in the 90s and 100s. 
Missouri has the highest death toll at 27. The heat is expected to 
last at least until today before a change in the jet stream brings 
cooler air from Canada to northern states. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Lauds Sarajevo Rebirth  
</P>
<P>
	SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- President Clinton said today  
he was awed by the ``remarkably astonishing'' rebirth of this 
war-ravaged city and he wants Sarajevo to stand as a symbol of 
tolerance in the Balkans and not for its violent past. ``The war is 
over,'' Clinton told students at a multiethnic high school. ``We 
have to build a better peace for Bosnia and all of Southeast 
Europe.'' During the war that ended in 1995, Sarajevo's besieged 
population was pinned down by Bosnian-Serb forces. Amid daily 
tragedies, a few seared the world's conscience and propelled the 
West to intervene with airstrikes that ended the war. 

</P>
<P>
	Woodstock Rape Reports Investigated  
</P>
<P>
	ROME, N.Y. (AP) -- Rape counselors and crisis intervention  
workers say they treated far more sexual assault victims than the 
four reported to police during the Woodstock '99 festival. Sandy 
Lattimore, emergency services director of the Rome office of the 
American Red Cross, said her staff treated multiple victims of 
sexual assaults. The Oneida County Rape Crisis Center yesterday 
reported that two other teen-age girls have come forward with 
allegations that they were raped. One of the alleged rapes occurred 
in a mosh pit 30 yards away from the stage, police said. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 13; Nasdaq Up 27  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before noon EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 13.30 points at 10,777.99. Advancing issues on the New York 
Stock Exchange led decliners 1,487-1,108. The Nasdaq was up 27.80 
at 2,667.81. 

</P>
<P>
	Tour de France Drug Tests Negative  
</P>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- All the cyclists in this year's  
Tour de France were tested for banned substances and none was 
found, world cycling's governing body said today. The International 
Cycling Union said it carried out tests during every stage of the 
race and there were no positive results. The three-week race was 
won by Texan Lance Armstrong, making a remarkable comeback from 
cancer. The cycling union said earlier that tests on Armstrong had 
shown traces of corticosteroids but this had been caused by a skin 
cream he was using with a doctor's OK. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
