<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Atlanta Shootings Saddens Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- President Clinton today  
expressed sadness over the deadly shooting rampage in two Atlanta 
brokerage firms. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after arriving here for a summit on rebuilding the  
Balkans region, Clinton said he received updates on the Thursday 
shooting spree during a stop at a U.S. air base in Italy. The 
president declined to discuss possible causes, saying he did not 
yet know enough about the events to draw any conclusions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our thoughts are primarily with the families of the victims  
and those who are struggling for their lives in the hospital,'' 
Clinton said. ``But in terms of what could have, should have been 
done and what this means for other issues, I think we have to wait 
until all the facts come in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said federal officials were assisting state and local  
authorities in their investigation. Nine people were killed and 12 
injured in the attack, one of the nation's worst workplace 
massacres. 
</P>
<P>
	The gunman, Mark O. Barton, 44, shot and killed himself as  
police cornered him at a suburban Atlanta service station. He was 
said to be upset over financial losses from day-trading stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Barton's wife, son and daughter also were found dead in their  
home. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
