<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Atlanta Mayor in Familiar Spotlight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- As the horror mounted and the manhunt for a mass  
murderer dragged on, Mayor Bill Campbell calmly told his city and a 
nation what he knew, what he didn't and sometimes how he felt. 
</P>
<P>
	It's an honesty Atlanta knows well. The two-term mayor is the  
city's most visible spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	The Centennial Olympic Park bombing, a hostage crisis involving  
children, a high-wire rescue of a construction worker from a huge 
inferno -- Campbell has been there for all of them, front and 
center. He was there again Thursday after Mark O. Barton killed 12 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	``From Colorado to Atlanta, these things occur. We do not know  
why,'' Campbell said after Barton committed suicide Thursday night. 
``We'll simply have to search our souls.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Pray for our city,'' the Democrat said during a news  
conference that was nationally broadcast. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks ago, Campbell also handled spokesman duties for the  
police after an estranged boyfriend killed all but one member of an 
Atlanta family. He also made several appearances on local TV later 
when he visited the lone 11-year-old survivor. 
</P>
<P>
	``The depth of this tragedy is so overwhelming that it's hard  
for us to comprehend,'' Campbell said at the funeral. ``We come 
today to show our love and support for this family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell, first elected in 1993, has made a habit of holding  
live news conferences soon after other high-profile incidents -- 
including the Centennial Olympic Park bombing and, more recently, a 
mass shooting that left all but one member of an Atlanta family 
dead last month. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a role that most cities delegate to a spokesperson or, in  
serious situations, a chief of police, though Police Chief Beverly 
Harvard was out of town Thursday. But Campbell's aides say he 
recognizes the need for leadership in such situations. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's the mayor of the city, and when something like this  
happens, he needs to be here,'' said his spokesman, Nick Gold. 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell remained soft-spoken and solemn but stayed very  
involved, pacing the scene as he received updates on his cell 
phone. It was, for him, a task that is growing far too familiar. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the past two weeks, we've had two deranged people kill 17  
people, perhaps more, in this city,'' he said. ``I have no 
explanation for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The third black to hold the mayor's office in the history of the  
city, Campbell addressed the media after the city's three bombings, 
including one of an abortion clinic in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell has also been in the national spotlight for his ardent  
defense of the city's affirmative-action program and his suit 
against gunmakers, later outlawed by the Georgia General Assembly. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
