<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Supports Background Checks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House, easing its stand against toughening  
gun control laws, voted Friday to support background checks on all 
firearms sales at gun shows. The nonbinding vote came the day after 
a gunman killed nine people in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	The action was on a resolution recommending that House  
participants in negotiations with the Senate support background 
checks. 
</P>
<P>
	Six weeks ago, while passing a juvenile crime bill, the House  
rejected gun control provisions adopted earlier by the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate agreed earlier this week to begin negotiations with  
the House to resolve the differences between the bills passed by 
each chamber. But House leaders did not appoint its members to the 
House-Senate committee until Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the House's earlier rejection of gun control provisions,  
it voted 305-84 for the nonbinding resolution recommending its 
negotiators support the requirement that background checks be 
conducted on all firearms sales at gun shows. Under current law, 
background checks are required only on sales by licensed dealers. 
</P>
<P>
	The resolution also calls for including measures to prevent  
violence in schools and ensuring that the legislation does not 
weaken existing gun regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., the House Judiciary Committee's top  
Democrat, said the vote was a repudiation of the National Rifle 
Association, which has lobbied against new gun control laws. 
</P>
<P>
	``With today's vote, more than 300 of my colleagues finally  
joined the majority of the Senate in showing the courage to take on 
the NRA and enact tough bans on criminal purchases at gun shows, 
the biggest single loophole in our nation's gun safety laws,'' 
Conyers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote was particularly important, he said, because it came a  
day after an office shooting that left nine people dead in Atlanta. 
Investigators say Mark O. Barton, an investor, shot nine people to 
death at two brokerage firms on Thursday after killing his wife and 
two children earlier in the week. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats said the tragedy should put more pressure on  
Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	``If this leadership doesn't act and doesn't pass common sense  
gun legislation, they are going to have to explain to the American 
public why the NRA has more influence over them than all the 
mothers and fathers and children of this country,'' said Rep. Nita 
Lowey, D-N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said provisions in the  
House bill that would toughen penalties against teen-age criminals 
would help reduce school violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``This legislation will not solve every problem, but it will  
take steps to make our schools safer,'' he said in a statement. ``I 
hope our Democrat colleagues put the good of the country in front 
of partisanship as we proceed with this issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some Democrats said they were pleased to see action on  
legislation that could result in tighter restrictions on gun 
ownership, but they still accused Republicans of obstruction. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's move. We are tired of seeing delay. We are tired of  
seeing stonewalling,'' said Rep. Rosa DeLauro, D-Conn. ``We also 
realize and understand that they have dragged their feet on this, 
putting it off until the last week. I don't know what they're 
hoping for, because it's not going away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate bill, in addition to requiring background checks on  
all firearms buyers at gun shows, would require dealers to provide 
safety devices with all handguns, ban importation of certain high 
capacity firearms clips and impose a lifetime prohibition of gun 
ownership by anyone convicted as a juvenile of a serious felony. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
