<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Tripp Indicted on Wiretap Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ELLICOTT CITY, Md. (AP) -- A grand jury indicted Linda Tripp  
today for secretly taping her phone conversations with Monica 
Lewinsky, charging she broke Maryland wiretapping laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tripp, whose tapes led to impeachment of the president,  
becomes the only central figure in the Lewinsky scandal to face 
criminal charges. 
</P>
<P>
	After a year of investigation, State Prosecutor Stephen  
Montanarelli said the grand jury indicted Mrs. Tripp on one count 
of illegal interception stemming from a phone conversation taped on 
Dec. 22, 1997, after she allegedly was told by her lawyer that 
secret taping was illegal. She also was charged with allegedly 
disclosing the contents of that conversation to Newsweek magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	Wiretapping in Maryland is punishable by up to five years in  
prison and a $10,000 fine for each offense. 
</P>
<P>
	Montanarelli, a Democrat, said he would prosecute the case  
himself. Asked whether the case would be seen by some as 
politically inspired, he said, ``I can't help how it will be seen 
.... I think we've done our duty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was Mrs. Tripp's more than 20 hours of recordings that  
launched Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's investigation of 
Clinton's sexual relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, a former White 
House intern. 
</P>
<P>
	The recordings of the two women's rambling and sometimes ribald  
conversations were released publicly by the House Judiciary 
Committee before the House voted to impeach Clinton for perjury and 
obstruction. He was acquitted in a Senate trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tripp had turned the tapes over to Starr's office under a  
grant of immunity from federal prosecution. But the deal did not 
protect her from prosecution by her home state. 
</P>
<P>
	Ignorance of the law is a valid defense in this case. But Mrs.  
Tripp, who taped the calls in her Columbia, Md., living room, 
testified for Starr's grand jury that she taped several 
conversations in late 1997 even after an attorney told her it was 
illegal. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tripp's current attorney, Joseph Murtha, asked that Mrs.  
Tripp be allowed to surrender voluntarily, rather than being 
arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no sign of Mrs. Tripp today at her home. No one  
answered a knock on the door and neighbors said they had not seen 
her for about a week. Rear Adm. Craig Quigley, a spokesman for the 
Department of Defense, said she had not come to work since Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Family spokesman Philip Coughter said Mrs. Tripp's attorneys are  
bringing on board Steve Kohn, a Washington attorney with experience 
in government whistle-blower cases. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House and representatives for Ms. Lewinsky declined to  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tripp, 49, said she began taping her friend's phone calls  
to protect herself because she was being pressured by Ms. Lewinsky 
to lie in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit against the 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky confided her sexual encounters with the president  
to Mrs. Tripp after the pair became friends while working together 
at the Pentagon. Ms. Lewinsky wanted Mrs. Tripp to deny knowledge 
of the relationship in an affidavit for the sexual harassment case. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tripp said Ms. Lewinsky also wanted her to lie about her  
knowledge of an alleged sexual advance by the president against 
White House volunteer Kathleen Willey. 
</P>
<P>
	New York book agent Lucianne Goldberg, who testified in Starr's  
investigation last November, said she urged Mrs. Tripp to start 
taping. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tripp also talked with Ms. Goldberg about writing a  
tell-all book about her years at the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Reached by phone in New York, Ms. Goldberg called Mrs. Tripp a  
``loyal government whistle-blower.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Now she will be able to have her day in court and tell her  
side of the story,'' Ms. Goldberg said. ``She has never been able 
to tell her side because she has always been under fear of 
indictment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton administration aide Bob Weiner -- who was questioned by  
Starr's team about his calls to a Democratic group that urged the 
state to investigate Mrs. Tripp -- said it was ``gratifying that the 
law may finally recognize her abuses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Her violations of privacy were an affront to the meaning of  
friendship,'' Weiner said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
