<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Atlanta Gunman Left Note Behind  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Mark O. Barton, the gunman who killed nine people  
at two brokerage firms Thursday, had lost roughly $105,000 in stock 
trading in less than two months, authorities said Friday. He left a 
note vowing revenge on those who had ``greedily sought my 
destruction.'' Barton's wife, son and daughter were found 
bludgeoned to death in the family residence. Thirteen also were 
wounded in the office attacks, with five still in critical 
condition tonight. Barton killed himself to avoid arrest. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate Passes Tax Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans pushed their $792 billion tax cut  
through the Senate Friday, courting a veto struggle this fall with 
President Clinton. The vote was 57-43 -- largely along party lines -- 
in favor of the GOP plan. Democrats claim the bill shortchanges 
Medicare and other domestic programs. The 10-year measure, which 
includes broad-based tax relief as well as provisions designed to 
address the so-called marriage penalty, would make it easier to 
accumulate retirement savings and pay for education. 

</P>
<P>
	Vujanovic Urges Milosevic To Resign  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Montenegrin Prime Minister Filip  
Vujanovic said Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic was doing 
tremendous harm to the country and urged him to resign as soon as 
possible. ``With a president like Milosevic, no country has a 
future,'' Vujanovic told BLIC daily. Vujanovic said Milosevic 
should leave office because Serbs and Montenegrins have suffered 
enough under him. 

</P>
<P>
	Car Bomb Kills 9 in Colombia  
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- A powerful car bomb ripped through the  
Medellin offices of the army's anti-kidnapping squad Friday, 
killing at least nine people and injuring 30 others, officials 
said. At least seven of the wounded were soldiers, Gen. Eduardo 
Herrera, commander of the army's 4th Brigade based in Medellin, 
told Radionet radio. No group had claimed responsibility for the 
attack, but Herrera blamed Colombia's largest rebel army, the 
leftist Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC. 

</P>
<P>
	Heat Wave Death Toll Reaches 93  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The heat wave gripping much of the nation has  
been linked to at least 93 deaths in 18 states since July 19. The 
Midwest has been hit hardest, with Missouri logging 29 heat-related 
deaths, Illinois 23 and Ohio 10. Temperatures neared 100 degrees 
Friday in many cities, and the heat index -- a measure of 
temperature and humidity -- rose past 110 in several places. It was 
104 degrees in Louisville, Ky., and 102 at the Little Rock, Ark., 
Air Force Base. 

</P>
<P>
	Fees To Subsidize School Internet  
</P>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- A federal program that adds fees to telephone  
bills to subsidize cheaper Internet hookups for schools and 
libraries was largely upheld by a federal appeals court Friday. 
Commissioner Susan Ness of the Federal Communications Commission 
called the ruling by the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ``a huge 
win for America's children.'' And Vice President Al Gore, whose 
support led opponents of the program to dub it ``the Gore tax,'' 
also applauded the decision as ``a victory for America.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Gerber Drops Bioengineered Suppliers  
</P>
<P>
	SUMMIT, N.J. (AP) -- Gerber, the nation's largest maker of baby  
food, will no longer buy genetically engineered corn and soybean 
products from suppliers. Gerber's parent company, Novartis AG of 
Switzerland, said it was considering the move even before the 
environmental group Greenpeace asked for information about the 
company's use of bioengineered products. Other baby-food makers 
have made similar decisions. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Close Lower; Dow Down 136.14  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks slid for a second straight session  
Friday, with the Dow Jones industrial average languishing behind 
other indicators amid concerns over interest rates. The Dow ended 
down 136.14 points at 10,655.15, adding to a 180-point plunge 
Thursday. On the NYSE, advancers led decliners 1,495-1,445. The 
Nasdaq was down 1.49 at 2,638.52. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Soccer Defeats Germany 2-0  
</P>
<P>
	GUADALAJARA, Mexico (AP) -- The United States upset Germany, the  
European champion, in a surprising 2-0 win Friday night, which put 
the Americans in the semifinals of the FIFA Confederations Cup. 
``We prepared well, and we had a great game,'' U.S. coach Bruce 
Arena said. ``I'm proud and satisfied with my players.'' 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF  
  	   	
</P>
