<DOCNO> APW19990730.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 15:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mass. Actions on Day-Trading Cos. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Massachusetts has been the most aggressive state in cracking  
down on alleged illegal activity at day-trading firms. Key points 
from the state's recent legal actions. 

</P>
<P>
	Oct. 19, 1998. Block Trading Inc.  
</P>
<P>
	Charges: Deceptive marketing; unlawful loan activities;  
encouragement of investment advisory activity by unregistered 
persons. 
</P>
<P>
	Outcome: The firm is in bankruptcy. Individuals charged agreed  
not to apply for registration with the Massachusetts Securities 
Division for five years. 

</P>
<P>
	Nov. 9, 1998. Bright Trading Inc.  
</P>
<P>
	Charge: Operation of an investment office without registering as  
a broker-dealer. 
</P>
<P>
	Outcome: Settled with payment of $30,000; corrections of its Web  
site information. 

</P>
<P>
	Dec. 10, 1998. All-Tech Investment Group Inc.  
</P>
<P>
	Charges: Deceptive marketing; co-mingling of customer funds;  
forgery of customer signatures; creation of ficticious accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Outcome: Firm settled with payment of $50,000; reimbursement of  
$228,000 to customers; Agreement not to accept new customers at 
Boston branch for two years. 

</P>
<P>
	Jan. 14, 1999. On-line Investment Services Inc.  
</P>
<P>
	Charges: Deceptive claim that 85 percent of customers were  
successful; unnecessary trading to generate extra commissions; 
transfers of funds between a customer's account and a manager's 
wife's account. 
</P>
<P>
	Outcome: Firm and branch manager settled with combined payments  
of $20,000; both withdrew registrations with Massachusetts 
Securities Division and agreed not to reapply for two years. 

</P>
<P>
	March 2, 1999. TCI Corp.  
</P>
<P>
	Charges: Deceptive claim that the firm's system generates ``6 to  
7 figure income'' per year; solicitation of funds for fraudulent 
``Institutional Investment Program.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Outcome: Cease and desist order issued; matter referred to the  
state attorney general for further investigation. 

</P>
<P>
	July 8, 1999. Landmark Securities Corp. and Equity Traders LLC.  
</P>
<P>
	Charges: Opening accounts for customers for whom day trading was  
unsuitable; falsification of new account forms; unauthorized 
transactions and fund transfers with a customer's account; promoted 
loans between customers at abusive interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Outcome: Still pending.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
