<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 16:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rep. Candidates Comment on Tax Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	What the Republican candidates for the White House in 2000 are  
saying about the House and Senate tax cut bills: 
</P>
<P>
	LAMAR ALEXANDER   	
</P>
<P>
	National Political Director Brian Kennedy said Alexander likes  
aspects of both bills, but they don't go far enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the first things he wants to do is triple the child tax  
credit to $8,000 and expand the definition of dependent to include 
care for elderly family members,'' Kennedy said. Alexander also 
wants to eliminate the marriage penalty and create tax incentives 
to encourage parents to save in education savings accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	GARY BAUER   	
</P>
<P>
	Bauer applauds both bills for the across-the-board tax cuts.  
</P>
<P>
	``I much prefer tax relief on the human side,'' Bauer said. ``I  
am in favor of a capital gains tax cut because I think it is 
important for the Republicans ... to have provisions that are aimed 
at family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer prefers the more sweeping marriage penalty provision in  
the Senate bill. ``It is ridiculous that there is any marriage 
penalty provision at all,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	PAT BUCHANAN   	
</P>
<P>
	Campaign spokesman Bob Adams said Buchanan favors the House  
bill. Buchanan was unavailable to elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	GEORGE W. BUSH   	
</P>
<P>
	Bush will announce his own tax and economic plans later this  
year, said campaign spokeswoman Karen Hughes. 
</P>
<P>
	``He believes the marriage penalty should be reduced,'' she  
said. ``He believes the death tax should be reduced. He also 
applauds the House and Senate for working to enact a sizable tax 
cut.'' 
</P>
<P>
	ELIZABETH DOLE   	
</P>
<P>
	Dole also plans to announce a tax package in the fall.  
</P>
<P>
	``She has no intention of getting involved in the minutiae of  
tax legislation'' now, said campaign spokesman Ari Fleisher. ``She 
is in favor of marriage penalty relief, death tax relief, and she 
has already said ... she would seek a 100 percent health care 
deduction for the self-employed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	STEVE FORBES   	
</P>
<P>
	Forbes, who is in favor of a flat tax, thinks both packages are  
flawed, but far better than anything the Democrats would offer, 
said campaign spokeswoman Juleanna Glover Weiss. 
</P>
<P>
	If he were president, he would sign a House-Senate compromise,  
but ``he would prefer whatever moves closer to tax 
simplification,'' Weiss said. 
</P>
<P>
	ORRIN HATCH   	
</P>
<P>
	Hatch favors across-the-board income tax reductions, capital  
gains tax cuts and the elimination of estate taxes and the marriage 
penalty, said campaign spokesman Jeff Flint. 
</P>
<P>
	``Another priority (for Hatch) in terms of tax cuts would be  
anything that adds greater flexibility to retirement planning,'' 
Flint said. 
</P>
<P>
	JOHN McCAIN  
</P>
<P>
	McCain said he prefers the Senate bill because the marriage  
penalty is better addressed and the bill has more immediate 
benefits for middle-income Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	But, McCain said, ``I am unhappy about the amount of special  
interest loopholes and benefits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DAN QUAYLE   	
</P>
<P>
	Quayle favors across-the-board tax cuts, but doesn't think the  
House and Senate cuts are deep enough, said campaign spokesman 
Jonathan Baron. Quayle has proposed a 30 percent tax cut. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, ``to phase (a tax cut) over 10 years is very long,  
and he has some concerns,'' Baron added. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 01:50:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Upsets Cuba in Baseball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- One day after a stirring victory over  
Cuba, the U.S. baseball team came out as flat as the prairie roads 
leading to the host city of the Pan American Games. 
</P>
<P>
	When they took the field against Brazil on Thursday night, the  
Americans already knew Canada had beaten Cuba 8-1, clinching the 
second seed in Pool A for the United States. Canada won the group, 
and world champion Cuba was third. 
</P>
<P>
	``We basically threw our hats out there today. We were flat and  
we knew it. We got to rebound and get ready for whoever we play 
next,'' American reliever Bobby Seay said after saving a 3-2 
victory over winless Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	Pool play is now over, and it's single elimination time  
beginning Saturday with the quarterfinals. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States needs victories Saturday over Panama and  
Sunday to make the gold medal game and qualify for the Sydney 
Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a very emotional game yesterday,'' U.S. coach Buddy  
Bell said, looking back at a 10-5 victory over Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just got done playing Brazil, who some would argue is not  
the strongest team in the tournament. But again, it's just like 
hockey. You go up against a hot goalie you will have a tough 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil reliever Toni Nakashima was especially bothersome to U.S.  
hitters, giving up just two hits in 3 2-3 innings. The Americans, 
who had 19 hits in beating Cuba, managed only five overall. They 
scored the go-ahead run on Mike Neill's bases-loaded fielder's 
choice in the fifth on a double-play ball bobbled by the shortstop. 
</P>
<P>
	``The left-hander they brought in was as good a pitcher as we've  
faced this whole tournament as far as command and mixing pitches. 
It's what you have to guard against,'' Bell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada's victory over Cuba means the Americans will not have to  
play the Canadians or Cubans before Monday's finals. 
</P>
<P>
	``They looked like they didn't want to be here,'' Canadian  
catcher Andy Stewart said of the Cubans. 
</P>
<P>
	Seay came on in the eighth with runners at second and third and  
struck out pinch-hitter T.N. Kussano, and then fanned two of three 
in the ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	Jason Hardtke homered for the United States in the first, but  
Brazil took a 2-1 lead in the second using a third-strike wild 
pitch, a throwing error by Neill and an RBI single by Victor 
Higuchi. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States tied the game in the bottom half when Brazil  
starter Douglas Assada fumbled a comebacker, allowing Neill to 
score. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil almost went ahead in the eighth, but Estevao Sato's long  
drive hit the top of the left field fence for a double instead of 
going over. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil finished 0-4 and is the only team in the nine-team  
tournament not headed for the quarterfinals. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. starter Ryan Anderson, who at 6-foot-10 is known as the  
``Little Unit,'' struck out nine in six innings Thursday night in a 
game played in Stonewall, some 20 miles outside of Winnipeg. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time Canada beat Cuba in baseball was at the  
Intercontinental Cup in Edmonton in 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a rugged game at times, with Canada's Aaron Guiel  
flattening Cuban catcher Ariel Pestano twice and getting ejected. 
Guiel made no attempt to slide and appeared to deliver a forearm 
shiver to Pestano in the seventh. 
</P>
<P>
	Players from both teams converged at home plate, but Guiel and  
Pestano were separated and no punches were thrown. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was angry,'' Guiel said. ``I decided I was going to try and  
take a guy out on the infield or the catcher. I had to show them we 
would stand up for ourselves.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
