<DOCNO> APW19990730.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 15:10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EPA To Ban Fruit Pesticide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government is banning a pesticide sprayed  
on as much as 30 percent of the nation's apple crop and cutting 
back on the widespread use of another chemical for the control of 
insects on fruits and vegetables. 
</P>
<P>
	The actions, to be announced Monday by the Environmental  
Protection Agency, stem from fears that the pesticides can cause 
damage to the brain and nervous system, especially in young 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	Government officials say this year's crop of apples and produce  
that have been sprayed with the chemicals are safe. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nothing to worry about,'' said Allen Jennings, director  
of the Agriculture Department's office of pest management policy. 
``I still plan on feeding my kids as many as they will eat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	EPA is acting under a 1996 law that requires it to reassess  
tolerance levels, or margins of safety, for hundreds of pesticides. 
</P>
<P>
	Agency officials refused Friday to discuss their plans. Details  
of the restrictions remained under negotiation with the pesticide 
makers, industry and government sources said. 
</P>
<P>
	They said, however, that methyl parathion would be banned from  
use on all fruit and many vegetables, and growers probably will be 
required to use smaller amounts of azinphos-methyl. 
</P>
<P>
	Azinphos-methyl is used on 80 percent of the nation's apples and  
on a wide variety of other crops, from pears to cotton and sugar 
beets. 
</P>
<P>
	Environmental groups, who contend the pesticides are dangerous,  
have been pushing for the restrictions for some time. They accused 
EPA of putting off decisions on other dangerous chemicals. 
</P>
<P>
	``The question is whether EPA has met its obligation to address  
the worst pesticides first. We think they've misled the public into 
believing that they have,'' said David Willinga, a senior scientist 
for the Natural Resources Defense Council. 
</P>
<P>
	Methyl parathion and azinphos-methyl are two of about 40  
pesticides known as organophosphates, which account for most 
pesticides used by American farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	EPA must evaluate 10,000 uses of various pesticides under the  
Food Quality Protection Act. Tuesday is the deadline for the agency 
to have finished the first third of those. 
</P>
<P>
	Farm groups say no sound scientific basis exists for restricting  
the two pesticides. They fear the public will react by shunning 
this year's crops. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an irresponsible action by the agency to take this action  
now. The data they're using to make this assessment is not 
complete,'' said Adam Sharp, director of governmental relations for 
the American Farm Bureau Federation. 
</P>
<P>
	A controversial portion of the 1996 law required EPA to  
compensate for incomplete scientific data about pesticide effects 
by using an additional margin of error of 10 times the current 
limit for cumulative exposures. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers have alternative chemicals but they like to rotate  
pesticides to prevent insects from building tolerances to them, 
said Wally Ewart, vice president for scientific affairs with the 
Northwest Horticultural Council in Yakima, Wash. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we lose this material, and we lose some other materials,  
over time we will get to a point where we have a loss of control 
and the cost will go up,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 20:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Eagles, McNabb Agree to 7-Year Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Donovan McNabb and the Philadelphia Eagles  
agreed to a seven-year contract worth as much as $54 million with 
incentives Friday night, ending contentious negotiations that were 
marred by racial accusations by his agent. 
</P>
<P>
	McNabb, the No. 2 pick in the draft, agreed to the deal and got  
on a plane to Philadelphia, where he was expected to sign it late 
Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Agent Fletcher Smith, whose comments about race playing a role  
stalled the negotiations, said the deal does not include voidable 
years like deals signed by top quarterbacks Tim Couch, Peyton 
Manning and Ryan Leaf. 
</P>
<P>
	It includes an $11.3 million signing bonus and incentive clauses  
that would trigger higher salaries in the final three years of the 
deal -- a similar structure to the one running back Ricky Williams 
got from New Orleans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always said the voidable structure was a structure I was  
interested in getting, because it had been done for the other top 
quarterbacks,'' Smith said. ``If I could not get that structure, I 
would be happy with a contract that gave us the same kind of things 
as the voidable structure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bottom line: While McNabb's total package could be worth  
more than Couch's $48 million, seven-year deal, it guarantees 
nothing more than a minimum salary beyond the fourth year if McNabb 
doesn't play in the first three. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're happy with the deal,'' Smith said. ``It's an attractive  
package.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McNabb missed his fifth day of practice Friday and second day of  
full-squad workouts. The first-round draft choice is slated to back 
up starting quarterback Doug Pederson for the Eagles, who were 3-13 
last season. 
</P>
<P>
	McNabb will report to training camp at Lehigh University  
Saturday in time for the first day of full-squad workouts in pads. 
On Thursday, new coach Andy Reid stressed the importance of McNabb 
getting his contract resolved and reporting to camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every day, every practice, every rep he is missing, you can't  
get those back,'' Reid said. ``There's no price that you can put on 
those. Donovan needs to be here, and we want him here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eagles executive vice president Joe Banner said, ``Andy believes  
in Donovan very passionately. He wanted Donovan to be there, but he 
never lost faith in Donovan and was incredibly supportive of what I 
trying to do as well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith and the Eagles had been at an impasse over the structure  
of the final few years of the contract. The Eagles were against 
voidable years and a buy-back clause, and essentially won that 
showdown. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though the media focused on voidable years, although it  
was an important issue, it was not the only issue,'' Banner said. 
``We tried to come up with satisfactory tradeoff. Ultimately, that 
led to a package that probably isn't exactly what either of us 
wanted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiations ceased for two days this week after Smith's  
comments about race playing a role in the talks aired on a cable 
television show. Smith cited white quarterbacks who got voidable 
contracts and a black quarterback, Steve McNair, who didn't. 
</P>
<P>
	But the talks were salvaged when Smith, who is based in Chicago  
and has dealings with former NBA superstar Michael Jordan, flew to 
Philadelphia on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We felt it would be more constructive if we worked face to  
face, rather than on the phone where there can be distractions,'' 
Banner said. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Banner acknowledged that the controversy affected the  
negotiations, both sides said they thought it was over. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given that the statement came out of my mouth, I never really  
felt that race was an issue to begin with,'' Smith said. ``It 
didn't interfere with the discussions, especially over the past two 
days.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said the contract includes 8-10 incentives. If any  
incentive is reached in any of the first three seasons, the 
escalated salaries in the final three years kick in. He named three 
of the incentives: 1,601 passing yards, 30 touchdowns and a 100 
quarterback rating. 
</P>
<P>
	If the escalators kick in, Smith said McNabb's salary would be  
``about 5 percent more'' than Couch's in the final three seasons. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 03:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls, Tokyo Stocks Mixed / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar fell against the yen today when  
investors shrugged off dollar-supportive comments by many Japanese 
officials. Tokyo share prices ended mixed after a lower start. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 115.26 yen in the late afternoon, down 0.42  
yen from late Thursday in Tokyo and also below its late New York 
level of 115.40 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 8.06 points,  
or 0.05 percent, closing at 17,861.86. On Thursday, the average 
rose 290.01 points, or 1.65 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, there was some end-of-the-month demand for  
dollars earlier in the session but the dollar later lost ground in 
Asia on speculative selling. 
</P>
<P>
	A series of comments by Japanese officials meant to bolster the  
dollar's value against the yen did not have the desired effect 
because they were not followed by any intervention by the Bank of 
Japan, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said that Japan is carefully  
watching the foreign exchange market, though he said that recent 
dollar-yen moves reflect a weakening of the dollar rather than a 
strengthening of the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other officials, Haruhiko Kuroda, vice finance minister  
for international affairs, said: ``An excessively strong yen is 
undesirable for Japan and Asian economies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The greenback has been weak against major currencies in recent  
weeks, including the euro and yen, on expectations of an economic 
recovery in Japan and fears of inflation in the United States, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent weeks, the Bank of Japan repeatedly bought dollars in  
an attempt to suppress the yen's surge and aid the nation's 
fledgling economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ranged between 115.05 yen and 115.85 yen in today's  
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 123.46 yen, down  
from 123.56 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, the Nikkei index was weighted down by weak  
Japanese economic data, an overnight fall on Wall Street and a 
moderate strengthening of the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's unemployment rate climbed to a record high 4.9 percent  
in June from 4.6 percent in May as many companies accelerated their 
restructuring, the government said. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Japan's jobless rate was high, dealers said this  
indicator is a lagging figure, adding that Thursday's 
stronger-than-expected 3.0 percent surge in seasonally adjusted 
industrial production for June was more significant. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the exchange's first section was estimated at 511.64  
million shares, compared with Thursday's turnover of 510.74 million 
shares. Decliners outnumbered advancers 621 to 586, with 102 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 11.20 points, or 0.76 percent, to 1,478.93. 
The TOPIX closed up 17.40 points, or 1.20 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.7850 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.8050 
percent, driving its price up to 100.12 yen from 99.95 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
