<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ariz. Couple Adopts 10 Kids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MESA, Ariz. (AP) -- Van and Shirley Hughes have soothed the pangs  
of empty-nest syndrome in a big, big way. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple, both 52, have adopted 10 brothers and sisters who  
range in age from 4 to 17. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm happy, I'm grateful,'' said Frank, their new 17-year-old  
son. He called the Hugheses ``angels from above.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Hughes family expansion, finalized by a court commissioner  
on Thursday, is believed to be one of the nation's largest sibling 
group adoptions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody thinks we're crazy, but the pros outweigh the  
cons,'' Mrs. Hughes said. ``The children are the best things in my 
life. They're more blessings than trials.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police found the children in April 1995 in a trash-strewn house  
in downtown Phoenix, living among rodents and fending for 
themselves after their mother abandoned them. 
</P>
<P>
	About that time, with their own two sons having moved out and  
married, the Hugheses decided to become foster parents. 
</P>
<P>
	In June, 3-year-old Maria arrived at their home. Twelve days  
later, Arizona child welfare workers asked the couple to take 
5-year-old Enrique and his 6-year-old brother, Juan. 
</P>
<P>
	Two more siblings -- 3-year-old Veronica and 2-year-old Donicio --  
came in January 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The five older children regularly visited their siblings, and in  
June 1997, caseworkers asked the Hugheses if they wanted to take 
them all. 
</P>
<P>
	``My head told me `no,' but my heart told me `yes,''' said  
Hughes, who took early retirement from the Navy as a prerequisite 
for the mass adoption. ``They're brothers and sisters, and they 
belong together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To make room, the couple converted a garage and dining room to  
transform their home into one with six bedrooms, three bathrooms 
and 11 TVs. They receive $6,600 a month in state aid for the 
children, and Hughes works as a night watchman to help cover the 
family's $1,500 monthly grocery bills. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Jane Hull lauded them for ``providing a new world full of  
love, support and safety.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hughes said the 10 children are thriving, with many of them  
straight-A students and excelling in sports. 
</P>
<P>
	``You should see us at Christmas,'' he said. ``It takes four  
hours to open presents, and that's just for the children. But you 
can't buy what we give to them, and we can't buy what they give to 
us.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
