<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium To Limit Meat Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Belgium has told the European Union it  
will severely restrict meat exports in August following more 
uncertainty about the extent of dioxin contamination of Belgian 
food. 
</P>
<P>
	The Belgian government pledged to prohibit the export of  
livestock and meat products throughout the month unless it has been 
tested and declared dioxin free, said Gerry Kiely, agriculture 
spokesman for the European Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The restrictions results from growing fears that the number of  
Belgian farms that used animal feed tainted with the cancer-causing 
chemical is larger that thought. ``Between now and the end of 
August we should have a definitive list of the (affected) farms,'' 
Kiely told reporters at EU headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	Belgium made its pledge after several EU nations at meeting of  
European veterinary experts Thursday complained they lacked clear 
information from about the scope of the country's dioxin problem 
and threatened to ban Belgian foods. 
</P>
<P>
	Some EU nations have already introduced new restrictions on  
Belgian imports following revelations in the past few days that the 
dioxin contamination, first uncovered in May, may have affected 
more farms than previously thought. 
</P>
<P>
	In response, the Belgian government said this week it will  
destroy tens of thousands of tons of stockpiled meat that cannot be 
certified as dioxin-free. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest export restrictions will tighten an export  
certificate system imposed in June by the EU Commission to allow 
Belgium to resume food sales banned because of the dioxin scare. 
</P>
<P>
	The current system lets Belgium issue export certificates to  
farms not linked to the feed company believed to be the sole source 
of the dioxin contamination. Through August all animals and animal 
products for export will have to be individually tested to ensure 
they are dioxin free. 
</P>
<P>
	Dioxin is believed to have entered the food chain through motor  
oil dumped in recycled cooking fat used in the production of animal 
feeds. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
