<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Author Ponders Bailout Money By MARTIN FACKLER </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- What would you do with $60 billion?  
</P>
<P>
	For Japan's government last March, the answer was simple: bail  
out a bunch of bankers. That decision so outraged one of Japan's 
best-known writers that he has written an unusual book -- and his 
proposals are striking a chord with many readers. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryu Murakami's latest book is actually more of a list: 122 other  
ways that the $60 billion could have been put to use. 
</P>
<P>
	And while it looks like a children's book, with its big,  
colorful illustrations and simple explanations, Murakami said its 
message is anything but childish. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to give the public the information, in a very  
understandable format, so they can decide for themselves whether 
this was the best choice,'' Murakami told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	For instance, readers discover that a fraction of the money,  
about $7 billion, could teach all the illiterate children in 
developing countries how to read and write. 
</P>
<P>
	Add $6 billion, and you could also buy blankets for all the  
homeless children in those countries. And enough would still be 
left over to, say, clean up all the world's land mines for $33 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Sports fans learn that for $1 billion -- mere pocket change in  
the overall bailout scheme -- Japan could have bought the Chicago 
Bulls basketball team. 
</P>
<P>
	Fanciful as some of these ideas may be, Murakami said he hopes  
the book, entitled ``What Could That Money Have Bought?,'' will 
give readers a sense of just how big the sum is -- and get them 
thinking if it could have been better spent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just think of what Japan could have done if its banks hadn't  
lost all that money,'' Murakami said. 
</P>
<P>
	Murakami is better known at home and abroad for his novels,  
which are often violent portrayals of disillusionment in modern 
society. 
</P>
<P>
	His first, ``Almost Transparent Blue,'' sold 1.4 million copies  
and won Japan's most prestigious literary award, the Akutagawa 
Prize. He has also branched into other media, directing the recent 
movie ``Tokyo Decadence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The illustrated book, a new departure for Murakami, sold almost  
30,000 copies in the week and a half since going on sale July 19. 
The publisher, Shogakkan, says 20,000 more are being rushed to 
stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Murakami said he happened upon the idea two years ago while  
reading in the newspaper about the collapse of a large Japanese 
brokerage. An article nearby reported on a buyout offer for British 
luxury automaker Rolls-Royce. 
</P>
<P>
	Murakami said he sat up in shock when he realized the money lost  
by the brokerage was enough to buy a company as famous as 
Rolls-Royce -- not once, but four times over. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just blew up,'' he recalled. ``I hope my book draws the same  
reaction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he found most of the figures in the book by searching  
the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Murakami said he is not against the bailout in principle.  
Japan's banks are saddled with bad loans made during the 
speculative surge in land prices in the 1980s. Fixing the problem 
is viewed as a crucial step in the attempts to revive an economy 
from the worst recession since World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said he believes Tokyo lawmakers handed the money to some  
of the world's largest companies without a proper explanation to 
the taxpayers, who must ultimately foot the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``Japanese leaders don't tell the public anything. They just  
expect the public to follow,'' he said. ``A modern country like 
Japan needs better information.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even if it comes in the form of a children's book.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
