<DOCNO> APW19990730.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 13:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reed May No Longer Fit in Buffalo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. (AP) -- First, Dominik Hasek. Next up may be  
Andre Reed. 
</P>
<P>
	These are unsettling times for Buffalo sports.  
</P>
<P>
	Reed, the Buffalo Bills' leading career receiver, is an expected  
holdout with training camp about to begin. His agent says he will 
retire if the team doesn't renegotiate his contract, release him or 
trade him. 
</P>
<P>
	Retirement now appears to lead the list.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's his only option,'' Jack Wirth said Friday, a day after  
Buffalo Sabres goaltender Dominik Hasek announced from the Czech 
Republic he will retire after next season. ``They said they won't 
trade him or release him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wirth said he last spoke with Buffalo general manager John  
Butler on Thursday, with no resolution in sight. Butler was not 
immediately available for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed was a no-show for two minicamps, including a mandatory one  
in June. He is to earn $1.3 million this season, leaving the 
35-year-old receiver underpaid next to comparable players. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed recorded his 12th season of 50 or more catches last year,  
which tied him with Jerry Rice for the NFL record. Rice makes $6 
million a season. 
</P>
<P>
	Wirth would not say how much money Reed is seeking. But the  
Bills signed 36-year-old quarterback Doug Flutie, tackle Jerry 
Ostroski and defensive back Ken Irvin for money well above what 
Reed is making. 
</P>
<P>
	In 14 seasons Reed has played more games than any player in team  
history. He is third in the NFL record book with 889 receptions and 
sixth in receiving yards with 12,559. He has caught a pass in 33 
consecutive games, the team's longest streak. He missed only one 
game last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bills reportedly say they have no room under the salary cap  
for more money for Reed. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they say it's the cap, they're lying,'' Wirth told The  
Rochester Democrat and Chronicle. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed's departure could mean more playing time for second-round  
draft pick Peerless Price, set to sign a four-year contract with an 
$800,000 signing bonus this afternoon. Price is said to have fully 
recovered from a knee sprain in minicamp in April. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Moulds came on strong last year with a Pro Bowl season in  
which he broke the Bills' season record for receiving yards with 
1,368, breaking Reed's mark of 1,312 set in 1989. Moulds averaged 
20.4 yards per catch last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed had 63 catches for 795 yards and five touchdowns last year.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 10:40:24 </DATE_TIME>
