<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Stocks Close Lower; Dow Down 136.14  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks slid for a second straight session today,  
with the Dow Jones industrial average languishing behind other 
market indicators amid continuing concerns over rising interest 
rates. At the close of trading on Wall Street, the Dow was down 
136.14 points at 10,655.15, adding to a 180-point plunge yesterday. 
Broader market indexes were also lower, although their losses were 
much more moderate. The Nasdaq composite index fell 1.49 to 
2,638.52. Shares extended their losses from a selloff yesterday 
sparked when the Labor Department said its Employment Cost Index 
rose 1.1 percent in the second quarter, a bigger-than-expected 
jump. The figures are closely monitored by Federal Reserve Chairman 
Alan Greenspan. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:        10,655.15 - 136.14
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1,495  Declines 1,445  Unchgd  554
NYSE Volume:         665,135,710
Most Active NYSE issue:         America Online95 1/16  - 3 11/16
S&AMP;P 500:         1328.71 - 12.32
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          788.21  + 3.62
Nasdaq Composite Index        2,638.52  - 1.49
Gold(final) -    $256.90    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Fri.
Silver(final) -   $5.460  troy oz., NY Comex spot month Fri.

</P>
<P>
	Personal Income Soars in June  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans' personal income galloped ahead  
faster than spending in June, the government said today. New home 
sales, meanwhile, rose 3.1 percent as buyers rushed to beat slowly 
rising mortgage rates. Both reports, economists said, were an 
outgrowth of a healthy U.S. economy, a low unemployment rate, a 
strong stock market and benign inflation. Neither report was 
expected to raise eyebrows at the Federal Reserve, which nudged up 
interest rates June 30 in a pre-emptive strike against inflation, 
economists said. The Commerce Department said personal income, 
which includes wages, interest and government benefits, rose a 
faster-than-expected 0.7 percent last month. It was the biggest 
income gain since a 0.9 percent rise in November and marked the 
first time since January that income growth outpaced the rise in 
spending. 

</P>
<P>
	London Stock Exchange Makes Change  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Change is coming to the London Stock Exchange. The  
management board of Britain's largest stock market said today that 
it plans to end the LSE's 240-year status as a member-owned 
organization and transform it into a company controlled by 
shareholders. The proposal aims to make the exchange more 
competitive and efficient in an era of intensified electronic 
trading. Initial shareholders will be the exchange's 294 current 
members, but they will be able to sell their shares to third 
parties, including foreign investors. A next possible step is seen 
as listing itself as a publicly traded company. 

</P>
<P>
	Feds Urged on Airline Competition  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A government plan to crack down on predatory  
practices within the airline industry is flawed and the 
Transportation Department should take other steps to boost 
competition, says a report to Congress released today. The National 
Research Council, in a study commissioned by the department, said 
airline competition could be improved by dropping flight 
restrictions at popular airports in New York, Chicago and 
Washington, and by creating special ``congestion fees'' that would 
raise extra money for gate and terminal construction. In addition, 
the council said the federal government should end its prohibition 
against foreign investment in and ownership of U.S. airlines. 

</P>
<P>
	SBC-Ameritech Merger Clears Hurdle  
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The Indiana Supreme Court ruled today that  
state regulators have no jurisdiction over the merger between 
telephone companies SBC Communications and Ameritech. The decision 
removes one of the few remaining obstacles to completion of the 
Baby Bell merger, which has already been cleared by the Justice 
Department and Ohio state regulators. In a separate decision based 
on today's ruling, the Indiana court also said the Indiana Utility 
Regulatory Commission has no jurisdiction over the pending merger 
of Bell Atlantic and GTE. SBC stock was up 11/16 at 57 1/8 today; 
Ameritech was up 1 9/16 at 73 5/16. 

</P>
<P>
	British Newspaper Deal Worth $1.98B  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Trinity has won the battle for the Mirror Group,  
reaching a deal to acquire the publisher of the tabloid Daily 
Mirror for $1.98 billion in stock and cash. The new company, to be 
called Trinity Mirror, will be Britain's largest regional newspaper 
company, with 155 newspapers that have a weekly circulation of more 
than 15.3 million and a daily circulation of 2.3 million. The deal 
is expected to yield annual cost savings of $24 million by the end 
of 2002. 

</P>
<P>
	China Sect Claims Sites Under Attack  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Web sites in the United States and elsewhere  
devoted to the Falun Gong meditation group are coming under heavy 
electronic attack, managers of the sites said today, and at least 
one ``hacking'' attempt appears to trace back to a Chinese national 
police bureau in Beijing. Falun Gong has been banned in China, 
where communist authorities are engaged in an escalating crackdown, 
arresting adherents and confiscating publications and videos. Bob 
McWee, of Middletown, Md., a Falun Gong practitioner, said a site 
he maintains to promote the group, www.falunusa.net, has been under 
persistent electronic assault. 

</P>
<P>
	EPA To Issue new Pesticides Rules  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Environmental Protection Agency is set to  
issue new restrictions for two pesticides that are widely used on 
fruit and vegetables. Some uses of methyl parathion will be banned, 
including its application on apples and other fruit, and 
azinphos-methyl also will be restricted, according to sources 
familiar with the EPA's plans. The action stems from concerns that 
the pesticides can cause nervous system damage, especially in young 
children. 

</P>
<P>
	E. Africa Broadcast Network Planned  
</P>
<P>
	DAR ES SALAAM, Tanzania (AP) -- A Tanzanian media executive  
announced plans today to start the first East African regional 
broadcasting network by the end of the year. Reginald Mengi, chief 
of the IPP Media, said he has received broadcasting licenses from 
neighboring Kenya and Uganda. 

</P>
<P>
	North Korea To Open Casino  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian gamblers looking for thrills will soon  
have a new -- and unlikely -- place to make a few bets: communist 
North Korea. With no direct flights from anywhere in the outside 
world, it's not easy to get to the $180 million Seaview Casino 
Hotel in North Korea's Rajin economic free zone, which opens 
tomorrow. Still, the Hong Kong investor, Emperor Group, is betting 
that northern Chinese -- banned from most forms of gambling at home 
-- will flock to the four-star hotel, which offers everything from 
blackjack and roulette to slot machines. 

</P>
