<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pebble Beach Golf Course Is Sold  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- The $820 million sale of one of the  
world's most famous golf courses to a group that includes actor 
Clint Eastwood, pro golfer Arnold Palmer and former baseball 
commissioner Peter Ueberroth was finalized Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The group agreed to buy the Pebble Beach Co. in June from the  
Lone Cypress Co., a subsidiary of Japanese golf resort operator 
Taiheiyo Club Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	``With this transaction, Taiheiyo Club Inc. has fulfilled its  
commitment to return the crown jewel of golf in the United States 
to American hands,'' Taiheiyo Club president Shoichi Okochi said. 
``We are very proud to have had the opportunity to be a part of the 
history of Pebble Beach resorts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The selling price suggests Pebble Beach has recovered most of  
its value since Marvin Davis sold it in 1990 to Minoru Isutani for 
an estimated $850 million. Isutani sold it two years later to Lone 
Cypress for an estimated $500 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The new ownership group, which also includes former United  
Airlines executive Richard Ferris and the General Electric Pension 
Trust, will retain the Lone Cypress name. Bill Perocchi, a former 
executive with Doubletree Hotels and Promus Hotels, was named the 
company's chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pebble Beach Golf Links, Spyglass Hill Golf Course, The  
Links at Spanish Bay and Del Monte Golf Course changed hands in the 
deal. Also included are The Lodge at Pebble Beach, The Inn at 
Spanish Bay and the 17-mile drive that winds through Pebble Beach 
and nearby Del Monte Forest. There are also plans to develop a new 
course and build 300 homes in Pebble Beach. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
