<DOCNO> APW19990730.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 07:47:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EEOC Investigating Morgan Stanley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A Federal agency is investigating alleged gender  
discrimination at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, after an executive 
with the venerable firm filed a sex bias complaint. 
</P>
<P>
	The case involving Allison Schieffelin, a veteran saleswoman,  
comes amid growing awareness of discrimination in venerable Wall 
Street firms. 
</P>
<P>
	In charges filed with the Equal Employment Opportunity  
Commission last year, Ms. Schiefflin claims she was passed over 
repeatedly for promotions, although less qualified men received 
them, court papers show. She also alleges that Morgan Stanley 
retaliated against her for trying to raise the allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan Stanley spokeswoman Jeanmarie McFadden called the charges  
``without merit.'' She said the company is ``firmly committed to 
the issue of diversity in the workplace'' and does not tolerate 
discrimination. 
</P>
<P>
	The EEOC took Morgan Stanley to Federal District Court in  
Manhattan on Wednesday, seeking a court order to force the company 
to turn over information about women's pay and promotion policies, 
Ms. Schiefflin's lawyer said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The EEOC took the action because Morgan Stanley did not comply  
with a February subpoena seeking the data. A person close to Morgan 
Stanley, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the information 
sought by the EEOC was ``irrevelant'' to the case. 
</P>
<P>
	``The issue is, at one level, the glass ceiling syndrome on Wall  
Street that everybody knows is there,'' said Ms. Schieffelin's 
lawyer, Wayne Outten. 
</P>
<P>
	The EEOC supervisory trial attorney handling the case, Elizabeth  
Grossman, said her New York office has been receiving more 
discrimination complaints involving Wall Street. She didn't give 
any details. 
</P>
<P>
	According to court papers and Outten, Ms. Schiefflin was passed  
over for the position of managing director in 1996 and 1998. In 
March 1998, her boss told her that she probably would never be 
promoted to the position, Outten said. 
</P>
<P>
	Outten said that Ms. Schieffelin planned to stay at the firm,  
and hoped that her action would result in her promotion to managing 
director. ``She's interested in trying to change the organization, 
have them present a level playing field for her and other women,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1995, Ms. Schieffelin had complained in writing that her  
boss discriminated against women, Outten said. She had also filed 
internal sexual harassment charges that Outten said were handled 
properly by Morgan Stanley in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Her complaint to the EEOC also charges that Morgan Stanley tried  
to force the matter before an industry arbitration panel to prevent 
Ms. Schieffelin from filing a discrimination lawsuit. The New York 
Stock Exchange, however, rejected Morgan Stanley's attempt. 
</P>
<P>
	In a high-profile case against a Wall Street firm, eight women  
sued the nation's largest brokerage in February 1997 on behalf of 
the company's female financial consultants. 
</P>
<P>
	A settlement was reached in September 1998 allowing 2,900 women  
who worked at Merrill Lynch between January 1994 through June 1998 
to file discrimination claims to be heard by mediators. 
</P>
<P>
	In an internal memo distributed in early June, the company said  
acknowledged that some of the claims appear to have merit. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
