<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Upholds Decision in Code Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A federal appeals court on Friday upheld a  
district court ruling blocking the sale of an Avant! Corp. software 
program allegedly produced using copyrighted code belonging to 
Cadence Design Systems Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. District Court issued a preliminary injunction blocking  
Avant! from selling its Aquarius software, based on the likelihood 
that Cadence would be able to prove it was produced with 
misappropriated code, and that the program infringed on the Cadence 
copyright. 
</P>
<P>
	The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed with the district  
court and upheld an injunction barring the sale of Aquarius, a 
program used to design computer circuits. Both companies make such 
software 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's ruling said the district court properly applied the law  
and had its own expert examine the software, then cited several of 
the ``strongest examples'' of duplication. Avant! argued that just 
56 lines of code were cited, calling that a very minimal 
duplication. 
</P>
<P>
	But the appeals court said the district court ruling cited only  
the strongest examples, but did not say those were the only 
similarities. 
</P>
<P>
	``The 9th Circuit decided that Judge (Ronald M.) Whyte was right  
in enjoining the sale of Aquarius,'' said Michael Page, one of the 
attorneys representing Cadence. 
</P>
<P>
	Cadence sued Avant!, claiming some former employees took the  
code with them when they left Cadence between 1990 and 1995 to join 
the company which later became Avant! 
</P>
<P>
	Page said the trial on that suit is scheduled for Oct. 12 in  
federal court in San Jose. 
</P>
<P>
	George Riley, attorney for Avant!, would not immediately  
comment. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
