<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 00:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Navy Has Backlog of Burials at Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Navy will be sending a flotilla of ships  
to sea in a rush program to eliminate a backlog in burials at sea. 
The backlog was brought to light by the Navy's prompt burial of 
John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife and sister-in-law. 
</P>
<P>
	After the well-publicized burial off the Massachusetts coast  
July 22, the Navy fielded complaints from families who have 
deceased loved ones awaiting burial at sea, a privilege of sailors, 
veterans, their spouses and dependent children. 
</P>
<P>
	The Navy has 52 sets of remains in storage awaiting burial, some  
for several months, Rear Adm. Craig Quigley, a Pentagon spokesman, 
said Thursday. All but three of those are in storage at Portsmouth 
Naval Medical Center, Va. The rest are at Navy facilities on the 
West Coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Adm. J.P. Reason, commander of the U.S. Atlantic Fleet, ordered  
immediate action to eliminate the backlog after he learned of it, 
Quigley said. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was completely unacceptable to him and he's working very  
hard to remove that backlog,'' Quigley said. ``Everyone involved in 
that would admit that this was not done very well and there's no 
really good reason for having that backlog there in the first 
place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The burials of Kennedy, his wife, Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, and  
her sister Lauren Bessette occurred a day after their bodies were 
found in the waters off Martha's Vineyard, Mass., following the 
July 16 crash of Kennedy's private plane. Asked why the burials 
were handled without delay, Quigley said it was a case of an 
``unusual circumstance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The destroyer USS Briscoe was at sea off the East Coast as the  
search for the Kennedy plane was under way. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because of the ability to be timely in that request, that was  
the decision that was made to send her north to accomplish the 
burials of those three at sea,'' Quigley said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 10 ships will be involved in relieving the backlog of  
sea burials by Aug. 6. The only remains that won't be buried by 
then will be those for which families have requested a later date 
or set other special conditions, such as a specific burial location 
requiring more time, Quigley said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Navy said that no ships will be sent to sea just for burials  
but will conduct the ceremonies while deployed for other missions. 
The Navy blamed the backlog on several factors, including a reduced 
fleet and increased demands on remaining ships to participate in 
various operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Sailors, retired Navy officers and enlistees, their spouses and  
dependent children are entitled to burial at sea. With special 
approval, as in the Kennedy case, others may also receive Navy 
burial rites at sea. 
</P>
<P>
	The service is free, although family members must prepare either  
a casket or cremated remains in containers that fit Navy 
specifications. Unlike in the Kennedy case, family members are not 
allowed to attend the rites, according to Navy Capt. Ryland Dodge 
of the Navy's Bureau of Medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	About 90 percent of the remains the Navy buries at sea are  
cremated. The Navy handles about 500 burials at sea each year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 07:30:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woodstock Rape Reports Investigated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME, N.Y. (AP) -- Rape counselors and crisis intervention  
workers say they treated far more sexual assault victims than the 
four reported to police during the Woodstock '99 festival. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities are investigating reports of rapes during the  
three-day concert, attended by an estimated 225,000 fans. 
</P>
<P>
	Sandy Lattimore, emergency services director of the Rome office  
of the American Red Cross, said she and her staff treated multiple 
victims of sexual assaults. Rosemary Vennero, crisis service 
director of the YWCA of Mohawk Valley, said her organization's rape 
crisis center had counseled four sexual assault victims. 
</P>
<P>
	The Oneida County Rape Crisis Center on Thursday reported that  
two other teen-age girls have come forward with allegations that 
they were raped. State Police Capt. John Wood said investigators 
were braced for additional reports of sexual assaults because 
victims typically do not come forward immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	Vennero said readily available drugs and alcohol, inattentive  
security and other factors for creating an atmosphere conducive to 
sexual assault -- ``I mean anything from groping, touching and 
molesting to rape and sodomy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the alleged rapes occurred in a mosh pit 30 yards away  
from the stage, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mosh pits are a place where concertgoers, usually boys and young  
men, hurl their bodies against each other in a release of 
aggression. 
</P>
<P>
	A woman said she was ``bodysurfing'' in the crowd when she was  
pulled into the pit, molested by two men and raped by another. 
</P>
<P>
	``Due to the congestion of the crowd, she felt that if she  
yelled for help or fought, she feared she was going to be beaten,'' 
a state police investigation report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Woodstock promoters Michael Lang and John Scher said they could  
not confirm the rapes had occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	``If, indeed, these reports are true, it is despicable,'' said  
Woodstock spokeswoman Ilene Marder. 
</P>
<P>
	The rape reports represented more bad publicity for the  
festival, meant to evoke the 1969 Woodstock and its ``peace and 
music'' theme. Fans rioted and burned property at the concert as 
the festival came to a close on Sunday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
