<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Firms Fined $28M in Age Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An insurance brokerage and employee benefits  
firm will pay $28 million to settle government claims that it 
discriminated by making members of its board of directors retire at 
age 62. 
</P>
<P>
	The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission said Thursday that  
Johnson and Higgins Inc. had agreed to settle a 1993 lawsuit filed 
by the federal government. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson and Higgins, which had 7,000 workers nationwide,  
allegedly enforced a mandatory retirement policy before it was 
acquired by Marsh &AMP; McLennan Companies Inc. two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Barbara Perlmutter, vice president of public affairs for Marsh &AMP;  
McLennan, said the company was ``pleased to have this matter behind 
us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said there was no such policy at Marsh &AMP; McLennan, which  
employs 50,000 people in more than 100 countries in insurance 
services, investment management and consulting. 
</P>
<P>
	The money will be divided among 13 retired Johnson and Higgins  
directors, with $100,000 going to the EEOC to cover the costs of 
the suit. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
