<DOCNO> APW19990730.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 14:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Greene Just Misses 100-Meter Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- Maurice Greene ran one of the fastest  
100 meters ever Friday, surging from the blocks and winning in 9.87 
seconds at the DN Galan Grand Prix meet. 
</P>
<P>
	With almost no wind, Greene was just eight-hundredths of a  
second off the world record he set last month in Greece. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just thrills me how well I'm running at the moment,''  
Greene said. ``This is a special stadium, a special meet. But it 
was not even close to a perfect race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Johnson had a far rougher day. The double Olympic  
champion in 1996 abandoned the 400-meter race after about 100 
meters, apparently pulling a right thigh muscle. Jerome Young of 
the United States won in 44.64. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not the way I would have wanted to win with Michael  
having to pull out,'' Young said. ``But a win is a win. I just 
concentrated on my own race and I never was aware that Michael 
stopped.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson left the stadium without comment and with a bandaged  
right thigh. 
</P>
<P>
	Marion Jones was unchallenged in the women's 200, leading from  
start to finish. The American's time of 22.07 was .05 off the 
stadium record. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think my race was anything special this evening,''  
Jones said. ``I felt very good coming off the turn of the bend, but 
I can't point to any other part of the race other than that which 
stands out in my mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to prize and appearance money, Greene earned a  
diamond valued at $10,000 for breaking his Olympic Stadium record 
of 9.90 set last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Obadele Thompson of Barbados was second in 9.96 and Greene's  
training partner Jon Drummond third in 10.04. Dennis Mitchell, 
another American, finished fourth in 10.05. 
</P>
<P>
	Ato Boldon of Trinidad, one of Greene's training partners, did  
not enter because of injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without Ato here to push me, I am particularly pleased with  
how I stepped up my game and pushed myself to this sort of time,'' 
Greene said. ``With Ato in the race, the competition would have 
been even stiffer and then who knows what might have happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boldon was timed in 9.86 in Athens, the fifth-fastest time in  
history, when Greene broke the world record. 
</P>
<P>
	Merlene Ottey, the 39-year-old veteran from Jamaica, finished  
second to Jones in 22.24. Inger Miller of the United States was 
third in 22.50. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was my first race this year 200 against Merlene and  
frankly every race against her is a keen contest,'' Jones said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ludmila Engquist was impressive in her first race since being  
diagnosed with breast cancer, taking the women's 100 hurdles in 
12.68. 
</P>
<P>
	Colin Jackson, the world-record holder from Britain, beat two  
Americans to win the men's 110 hurdles in 13.12 
</P>
<P>
	Engquist, who is undergoing chemotherapy, edged Melissa Morrison  
of the United States by one-hundredth of a second in excellent 
conditions before a sellout crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt the whole of Sweden was with me today and with that  
kind of support I knew I couldn't fail,'' said Engquist, a former 
Russian citizen who competes for Sweden. 
</P>
<P>
	The Olympic champion three years ago in Atlanta, Engquist  
recently returned from training in Spain. 
</P>
<P>
	``All my fans are responsible for this win,'' Engquist said.  
``They have kept going with me throughout my illness and the 
crowd's reaction was just so amazing even before the race 
started.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sharon Jewell of the United States, was third in 12.73.  
</P>
<P>
	Mark Crear, who's fastest this year in 12.98, was second behind  
Jackson in 13.13, with Tony Dees third in 13.36. 
</P>
<P>
	``During the last few weeks I have been trying to concentrate on  
being Colin Jackson and to forget my weaknesses,'' Jackson said. 
``This was one of my best performances here in Stockholm. 
Especially my start was good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Christopher Koskei of Kenya won the men's 3,000 steeplechase in  
8:10.71 and Maria Mutola of Moazmbique won the women's 800 in 
1:57.12. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 08:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tripp Wiretap Indictment Uncertain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ELLICOTT CITY, Md. (AP) -- As the yearlong grand jury  
investigation of Linda Tripp's secret tape recordings drew to a 
close, the state prosecutor appeared at the courthouse today, 
refusing to say whether he would seek an indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tripp's attorney, Joseph Murtha, was preparing for the  
possibility of an indictment on wiretapping charges. He said, 
however, he had not been notified by state prosecutors that charges 
were imminent. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Murtha asked that if Mrs. Tripp is indicted, she  
be allowed to surrender voluntarily, rather than being arrested at 
her Columbia, Md., home. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard County State's Attorney Marna McLendon scheduled a press  
conference about the Tripp investigation for this afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Family spokesman Philip Coughter said Mrs. Tripp's legal team  
will hold a news briefing after McLendon finishes. Coughter also 
said Mrs. Tripp's attorneys are bringing on board Steve Kohn, a 
Washington attorney with experience in government whistle-blower 
cases. 
</P>
<P>
	``We expect the grand jury to hopefully come to some  
conclusion,'' Maryland state prosecutor Stephen Montanarelli, who 
has been presenting evidence in the probe to a Howard County grand 
jury, said as he entered the county courthouse. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tripp secretly tape-recorded telephone calls she had with  
Monica Lewinsky, triggering the biggest crisis of Clinton's 
presidency. But Mrs. Tripp's taping may have violated Maryland's 
wiretap law. 
</P>
<P>
	If Mrs. Tripp is indicted, she would become the only central  
figure in the Lewinsky affair to face criminal charges. Clinton was 
acquitted in a Senate impeachment trial on charges of perjury and 
obstruction of justice. 
</P>
<P>
	A peripheral figure in the investigation, Julie Hiatt Steele,  
was prosecuted for obstructing prosecutor Kenneth Starr's probe of 
Clinton. But the jury deadlocked on the charges and Starr elected 
not to retry the case. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Mrs. Tripp's tape recordings, which she supplied Starr's  
office under a grant of immunity from prosecution, that started the 
investigation of the president and led to his impeachment in the 
House. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tripp's federal immunity does not protect her in a state  
case. 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland law forbids anyone from intercepting phone  
conversations without the other party's consent. Wiretapping is 
punishable by up to five years in prison and a $10,000 fine for 
each offense. 
</P>
<P>
	Ignorance of the law is a valid defense. But Mrs. Tripp  
testified for Starr that she taped several conversations in late 
1997 even after an attorney told her it was illegal. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tripp, 49, said she began taping her phone calls because  
she was being pressured by Ms. Lewinsky to lie in the Paula Jones 
sexual harassment case against the president. Ms. Lewinsky, who 
became friends with Mrs. Tripp when they worked at the Pentagon, 
wanted Mrs. Tripp to deny knowledge of a sexual relationship 
between Clinton and the former White House intern. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0152 </DOCNO>
