<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Domestic Partners To Get Benefits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A federal appeals court Friday refused to  
exempt airlines from the city ordinance requiring companies to 
offer benefits to employees' domestic partners. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling from the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals means the  
airlines must begin Monday to offer bereavement leave, family 
medical leave and spousal flight discounts to San Francisco 
domestic partners. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours later, United Airlines announced it would offer benefits  
to domestic partners of employees and retirees elsewhere in the 
country beginning next May. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're not doing it out of the goodness of their hearts,''  
said Deputy City Attorney Marc Slavin. ``But it's gratifying that 
they have finally come around to the conclusion that offering equal 
benefits makes good business sense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The city law, which took effect in 1997, requires companies  
doing business with the city to offer the same benefits to 
employees' domestic partners as they do to employees' spouses. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, a federal judge directed the airlines to comply with  
portions of the law for their employees in San Francisco, although 
she exempted the companies from the ordinance's pension and health 
benefits requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	The airlines appealed the decision, asking for a temporary  
exemption during the appellate process. Friday's ruling rejected 
that request. The appeal is ongoing. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we have said from the very outset, this case has never been  
about gay and lesbian rights,'' said United Chairman and CEO James 
Goodwin. ``What we oppose -- and what we will continue to oppose -- 
are local municipalities intruding upon the federal domain by 
attempting to legislate the employee benefits package of companies 
like airlines doing business nationwide.'' 
</P>
<P>
	United employs 20,000 people in San Francisco.  


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
