<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Senate Passes Tax Cut Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Republicans today pushed through a $792  
billion tax cut package that sets up a showdown with the White 
House over how best to make use of big budget surpluses. The vote 
was 57-43. ``It helps the family and it helps the country,'' said 
the Senate Finance Committee chairman, Sen. William Roth, R-Del., 
author of the 10-year plan. President Clinton has said he would 
veto any measure that closely resembles the Senate bill or a 
similar House measure because the tax cuts are too large and 
endanger the nation's economic well-being. 

</P>
<P>
	Police Reveal Atlanta Shooting Note  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- In a note left explaining the violence that  
killed his family and nine people at two brokerage firms, Mark O. 
Barton said he killed his daughter and his 11-year-old son with 
hammer blows, then pulled the bedcovers to their chins and tucked 
their favorite toys beside them. The note did not directly discuss 
yesterday's slayings at the two brokerage firms, but did refer to 
greedy people. ``I don't plan to live very much longer, just long 
enough to kill ... the people that greedily sought my 
destruction,'' he wrote. 

</P>
<P>
	Tripp Indicted on Wiretap Charge  
</P>
<P>
	ELLICOTT CITY, Md. (AP) -- A grand jury indicted Linda Tripp  
today for secretly taping her phone conversations with Monica 
Lewinsky, charging she broke Maryland wiretapping laws. Mrs. Tripp 
becomes the only central figure in the Lewinsky scandal to face 
criminal charges. State Prosecutor Stephen Montanarelli said the 
grand jury indicted Mrs. Tripp on one count of illegal interception 
of a phone conversation on Dec. 22, 1997, after her lawyer 
allegedly told her the taping was illegal. The other count is for 
allegedly disclosing the contents of that conversation to Newsweek 
magazine. 

</P>
<P>
	World Leaders Pledge Balkan Reforms  
</P>
<P>
	SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- In a city symbolizing both  
war and rebirth, world leaders pledged today to help bring 
prosperity and freedom to struggling Balkan countries and build a 
Europe ``at long last undivided, democratic and at peace.'' The 
summit of nearly 40 nations underscored the isolation of 
Yugoslavia's Slobodan Milosevic, blamed for four wars that killed 
more than 250,000. ``I do not believe that we should give 
reconstruction aid to Serbia as long as it rejects democracy and as 
long as Mr. Milosevic is in power,'' President Clinton said. ``We 
have had enough of ethnic cleansing.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Heat Wave Death Toll Climbs to 79  
</P>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The worst drought in a decade has seized  
the Northeast, withering crops, feeding forest fires and sucking 
streams and lakes so dry that Baltimore has only a month's worth of 
drinking water in its reservoirs. At least 79 deaths in 14 states 
have been blamed on the heat wave that has gripped much of country 
since July 19. Missouri has the highest death toll at 27. 

</P>
<P>
	NTSB: No JFK Jr. Plane Fire  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The wreckage of John F. Kennedy Jr.'s plane  
showed no signs of in-flight breakup or fire, and the engine 
appeared to have been working when the aircraft plunged into the 
ocean, The National Transportation Safety Board said today. The 
board also said that Kennedy had received a weather forecast via 
the Internet for his flight. The report, issued about two hours 
before takeoff, was for good visual-flight-rules conditions, with 
six to eight miles visibility. No weather warnings were issued to 
other pilots flying Kennedy's route. 

</P>
<P>
	Personal Income Soars in June  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans' personal income galloped ahead  
faster than spending in June, the government said today and new 
home sales rose 3.1 percent as buyers rushed to beat slowly rising 
mortgage rates. Both reports, economists said, are an outgrowth of 
a healthy U.S. economy, a low unemployment rate, a strong stock 
market and benign inflation. Neither report is expected to raise 
eyebrows at the Federal Reserve, which nudged up interest rates 
June 30, economists said. But financial markets are jittery about 
the possibility of further rate increases. 

</P>
