<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reds 7, Giants 4  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Denny Neagle went through eight months, seven  
starts and two stints on the disabled list before finally getting a 
win for the Cincinnati Reds. 
</P>
<P>
	Neagle gave up three solo homers -- two by Barry Bonds -- but the  
Reds used a big first inning and a couple of solo homers of their 
own to beat the San Francisco Giants 7-4 Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	It was 103 degrees downtown at the first pitch, and the humidity  
made it feel like 111 degrees on Cincinnati's hottest day since 
1988. 
</P>
<P>
	Neagle (1-3) gave up six hits and struck out five as he held out  
in the heat for 5 2-3 innings and 95 pitches. The left-hander was 
rushed back from his latest minor league rehab stint and activated 
off the disabled list Friday to help an injury-thinned rotation. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Reds got Neagle from Atlanta last Nov. 10 in a  
five-player deal that included Bret Boone, they figured he'd become 
their No. 1 starter. Instead, he spent two stints on the disabled 
list with shoulder weakness and went 0-3 in six starts from April 
21 to May 19. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory was Neagle's first since last Sept. 26 with Atlanta.  
Appropriately, it came against the Giants -- Neagle is 10-1 career 
against San Francisco, including 8-0 in his last 10 starts. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds, one of three Giants who got contract extensions before  
the game, hit solo homers in each of his first two at-bats, but the 
Giants couldn't overcome a four-run first inning off Mark Gardner 
(3-9). 
</P>
<P>
	Barry Larkin had three hits and Mike Cameron and Eddie Taubensee  
hit solo homers as the Reds got their sixth victory in seven games. 
Cincinnati improved to a season-high 17 games over .500 at 59-42. 
</P>
<P>
	After retiring the first two batters in the first, Gardner hit  
Sean Casey, walked Greg Vaughn, gave up an RBI single to Larkin and 
then walked Taubensee and Aaron Boone to force in another run. 
Chris Stynes followed with a two-run single. 
</P>
<P>
	Cameron led off the second with his 12th homer and Taubensee hit  
his 11th homer off Gardner with two outs in the fifth for a 7-3 
lead. Gardner has given up 21 homers, the most on the Giants' 
staff. 
</P>
<P>
	After Gabe White gave up an RBI double to Stan Javier with one  
out in the San Francisco ninth, Scott Williamson came in and got 
the final two outs for his 15th save. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the game, the Giants agreed to a four-year contract with  
first baseman J.T. Snow, who was eligible for free agency after the 
season. They also exercised Bonds' option for 2001 and Jeff Kent's 
option for 2002, keeping both of them under contract for another 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds homered in each of his first two at-bats, his second  
multihomer game of the season and the 35th of his career. He has 
hit 26 homers in Cincinnati, the second-most by a visiting player. 
Hall of Famer Mike Schmidt hit 29. 
</P>
<P>
	Rich Aurilia also homered off Neagle, who has allowed 11 homers  
in 31 innings this season. With the win Friday, Neagle's earned run 
average shrunk from 8.17 to 7.55. 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Bonds is 13-for-37 career off Neagle with five homers. ...  
Aurilia's homer was his 16th, leaving him one shy of the San 
Francisco record for a shortstop. Darryl Spencer hit 17 in 1958. 
... Gardner gave up 29 homers last season, ninth-most in the NL. 
... Reds second baseman Pokey Reese had more tests on his bruised 
left hand Friday that found no fracture. He was hit by a pitch last 
Monday and hasn't played since. ... Steve Parris, who was scratched 
from his start Friday because of a strained shoulder muscle, played 
catch Friday and reported improvement. ... Reds reliever Stan 
Belinda singled in the sixth off Gardner, his first hit since Sept. 
7, 1997. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
