<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Laura Bush Campaigns for Husband </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Flying solo for the first time on the  
campaign trail, Laura Bush says one of her husband's big strengths 
is that he satisfies a yearning from voters for politicians who 
``won't embarrass them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I do think that's something Americans are interested in now,''  
Mrs. Bush, the wife of Texas governor and GOP presidential hopeful 
George W. Bush, said in an interview with The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	She was stressing character themes in her public appearances in  
Iowa, and repeated it during the interview. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if it's the core theme,'' she said. ``I think  
Americans want somebody who they do trust, who they feel like won't 
embarrass them, but instead will make them proud.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Mrs. Bush, who interrupted a family vacation in  
Kennebunkport, Maine, for the campaign swing, also pleaded for 
privacy. She conceded that virtually every move the Bush family 
makes will come under the glare of scrutiny, but argued for limits. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the same time, I hope we'll have some privacy,'' she said.  
``I think the American people think their leaders ought to have a 
little privacy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Mrs. Bush has been active on her husband's behalf in Texas  
and has traveled the country with him, she was on her own for the 
first time in a two-day swing through the state where precinct 
caucuses launch the presidential nominating season. 
</P>
<P>
	She pledged to keep an active campaign schedule, but said it  
will be limited by having twin daughters entering their senior year 
in high school. ``Because we have two girls who are seniors who 
will have a very busy year with school and college applications, 
I'll be at home, but I'll also campaign,'' Mrs. Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	She said her daughters should be exempt from public scrutiny  
because they won't be part of the campaign. ``I think everyone 
understands that our daughters aren't running for office,'' she 
said. ``They won't be campaigning with us and we won't be using 
them in television ads, for instance. They want a private life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Bush said the decision to make the run was made easier by  
the couple's experience during former President Bush's term. ``One 
thing that really reassured us about George running for president 
is we've seen a family in the biggest job as parents,'' she said. 
``We know that we had a private family life with them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Bush said her role would be as surrogate, not an adviser.  
``We don't really talk about politics that much,'' she said. ``Like 
every family we talk about our children, our plans for the 
weekend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The character issues that were her focus draw a less-than-subtle  
contrast with sex scandals that have rocked the Clinton White 
House. 
</P>
<P>
	``Governor Bush has represented Texas with dignity and honor,''  
Mrs. Bush said. ``I'd love to see him do the same thing for our 
nation in its highest office.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After speaking with activists, Mrs. Bush, a former elementary  
school teacher, went to an inner-city elementary school, where she 
read to second-graders and chatted with fifth-graders, underscoring 
the theme of her visit. 
</P>
<P>
	In her speeches, Mrs. Bush talked about education, but the most  
interest was in what she called ``our partnership,'' which hasn't 
gotten heavy public scrutiny. 
</P>
<P>
	``Marrying him was apparently the smartest political move that I  
ever made, not bad for somebody who didn't know anything about 
politics,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
