<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giants' Sehorn Under Microscope </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Stung by criticism from teammates and his  
coach, New York Giants cornerback Jason Sehorn on Friday defended 
his decision to rehabilitate his surgically repaired right knee on 
his own. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it offended somebody, I really don't care because they are  
not the people I have to worry about while rehabing,'' Sehorn said 
after the Giants' first training camp practice. ``I'm the person I 
have to worry about. If everybody likes me and I can't play 
football, it does me a lot of good. 
</P>
<P>
	``I also know this, if I can play football again, no one will  
care what I did in the offseason,'' the 28-year-old added. 
</P>
<P>
	Sehorn's status for this season is one of the big question marks  
as the Giants look to rebound from an 8-8 season that saw them miss 
the playoffs a year after winning the NFC East. 
</P>
<P>
	Sehorn's absence was a part of that fall. One of the NFL's best  
cover corners, he missed the year after tearing a knee ligament 
returning a kickoff against the New York Jets in an exhibition game 
in August. 
</P>
<P>
	While many have wondered whether he would be able to regain the  
form that allowed him to intercept six passes in 1997 and to 
usually take an opponent's top receiver out of the offense, there 
have been other concerns in the offseason. 
</P>
<P>
	Unidentified teammates were quoted as being upset that Sehorn  
worked out on his own in California and criticized him for being a 
loner who didn't get along with everyone. They were also upset he 
didn't participate with them in the offseason workout program. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last time I checked, I wasn't a loner. I just do my own  
thing,'' Sehorn said. ``I don't see that as a problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even coach Jim Fassel was upset that Sehorn missed voluntary  
workouts at Giants Stadium during the summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Sehorn took the blame for that one with an excuse. He was in the  
process of going through a divorce with his wife, Whitney. 
</P>
<P>
	The comments from teammates hurt though, particularly ones  
attributed to defensive end Michael Strahan about missing the 
offseason workouts. The two have since met and things are OK, 
Sehorn said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only thing that frustrated me was seeing myself getting  
beaten up for getting myself in shape on my own,'' Sehorn said. ``I 
wasn't healthy and I had to do something different. I have the 
confidence in my ability that I was doing what was best for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sehorn's rehabilitation plan involved hiring personal strength  
and running coaches as well as a nutrition consultant. Most of his 
free time he spent alone. He returned to camp bigger and stronger, 
weighing in at 219 pounds, four pounds above the team's target 
weight. 
</P>
<P>
	Sehorn only worked out on a limited basis on Friday. He strained  
a hamstring running last week and Fassel does not want to push him 
until he is ready. It is expected that he will practice next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Sehorn understands that it's more important to be ready for  
Sept. 12, the season opener at Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	Before that, he knows he has to prove himself again on the  
field. He's done it working out on his own, and the knee had 
responded well. In games, opposing receivers will dictate his 
movements and that cannot be simulated. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know I can play,'' Sehorn said. ``I just have to do it to  
answer the questions in my own mind, as well as everybody else's.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And if Sehorn does, no one will question the other areas of his  
life. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you go 8-8 and have a lot of problems, there is a whole  
lot of things written about that aren't football related,'' Sehorn 
said. ``When you go 12-4 and go the playoffs and do well, people 
leave those things alone.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
