<DOCNO> APW19990730.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 21:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Note Surfaces From Atlanta Killer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The gunman who killed nine people at two  
brokerage firms had lost roughly $105,000 in stock trading in less 
than two months and left a note vowing revenge on those who had 
``greedily sought my destruction,'' authorities said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark O. Barton, a chemist turned day stock-trader, walked  
Thursday into the office of two brokerage firms where he traded and 
fired randomly at traders and employees. Nine died and 13 were 
wounded, with five still in critical condition Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours later, he killed himself as police pulled over his van. In  
the van, police found the two guns used in the shooting, two 
additional handguns, 200 rounds of ammunition and two pairs of 
handcuffs. 
</P>
<P>
	His wife, son and daughter were found bludgeoned in the family  
residence. In his note, left in the apartment and released Friday 
by police, he said he wanted to spare his children a ``lifetime of 
pain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barton also denied killing his first wife and mother-in-law in  
1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Barton had taken out a $600,000 life insurance policy on his  
first wife two months before she was killed. Authorities said 
Barton was the prime suspect in the bludgeoning of Debra Spivey 
Barton and Eloise Powell Spivey at an Alabama campground, but he 
was never charged. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no reason for me to lie now,'' he wrote.  
</P>
<P>
	Barton settled with the insurance company for $450,000,  
according to federal court records. Of that, $150,000 was to be 
held by Barton for his children. 
</P>
<P>
	After the rest was divided among Barton's lawyers and his  
children's temporary guardian, Barton was left with about $194,000. 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear whether Barton had used the insurance money to  
begin his stock-trading career. In a client profile Barton 
submitted to one of the brokerages, he claimed a net worth of 
$750,000 that excluded his residence, and an annual income of 
$85,000. 
</P>
<P>
	In the note found with the bodies, he referred to an  
overpowering fear that drove him to murder, but contained no 
references to his recent financial losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at Momentum Securities said Barton traded at the  
Atlanta office for a total of 15 days beginning June 9, and the 
trading resulted in an approximate $105,000 loss. All-Tech 
Investment Group would not release any details of his trading. 
</P>
<P>
	His latest loss -- $20,000 -- occurred Tuesday, according to a  
brokerage source that demanded anonymity. Authorities say they 
believe he killed his wife Tuesday and his children on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wake up at night so afraid, so terrified that I couldn't be  
that afraid while awake. It has taken its toll,'' Barton wrote. ``I 
have come to hate this life and this system of things. I have come 
to have no hope.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He killed his family by hitting them with a hammer while they  
slept and holding them underwater in the tub to make sure they 
wouldn't wake up. Later, he tucked the children's bodies into bed 
with their favorite toys. 
</P>
<P>
	Barton's note focused mostly on his 11-year-old son, Matthew,  
and 7-year-old daughter, Mychelle. 
</P>
<P>
	``I killed the children to exchange them for five minutes of  
pain for a lifetime of pain,'' he wrote. ``I forced myself to do it 
to keep them from suffering so much later.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dave M. Davis, a forensic psychiatrist and director of the  
psychiatric clinic at Piedmont Hospital in Atlanta, said Barton's 
letter indicates he was severely depressed and paranoid. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we have these multiple murderers, who are quite different  
from serial killers, they tend to kill people like themselves,'' 
Davis said, noting Barton killed other stock traders. 
</P>
<P>
	Barton was worried that his mental problems would be passed on.  
</P>
<P>
	``The fears of the father are transferred to the son. It was  
from my father to me and from me to my son,'' he said. ``I had to 
take him with me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The notes, written on Thursday, also said: ``I don't plan to  
live very much longer. Just long enough to kill as many of the 
people that greedily sought my destruction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the shooting spree in Atlanta's Buckhead commercial  
district, Barton fled to the city's northern suburbs. 
</P>
<P>
	He shot himself in the head when he was cornered by police about  
five hours after the manhunt began. 
</P>
<P>
	The bizarre letter left an image of a person far different from  
the doting father and Boy Scout volunteer that neighbors described. 
He did homework with his son and stayed up late playing video games 
with his children. 
</P>
<P>
	Neighbors were shocked to see his photo all over TV Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	Sabrina Stowers, a former neighbor in Morrow, said Barton never  
seemed stressed, even though he worked in the pressure-cooker world 
of day trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Barton drove Matthew and Ms. Stower's son, Brian, to Boy Scouts  
every Tuesday, she said. And he would play video games with the 
boys during sleepovers, always getting them to school on time the 
next day. 
</P>
<P>
	Kent Woerner, principal of McGarrah Elementary School in Morrow,  
said Barton was active and concerned with his children's education. 
Despite their mother's murder, the children never exhibited 
emotional problems, Woerner said. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Hauptman, Barton's former criminal lawyer, said the  
gunman was a knowledgeable chemist who could have taken even more 
lives than he did. 
</P>
<P>
	``While this thing is tragic, I don't think the city realizes  
how lucky we are,'' Hauptman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``With his extensive knowledge of chemistry and the availability  
of chemicals on the open market, he could have walked into that 
building with a homemade bomb sufficient to blow up the whole 
building.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
