<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 17:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Fall; Dow Drops 136.14 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks sank for a second straight  
session Friday, languishing behind broader market measures, as 
worries about higher interest rates sapped enthusiasm for highly 
priced stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average fell 136.14 points to close at  
10,655.15, adding to a 180-point plunge Thursday. It was the lowest 
close since June 28. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip index tumbled 255.81 points, or 2.3 percent, for  
the week and dropped 2.9 percent for the month of July. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader market indexes posted more moderate losses. The Standard  
&AMP; Poor's 500 fell 12.31 to 1,328.72, and the Nasdaq composite index 
dipped 1.52 to 2,638.49. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes only the blue-chips count, and if you measure by the  
Dow, it's another lousy day for the market,'' said Barry Hyman, 
senior equity analyst at Ehrenkrantz King Nussbaum. Still, the Dow 
is up 16.2 percent so far this year, well above the modest 
expectations of analysts when the year began. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's selloff was an extension of a slump sparked Thursday  
when the Labor Department said its Employment Cost Index rose 1.1 
percent in the second quarter, a bigger-than-expected jump. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists said the data, closely monitored by Federal Reserve  
Chairman Alan Greenspan, could encourage the Fed to raise interest 
rates when its policy-making Federal Open Market Committee meets on 
Aug. 24. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed raised interest rates in June and has signaled its  
willingness to do so again in an effort to contain inflation. In 
the meantime, Wall Street players are carefully watching all fresh 
economic data. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday offered a full plate of new figures that provided the  
impetus for more selling. A report from the Commerce Department 
showed that Americans' personal income surged in June and outpaced 
spending, but the nation's savings rate remains near a record low. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate report, the Commerce Department said sales of new  
single-family homes rebounded in June, rising 3.1 percent, better 
than forecast. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Friday, the National Association of Purchasing Management's  
Chicago branch reported that manufacturing activity in that region 
of the country area accelerated at a faster-than-expected pace in 
July. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond markets, already retreating before the figures came out,  
fell further on the news. Yields on 30-year Treasury bonds rose to 
6.10 percent from 6.07 percent late Thursday. On Thursday, the rise 
in yields was even steeper. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial stocks continued to slide Friday under the threat of  
higher rates. Dow components American Express tumbled 6 13/16 to 
131 3/4 and J.P. Morgan dropped 2 3/4 to 127 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bond investors are already jittery and when you give them an  
excuse to sell, they sell,'' said Anthony O'Bryan, a market analyst 
at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis. ``And when bonds are down, 
that throws a wet blanket on the financial sector.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since the prospect of a second interest-rate increase hit the  
market last week, investors have gravitated away from many highly 
priced stocks, which may become less appealing when rising 
borrowing costs begin cutting into corporate profits. General 
Electric has slid 9.1 percent from its July 19 close of 120 to 109 
Friday, following a drop of 3. 
</P>
<P>
	``That drop is disconcerting,'' said Hyman. ``You don't want to  
see a bellwether Dow stock weaken like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Automakers were mostly lower Friday, dragged down by  
DaimlerChrysler, which lost 5 7/16 to 72 1/8. The company posted flat 
earnings on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow's decline overshadowed strength in some lesser-known  
Nasdaq stocks. Lam Research, a maker of equipment used to build 
circuits on computer chips, rose 9 to 55 3/8 after reporting earnings 
that topped Wall Street analysts' estimates. Also, the Russell 2000 
index of smaller companies rose 3.19 to 444.77. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange. Composite volume totaled 875.77 
million shares, compared with 903.57 million in the previous 
session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 4.74 to 626.07, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 3.64 to 788.23. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average slipped 0.05 percent.  
European indexes mostly rose, as Germany's DAX index gained 1.0 
percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 gained 1.9 percent, and France's 
CAC-40 closed 1.8 percent higher. 





</P>
</TEXT>
