<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orthodox Christians Call For Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- One of the largest Orthodox Christian churches  
in the United States called Friday for all North Americans who 
share the faith to unite under one leadership body, regardless of 
ethnic backgrounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders of the Orthodox Church in America adopted a statement  
made Thursday by the church's presiding bishop, who called for an 
end to a ``status quo'' in which the roughly 15 Orthodox churches 
of different ethnic origins share beliefs but not leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a missionary church we are not permitted to repeat the  
mistakes of the past associated with ethnic identities,'' said 
Metropolitan Theodosius, the head of the Orthodox Church in America 
since 1977, in a speech at the church's national convention. ``Our 
doors are open to all people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first Orthodox Christians came to North America in 1794 when  
Russian missionaries arrived in Kodiak, Alaska. They lost central 
leadership in 1917 when Bolsheviks in the Russian revolution 
arrested Moscow's Orthodox Christian patriarch and stopped funding. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the religion is so splintered that some cities, like  
Pittsburgh, have six different branches representing different 
ethnicities. There are about 4 million Orthodox Christians in the 
United States, one-quarter of whom belong to the OCA, made up of 
Bulgarian, Rumanian, Russian and Syrian churches. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement Friday isn't likely to be controversial with  
other branches of the church. Leaders from all North American 
branches passed a resolution in 1994 calling for central 
leadership. But the church's spiritual leader, Archbishop of 
Constantinople Bartholomew, rejected the idea. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
