<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ga. Gunman Eluded Police for 5 Hours </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- As police rushed in to Securities Centre  
responding to calls of gunfire and four possible deaths, the man 
they were seeking was across the street ready to kill again. 
</P>
<P>
	While police investigated the carnage in the first building,  
Mark O. Barton walked calmly past a guard and murdered five more 
people in another part of the office complex. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, while nearly every officer in Atlanta was looking for him,  
Barton walked to his minivan and drove out of town. 
</P>
<P>
	As police scoured every inch of the office buildings in a  
painstaking search, Barton was already in Atlanta's northern 
suburbs, trying to steal a getaway vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
	He would elude police for five hours before killing himself when  
cornered at a gas station. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know how he got away,'' Police Chief Beverly Harvard  
said Friday, a day after Barton completed a bloody rampage that 
also included the deaths of his wife and two children in 
Stockbridge just south of Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did everything exactly as it should have done, and the  
officers did an excellent job, especially when it came to response 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear how Barton carried his two handguns, a 9 mm Glock  
and a Colt .45, as he walked around Buckhead -- a commercial 
district north of downtown. 
</P>
<P>
	The original call from the first round of shooting at Securities  
Centre came into police at 2:56 p.m., Ms. Harvard said, and the 
first officer was on the scene within four minutes. After surveying 
the Momentum Securities office, he called for backup, and one of 
those responding officers heard the shots from across the street at 
Piedmont Center. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was just getting off his motorcycle,'' Harvard said. ``That  
initial call came over at 3:07 p.m., so there wasn't a lot of time 
that had passed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The officer ran to the building, but somehow Barton had already  
left the first-floor office All-Tech Investment Group and escaped 
in his minivan. Police, thinking he was still inside, began a long 
search of the complex. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to remember that it was the end of the business  
day,'' Ms. Harvard said. ``And we are talking about Piedmont 
Avenue, one of the busiest streets of the city. There were a lot of 
people coming and going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since police didn't know that Barton had left, they had to  
secure both buildings and the surrounding area, looking for the 
gunman as well as those who locked themselves in offices for 
safety. 
</P>
<P>
	The search didn't stop until about 8 p.m., when a detective  
heard that Cobb County Police had found Barton heading north on 
Interstate 75. Soon after, Barton pulled over and killed himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Both of the office buildings -- where Barton was a frequent  
customer -- had unarmed guards in the lobbies. Piedmont Center, the 
second building, had security cameras, but they were not constantly 
monitored. 
</P>
<P>
	And during business hours, customers and employees can come and  
go unimpeded. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Barton was a regular client, and one of those people who  
would have never been stopped,'' said Magnes Welsh, spokeswoman for 
Jones Lang Lasalle, the Chicago firm that manages Security Centre. 
``There was nothing unusual about his arrival at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Such arrangements are not unusual among such office buildings,  
said Joseph Ricci, spokesman for the American Society for 
Industrial Security. 
</P>
<P>
	``For that building, that may have been adequate, especially if  
it didn't have agencies that were high threat risks,'' Ricci said. 
``There is no way to prevent someone with artillery, even if there 
is an armed guard there. If someone has the will, there isn't much 
to stop them.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
