<HEADLINE> House Panel Calls Census Emergency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Republican-led House Appropriations  
Committee fought off Democrats Friday and insisted on calling the 
2000 Census an emergency, underlining the GOP's continuing struggle 
to pay for next year's spending bills. 
</P>
<P>
	On successive party-line votes, the committee held fast to its  
prior decision to label as an emergency expense the $4.5 billion 
cost of the constitutionally ordained head count. That designation 
lets Congress ignore legally required spending limits and pay for 
an item with the anticipated federal surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	The fight came as the panel used a voice vote to approve a $37.7  
billion measure financing the departments of justice, state and 
commerce for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	A fight also loomed over a separate $94 billion measure  
financing veterans, housing, environmental and space programs, 
which also have received veto threats. That bill would cut 
Clinton's $13.6 billion proposal for NASA's budget by 10 percent 
and trim his plans for public housing. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Hal Rogers, R-Ky., chairman of the subcommittee that wrote  
the justice, state, commerce bill, said removing the census' 
emergency tag and squeezing its costs into the rest of the bill 
would ``create a crisis.'' He said it would force layoffs of FBI 
agents and closures of 80 U.S. embassies. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., said the emergency designation was  
only the latest in which Republicans were using budget techniques 
and estimates manufactured by ``the Wizard of Oz.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Obey's efforts first to remove the emergency label for the  
entire $4.5 billion, and then for a portion of it, lost by 30-26 
and 32-26. 
</P>
<P>
	White House advisers have threatened a veto by President Clinton  
because the bill cuts his requests for hiring police officers, 
legal aid for the poor, U.S. participation in international 
organizations and other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee also voted 29-23, mostly along party lines, to  
reject an amendment by Rep. Jose Serrano, D-N.Y., that would have 
lifted partially the four-decade Cuba trade embargo by allowing 
U.S. sales of food and medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	To help pay for a separate, $300 billion measure financing  
health, labor and education programs, Republicans are considering 
another budget gimmick. 
</P>
<P>
	They would delay some federal Medicaid payments to the states  
from late September 2000 into early October, said aides speaking on 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	That timing shift would push the expenditure out of the books of  
fiscal 2000 and into 2001, allowing Republicans to claim savings 
next year of several billion dollars. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
