<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 05:10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dominator To Bid NHL Farewell </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) -- Three months after losing the  
Great One, hockey is now preparing to bid farewell to the 
Dominator. 
</P>
<P>
	Dominik Hasek, whose acrobatic saves made him the NHL's top  
goalie of the 1990s, will play one more season for the Buffalo 
Sabres before retiring and returning to the Czech Republic. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek is tired of the limelight and wants his two children,  
9-year-old Michal and 4-year-old Dominika, to grow up in his 
homeland. 
</P>
<P>
	``I decided to retire because of my friends and my family,''  
Hasek said Thursday. ``When Michal turns 18, it will be his 
decision whether he becomes an American or a Czech boy. But now, we 
want both kids to live with us in the Czech Republic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek's announcement came one day after Barry Sanders stunned  
the NFL by announcing his retirement. Wayne Gretzky, Michael Jordan 
and John Elway also retired recently, meaning five of the best team 
athletes in the world retired or announced plans to quit in the 
same year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously it will be difficult to replace somebody of the  
caliber of Dominik Hasek,'' said Sabres assistant general manager 
Larry Carriere, who flew to Prague for the news conference. ``But 
he gave us the opportunity to plan ... our future a year in 
advance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo owner John Rigas said the city was blessed'' to have  
Hasek. 
</P>
<P>
	``Buffalo has had the experience of watching an extraordinary  
human being,'' Rigas said. Next season ``should be a year of 
celebration because Dominik has certainly earned that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fans, media and Czech hockey players hailed Hasek's decision.  
</P>
<P>
	``With all the economic and social troubles this country is  
going through, it's incredible that someone so rich wants to come 
back and live here,'' hockey fan Jitka Heksova said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek's decision was front-page news in all Czech newspapers  
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Fellow Czech star Jaromir Jagr of the Pittsburgh Penguins, who  
also wants to return home when his playing days are over, said he 
understood. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure he's done the best thing for him and for his family,  
although he's in such great shape that he could play for another 
ten years, '' Jagr told Czech TV. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek has earned millions of dollars, won Olympic gold and  
earned five trophies as the NHL's top goalie. But he won't miss the 
spotlight. 
</P>
<P>
	``The attention I've received is overwhelming,'' Hasek said.  
``It's something I don't enjoy at all. It's time to step back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NHL commissioner Gary Bettman held out hope that the 34-year-old  
goalie would continue playing after next season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wish him well and we wish he could change his mind,''  
Bettman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek said he first started thinking about retirement nine  
months ago and met with Sabres' management about it. He and his 
wife made the final decision to quit just before the playoffs, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite struggling much of last season with a groin injury.  
Hasek helped the Sabres reach the Stanley Cup finals, where they 
lost to Dallas in six games. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek, known for flopping to the ice to block shots and even  
releasing his stick and grabbing for the puck with two hands, was 
paid $7 million last season. Only Patrick Roy of the Colorado 
Avalanche, who made $7.5 million, had a higher salary among 
goalies. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek has two years remaining on his contract, $7 million for  
the upcoming season and $7.5 million for 2000-01, and the club 
holds an option at $9 million for the following season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have enough money to live a nice life, not only for me but  
for kids and wife,'' Hasek said. ``If somebody offered me $25 
million to play one more year, I wouldn't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek was the NHL's most valuable player in 1997 and 1998, but  
his career highlight came at the 1998 Winter Olympics in Nagano, 
Japan. He led the Czechs to the gold medal with a performance that 
made him a national hero. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo acquired Hasek in 1992 in a trade from Chicago, where he  
was a backup to Ed Belfour. 
</P>
<P>
	He went to the NHL in January 1990 after the fall of the Iron  
Curtain. It took him three years to make his big breakthrough, and 
his years as a backup left him contemplating a return to Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Now he is getting ready to retire. And unlike some top athletes  
who quit and then return, Hasek has no plans to play again after 
next season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once I take off my equipment for the last time, that's going  
to be forever,'' Hasek said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
