<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gwynn, McGwire Eye Milestones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Baseball fans in St. Louis, who witnessed  
history last season, may get a double dose of the same in the 
coming days. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark McGwire and the Tony Gwynn are on the doorstep of career  
milestones. McGwire, who set a major league record with 70 home 
runs last season, hit his 38th Friday night and needed five more to 
reach 500 for his career. And Gwynn was just nine hits short of 
3,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning Monday, the San Diego Padres and Gwynn come to town  
for four games. McGwire, who witnessed Dave Winfield's 3,000th hit, 
is looking forward to seeing Gwynn join the club. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire also tried to downplay both accomplishments, although  
his recent history shows that when he gets close to a special 
number the homers start coming in bunches. He had homered 11 time 
in 15 games, sprinting to become the 16th player in history in the 
500 club, much like he ended last season with five homers in three 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not historic, it's just a milestone,'' he said. ``He'll  
get 3,000 hits, it's inevitable, and I'll get 500 homers. It's 
going to happen someday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cardinals manager Tony La Russa was hoping both wouldn't happen  
on the same day, which would steal a little thunder from both 
players. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a what-if thing,'' La Russa said. ``But I don't think  
the odds of that are too good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire is giving himself every chance to do it for the home  
fans, in front of whom he had homered 69 times in 153 career games. 
He has no plans to take any games off in the homestand, despite 
frequent triple-digit heat the last few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just had a day off yesterday,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Cardinals fans have a lot better chance to witness Gwynn's  
historic hit. Only 21 players have reached 3,000 hits and Gwynn 
would become the first National League player to reach 3,000 in 20 
years -- the last being the Cardinals' Lou Brock in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	``He might get it this weekend,'' McGwire joked. ``The chances  
are really good that it'll happen here. He has a lot easier shot of 
getting nine hits over six home runs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire's so confident of it, he's thought ahead to the series  
and decided against a milestone pow-wow with Gwynn. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll just talk to him at first base after his 3,000th hit,''  
McGwire said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn has won eight National League batting titles, tied with  
Honus Wagner for most in league history and one more than Stan 
Musial won in his Cardinals career. Musial, with 3,630, ranks 
fourth in the 3,000-hit club. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire gave fans at Busch Stadium a lifetime's worth of  
memories last season when he swatted several of the most historic 
home runs. Those included No. 61, which tied Roger Maris' 
37-year-old record, No. 62, which broke it, and No. 70 in his final 
at-bat of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	The baseball that McGwire hits for No. 500 is expected to have  
considerable value, recalling the excitement over last season's 
historic home run balls. Comic book creator Todd McFarlane spent 
$3.2 million to acquire the 70th homer ball. 
</P>
<P>
	The 500-home run club includes Henry Aaron, Babe Ruth, Willie  
Mays, Frank Robinson, Mel Ott, Jimmie Foxx -- but no Cardinals. 
Musial hit 475 home runs in his career. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
