<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Note Surfaces From Atlanta Killer  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Mark O. Barton, the gunman who killed nine people  
at two brokerage firms yesterday, had lost roughly $105,000 in 
stock trading in less than two months, authorities said today. He 
left a note vowing revenge on those who had ``greedily sought my 
destruction.'' Barton's wife, son and daughter were found 
bludgeoned in the family residence. Also in the note -- left in the 
family's apartment -- Barton denied killing his first wife and 
mother-in-law in 1993. In the van with his body, police found the 
two guns used in the shooting, two additional handguns, 200 rounds 
of ammunition and two pairs of handcuffs. 

</P>
<P>
	Heat Wave Death Toll Climbs to 91  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The heat wave gripping much of the nation has  
been linked to at least 91 deaths in 17 states since July 19. The 
Midwest has been hit hardest, with Missouri logging 29 heat-related 
deaths, Illinois 23 and Ohio 10. Temperatures neared 100 degrees 
today in many cities, and the heat index -- a measure of temperature 
and humidity -- rose past 110 in several places. It was 104 degrees 
in Louisville, Ky., and 102 at the Little Rock, Ark., Air Force 
Base. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate Passes Tax Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans pushed their $792 billion tax cut  
through the Senate today, courting a veto struggle this fall with 
President Clinton. Democrats claim the measure shortchanges 
Medicare and other domestic programs. The vote was 57-43 -- largely 
along party lines -- in favor of the GOP plan. The 10-year measure, 
which includes broad-based tax relief as well as provisions 
designed to address the so-called marriage penalty, would make it 
easier to accumulate retirement savings and pay for education. 

</P>
<P>
	NTSB: JFK Jr. Plane Functioned OK  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- John F. Kennedy Jr.'s plane apparently was  
functioning properly when it slammed into the ocean, but the 
weather may have been worse than a forecast Kennedy had received, 
the government said today. The National Transportation Safety 
Board, in its first update in a week on its investigation of the 
July 16 crash that killed Kennedy, his wife and her sister, said 
about 75 percent of the wreckage has been recovered from the waters 
off Martha's Vineyard, Mass. The wreckage shows no sign of 
in-flight breakup or fire, and the engine appeared to have been 
working fine at the time of the crash. 

</P>
<P>
	Tripp Indicted on Wiretap Charge  
</P>
<P>
	ELLICOTT CITY, Md. (AP) -- Linda Tripp, whose secretly recorded  
phone conversations with Monica Lewinsky led to the impeachment of 
President Clinton, was charged by the state of Maryland today with 
illegal wiretapping, making her the only major figure in the sex 
scandal to face a criminal charge. A grand jury indicted Mrs. Tripp 
on two counts of breaking Maryland's wiretapping law. Each offense 
could carry up to five years in prison and a $10,000 fine if she 
were to be convicted. 

</P>
<P>
	Morocco King To Follow Dad's Reforms  
</P>
<P>
	RABAT, Morocco (AP) -- Morocco's new king said today he will  
honor his late father by continuing his free market reforms and by 
seeking peace in the region. In his first address to this North 
African nation since assuming the throne July 23 after the death of 
his father, Hassan II, the king said he wanted to continue to build 
a free and open country. He said one of his priorities would be to 
continue to improve Morocco's human rights record. 

</P>
<P>
	House Panel Eases Proposed NASA Cut  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House Appropriations Committee voted today  
to ease proposed cuts in NASA's budget but left the space agency 
well short of what President Clinton wants for next year. NASA's 
extra $400 million was part of an effort by majority Republicans to 
bolster support for a massive $92 billion measure financing 
veterans, housing, space and environment programs for the coming 
fiscal year. The panel also boosted spending for veterans' health 
care by $700 million, responding to pressure from veterans' groups. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Close Lower; Dow Down 136.14  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks slid for a second straight session today,  
with the Dow Jones industrial average languishing behind other 
indicators amid concerns over interest rates. The Dow ended down 
136.14 points at 10,655.15, adding to a 180-point plunge yesterday. 
On the NYSE, advancers led decliners 1,495-1,445. The Nasdaq was 
down 1.49 at 2,638.52. 

</P>
<P>
	Mets Rally Past Cubs 10-9  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The New York Mets overcame Sammy Sosa's major  
league-leading 38th home run and rallied to beat the Chicago Cubs 
10-9 today. Rickey Henderson, with the game tied 8-8, hit a leadoff 
homer in the sixth off Kyle Farnsworth (2-4) to help lead the Mets 
to their 14th win in 18 games. John Olerud added a key insurance 
run with a solo homer off Rick Aguilera in the ninth. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF  
  	   	
</P>
