<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mixed Portrait of Atlanta Gunman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A father who loved to play with kids. An easy-going Scout  
master. A churchgoing man who worked all day at his computer. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark O. Barton shattered the gentle images held by some of his  
former neighbors in a burst of gunfire at two office buildings in 
Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Barton, 44, who ran a chemical consulting business out of his  
home before becoming a securities day trader, shot himself to death 
in his minivan as police closed in on him Thursday. Earlier, he 
opened fire at two brokerage firms, killing nine workers and 
wounding a dozen more. 
</P>
<P>
	As police combed Atlanta looking for him, they made a grisly  
discovery: the bodies of Barton's second wife, and his son and 
daughter from a previous marriage, all bludgeoned to death with a 
blunt instrument in the two days before the office shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	Barton, who had split up with his wife, Leigh Ann, 27, earlier  
this year, had been living with his two children, 11-year-old 
Matthew and 7-year-old Elizabeth Mychelle, in Morrow, a suburb 
south of Atlanta. Over the July 4th weekend, the three of them 
moved to nearby Stockbridge to live in Mrs. Barton's apartment. 
</P>
<P>
	Barton had lived in Morrow for about a year, renting a neat  
two-story house in a modest residential neighborhood, said 
Christine Johnson, who lived two doors away. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Johnson said Barton seldom left his house and was always at  
work on his computer. When he did go out, it was to walk around the 
neighborhood for exercise. 
</P>
<P>
	``He kept to himself,'' Mrs. Johnson said. ``If he drove by in  
his van he threw his hand up. But that was about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another neighbor, Sabrina DeFreese Stowers, said Matthew was  
best friends with her son Brian, 13. It was Barton who persuaded 
the shy Brian to join the Scout troop he helped run. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was just too mild-mannered,'' said Ms. Stowers, a postal  
worker. ``Nothing bothered this man. ... He just seemed like he 
didn't have a violent bone in his body.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A good conversationalist, they once discussed their mutual  
liking of chemistry. Barton had either studied chemistry or held a 
chemistry degree, Ms. Stowers recalled. She had also met Mrs. 
Barton. 
</P>
<P>
	``They seemed like the ideal couple. He was an attractive guy. A  
nice guy,'' she said. ``I didn't know he was a psycho.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brian, who had recently spent the night at the Bartons' home in  
Stockbridge, said the elder Barton was playful. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was just like me or Matthew,'' the boy said. ``He would  
play basically anything we would play, like we would show him 
something on the Internet that we found, like games, and he would 
help us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Brian's grandmother, Marsha Jean DeFreese, said Barton  
``looked odd to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought something's weird about this man.''  
</P>
<P>
	Barton grew up in Sumter, S.C., according to people living near  
Barton's widowed mother. He didn't visit often, but he did attend 
his father's funeral several years ago, said Alice Mathis, who 
lives across the street from Gladys Barton. 
</P>
<P>
	To Cindy Northcutt, who lived on the same street as Barton, the  
man ``always seemed preoccupied.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He had other things on his mind,'' she said. ``He didn't seem  
friendly at all. He was making an effort to have something to do 
with you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neighbors in Morrow said Mrs. Barton was active in the Girl  
Scouts. On Wednesday, she was expected at an outing, but never 
showed up. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, Barton's first wife, Debra Spivey Barton, 36, and her  
mother, Eloise Powell Spivey, 59, were bludgeoned to death with a 
sharp instrument at a campground in northeast Alabama. Authorities 
said Barton was the prime suspect, but he was never charged. Barton 
eventually got custody of their two children. 
</P>
<P>
	A few months after the slayings, Mrs. Spivey's husband told the  
Atlanta Journal-Constitution that ``until the murders, Mark was the 
perfect son-in-law.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
