<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religious Leaders Eye Gun Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A minister who represents 300,000 United  
Methodists in northern Georgia called for tighter regulations on 
guns Friday in the aftermath of the Atlanta office shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Moses Woodruff of Atlanta acknowledged that a  
``combination of things'' drove Atlanta gunman Mark O. Barton to 
kill, but he said the problem was ``exacerbated by access to 
guns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other religious leaders made similar calls to toughen the  
nation's gun laws. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are taught in Leviticus 19, `Do not profit by the blood of  
your neighbor,''' said Rabbi David Saperstein, who leads a 
religious coalition working for nationwide gun controls. The group 
includes the Roman Catholic Church, mainline Protestant 
denominations and Jewish organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	A prominent clergyman who opposes gun controls, the Rev. Richard  
Land of the Southern Baptist Convention, predicted that proponents 
of tighter regulations will use Thursday's deaths ``to whip up 
hysteria.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Such arguments, he said, won't be effective with his  
constituency, the nation's largest group of Protestants. Since 
Littleton, most conservative Protestants have tended to blame the 
media for the nation's violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of us grew up in a region where guns were as natural a  
thing as lawn mowers,'' he said. ``The problem is not the guns but 
what people are doing with the guns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As an example, he cited Barton, who killed his wife and children  
with a hammer before shooting nine people. Barton, he said, was a 
disturbed man who ``would have killed whether he had access to guns 
or not.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
