<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mets Still Seek First Complete Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Mets' pitching staff is closing in  
on a mark of futility, although it hasn't affected them at all in 
the standings. 
</P>
<P>
	No Mets pitcher has thrown a complete game this season. In fact,  
Mets pitchers haven't had a complete game since Al Leiter did it 
last Sept. 4 -- a string of 124 games. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets' streak is the second-longest stretch ever, 16 short of  
the record set by the Anaheim Angels in 1998-99. And yet, the major 
league leaders in complete games -- the Philadelphia Phillies and 
the Baltimore Orioles with 11 each -- are in third and fourth place, 
respectively, in their divisions. 
</P>
<P>
	In this era of high-octane offenses, specialized relievers and  
pitch-count paranoia, the Mets are proving complete games don't 
really matter. They are in second place in the NL East, a half-game 
behind the Atlanta Braves. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a better record than they do,'' Mets general manager  
Steve Phillips said recently when asked whether it mattered that 
Baltimore had 11 more complete games than his staff. 
</P>
<P>
	It is starting to matter for the Mets' pitchers, who are growing  
weary of answering questions about their inability to pitch nine 
innings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I get sick and tired that we don't have a complete game,''  
said Leiter, who had four last year, but hasn't gone past the 
eighth inning this season. ``There are other teams that have one. 
But when you just have the goose egg up there, it's something to 
write about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, every other team has at least one. And Curt Schilling  
and Randy Johnson have eight each. The closest the Mets came was an 
8 1-3-inning performance by 40-year-old Orel Hershiser on June 29 
against the Florida Marlins. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes no difference nor any sense for me to worry about  
that,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine said Sunday after pulling 
Leiter with a 5-1 lead after eight innings. ``He threw 130 pitches. 
I didn't want him to throw 150 just to get the complete game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Using the bullpen every game has taken its toll on Mets  
relievers, who average more than 3.1 innings per game. Even though 
they are second in the majors with a 3.26 ERA, Phillips is 
concerned enough about possible burnout that he is aggressively 
looking to deal for another reliever before Saturday's trade 
deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets aren't the only team struggling to complete what they  
started. In recent years, the complete game has gone the way of the 
scheduled doubleheader and the 1-0 pitchers' duel. They just aren't 
many anymore. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1979, 21 percent of starts resulted in complete games, and  
Phil Niekro led the majors with 23. The next year, with Billy 
Martin at the helm, the Oakland Athletics completed 94 games and 
had three pitchers with more than 20. Through Wednesday, only 4.3 
percent of starts have been completed. 
</P>
<P>
	There are many reasons for the change. Perhaps most important is  
the use of specialized relievers. Most managers would prefer to use 
a fresh reliever in late innings than let a tiring starter face a 
batter for a third or fourth time. 
</P>
<P>
	``The formula for success used to be five starters, a setup man  
and a closer,'' Rangers pitching coach Dick Bosman said. ``That 
formula has changed. Now you hope for five maybe six or seven 
innings out of the starter and match up the rest of the way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bullpen specialists aren't the only factor limiting complete  
games. With the proliferation of statistics and medical technology, 
managers are realizing the effects high pitch counts can have on a 
pitcher's performance and health. 
</P>
<P>
	And with more runs scored meaning more batters, and more patient  
hitters and smaller strike zones meaning more pitchers per at-bat, 
pitch counts are rising and managers are concerned. 
</P>
<P>
	After Cubs phenom Kerry Wood blew out his elbow following a  
rookie season when he topped 121 pitches four times in five starts, 
other managers have taken heed. The Tigers refuse to let Jeff 
Weaver top 110 pitches, sometimes to the detriment of the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't sacrifice the future for right now,'' Tigers manager  
Larry Parrish said. ``Some people are thinking I don't want to win. 
I feel like I want to win more than anybody. I'm the guy that it 
affects the most.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
