<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands of Saturn Owners Gather </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRING HILL, Tenn. (AP) -- Richard and Joan Stover had so much  
fun at the first Saturn ``homecoming,'' a rain-soaked, 
mud-splattered affair five years ago, they had to come back. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a family reunion,'' said a smiling Mrs. Stover, who wore  
a ``This is Saturn Country'' T-shirt and carried a red umbrella to 
ward off the intense sun as they listened to a doo-wop band Friday 
morning. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stovers, who drove up from Fort Pierce, Fla., in their new  
``homecoming edition'' sedan, were among thousands streaming into 
Spring Hill for two days of plant tours, test drives, parades and 
concerts. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 44,000 attended the last homecoming and as many as  
60,000 were expected this weekend, paying $40 per adult and $15 for 
every child over 6. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturn hopes the event will help jump-start the ``different kind  
of car company,'' a General Motors subsidiary that has seen an 
erosion in customer satisfaction, declining sales and labor strife 
in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	This week, Saturn dropped to No. 6 after four years in the top  
slot of the J.D. Power and Associates annual survey of customer 
sales satisfaction. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturn chairman and president Cynthia Trudell acknowledged this  
was a blow for a company that touts its customer loyalty and 
``no-haggle'' selling practices, but said she doesn't believe 
dealers were putting pressure on customers because of slumping 
sales and dealer profit margins. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what's most exciting about homecoming,'' she said. ``It  
gives us an opportunity to talk directly to our customers to find 
out,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Folks spent a lot of time looking for relief from the sunny  
skies and 101-degree heat, seeking shade under camera platforms to 
set up blankets in front of a stage, using spray bottles connected 
to fans to spray a cool mist on their faces and arms, and draining 
free coolers of ice water before midday. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the only corporation in America that does this kind of  
thing,'' said Marie Wilcox of Indianapolis as she stood in line to 
get on a bus for a tour of the plant nestled among the rolling 
hills of this small Middle Tennessee town. ``To see firsthand how 
the car is made, that's pretty awesome.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
