<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boxing Officials Sue NJ Commissioner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Two female boxing officials are suing the  
New Jersey athletic commissioner, saying their civil rights were 
violated because they were refused licenses to work in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Boxing judge Lynne Carter and referee Velma Garrick filed the  
lawsuit in U.S. District Court, charging that Commissioner Larry 
Hazzard discriminated against them because of their gender. The 
lawsuit, which also names the State Athletic Control Board, alleges 
that Hazzard refused to renew Carter's license for 1997 and refused 
to grant Garrick a license in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Hazzard declined to comment on the lawsuit.  
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit seeks damages in excess of $75,000.  
</P>
<P>
	Carter became the first black female boxing judge in New Jersey  
in 1982 and Garrick has been a referee at more than 50 professional 
matches. Both are licensed in Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither women was given a hearing before being denied their  
licenses. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit also charges that Hazzard and the control board's  
decision caused the two women pain and emotional distress. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
