<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jays Honor Cito Gaston, Joe Carter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Cito Gaston and Joe Carter were given a permanent  
place in Toronto Blue Jays' history Friday night, as the team added 
their names to the Level of Excellence, the highest award bestowed 
by the club. 
</P>
<P>
	Gaston and Carter joined Dave Stieb and George Bell as the only  
Blue Jays to receive the honor. 
</P>
<P>
	Gaston managed the Blue Jays to two World Series championships,  
four division titles and a franchise-record 681 wins. Carter, the 
franchise career leader with 203 home runs, won the 1993 World 
Series against Philadelphia with a homer in the bottom of the ninth 
inning. 
</P>
<P>
	After Carter and Gaston received a three-minute standing ovation  
upon being introduced, a video tribute was played and both spoke 
briefly before the Blue Jays' game against the Detroit Tigers. 
</P>
<P>
	``All the great moments in my career, the World Series-winning  
homer, the All-Star games, happened in Toronto,'' Carter said. ``I 
couldn't have asked for a better place to play, and I feel very 
honored to join the level of excellence with my good friend, and I 
think one of the game's best managers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gaston, who said recently he could have received more credit for  
the Blue Jays' success, thanked the fans for the way he was 
treated. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still live here. I love it here,'' Gaston said. ``I want to  
thank the fans and the organization. You've treated me like 
family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Blue Jays unveiled commemorative signs as Gaston and Carter  
received another standing ovation. They also threw out the 
ceremonial first pitches. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
