<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steelers' Dawson Not Ready To Retire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LATROBE, Pa. (AP) -- As players 10 years younger barely made it  
through a succession of sprints Friday on the first day of the 
Pittsburgh Steelers' camp, Dermontti Dawson cruised through them 
with little effort. 
</P>
<P>
	At 34, an age at which many offensive linemen are on their last  
legs both competitively and career-wise, Dawson apparently hasn't 
lost a step. Or his edge on the rest of the NFL's centers. 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe it's the motivation that comes with being a nearly  
unanimous pick for the All-Pro team the last couple of years -- 
exactly the kind of drive that Barry Sanders, another player at the 
top of his game, couldn't muster. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders retired this week from the Detroit Lions while still in  
the upper echelon of NFL running backs, with Walter Payton's NFL 
rushing record in sight and millions of dollars remaining on his 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	To Dawson, the urge to compete, and to make money, remains too  
strong to step away from a game he still dominates as few NFL 
players do at any position. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a lot of money,'' said Dawson, who will make $2.9 million  
in base salary this year and $3 million in 2000. ``When those 
paychecks start coming in, it's hard to walk away from that much 
money. Where else am I going to have the chance to make that much 
money in my lifetime? 
</P>
<P>
	``But you've got to have a passion for this game to enjoy it, to  
play it, and I still do. Maybe Barry didn't have that passion left 
in him,'' Dawson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Steelers' play dropped off precipitously last year as a team  
that fell four points short of reaching the Super Bowl in the 1997 
season finished 7-9, their first losing record since 1991. But if 
there was any drop-off in Dawson's play, it wasn't apparent. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's so consistent and so durable,'' coach Bill Cowher said.  
``Week in and week out, he's there. He plays at a very high level 
and certainly he has been recognized as one of the very best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even as quarterback Kordell Stewart struggled nearly all season,  
creating even more pressure on the Jerome Bettis-led running game 
to produce, Dawson constantly fought off double teams to create 
running room up the middle. 
</P>
<P>
	As his 11th NFL season approaches, Dawson realizes he is much  
closer to the end of his career than the beginning. But that end is 
not yet in sight, especially for a player who someday may join the 
center he succeeded, Mike Webster, in the Pro Football Hall of 
Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm 34, which is old in football years, so it's a year-to-year  
thing with me right now,'' he said. ``The first and foremost thing 
is to get through this year, then I'll hope to make it through next 
year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 2000 season would be the last under his current contract,  
and Dawson has not yet ruled out playing beyond then, even though 
he would be 36 in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it happens, it happens,'' he said. ``As long as the  
Steelers want me here, that's the key. But when the time comes, 
I'll know.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
