<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 04:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A's Gets Velarde, Olivares in Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Moving to stay in the playoff chase, the  
Oakland Athletics strengthened their pitching and offense by 
acquiring right-hander Omar Olivares and slugging infielder Randy 
Velarde from Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
	In return, the Angels received three minor leaguers from the  
A's. 
</P>
<P>
	``This certainly helps us out in the rotation, and the  
organization has always been a big fan of Velarde. It gives us 
another right-handed bat, and we just think he's a fit,'' A's 
general manager Billy Beane said. ``Olivares has arguably been one 
of the top 10-12 guys in the league in terms of ERA and he's a 
solid major league starter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Velarde was hitting a team-high .306 for the Angels and was tied  
for the team lead with 115 hits. He also has nine homers and 48 
RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivares, one of the Angels' most reliable starters, was 8-9  
with a 4.05 ERA in 20 starts. He led the team in wins and was tied 
for second in the league with three complete games. 
</P>
<P>
	The two were expected to join Oakland by tonight.  
</P>
<P>
	Both will be free agents after the end of this season.  
</P>
<P>
	``We appreciate everything Randy and Omar have done for the  
Angels,'' Angels general manager Bill Bavasi said. ``Randy has 
worked extremely hard to get his game back to the level he demands 
of himself, and his numbers this season reflect that. Omar did some 
great things for us last season in a variety of roles, and this 
season has been one of our most consistent starters. However, at 
this point in time we need to make some moves for the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beane said the deal for two veterans sends a message that the  
second-place A's were not conceding anything last weekend when they 
dealt away pitching ace Kenny Rogers. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogers, who went to the Mets for a pair of minor leaguers, will  
be a free agent at the end of the season and had said he wouldn't 
return to Oakland. 
</P>
<P>
	Beane said Rogers was traded while Oakland could still get  
something for him, and that anyone who thought it signaled the 
start of the dismantling of the A's had misread the club's 
intentions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We weren't throwing in the towel when we traded Rogers,''  
Beane said. ``We did have a plan. We had an idea of what we wanted 
to do. The club has played well. Hopefully, this will give us a 
little shot of adrenaline.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The A's must make roster space for the additions and drop one of  
the current pitchers from the rotation, but Beane declined to 
discuss the affected players because they hadn't been notified yet. 
</P>
<P>
	Beane did suggest the club could make another deal before  
Saturday's trading deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've still got some ideas, some things we're still talking  
about,'' Beane said. ``We're still running through some things 
internally. We're trying to improve our club for the short term and 
the long term, if possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Angels acquired right-hander Elvin Nina and outfielders Jeff  
DaVanon and Nathan Haynes. 
</P>
<P>
	DaVanon and Nina were playing for the A's Double-A affiliate at  
Midland. 
</P>
<P>
	DaVanon was hitting .341 with 11 homers and 59 RBIs, while Nina  
was 3-2 with a 4.80 ERA in seven games, including four starts at 
Midland. 
</P>
<P>
	Haynes was batting .313 with 12 stolen bases in 35 games at  
Single-A Visalia. 
</P>
<P>
	``With Jeff and Nathan, we feel we have added some much needed  
speed to our system. Both have had success in that area in a 
relatively short time. Elvin is a young man with a live arm and a 
good mix of pitches,'' Bavasi said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
