<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Saints' Roaf Still Unsatisfied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LA CROSSE, Wis. (AP) -- William Roaf comes from a family that  
treats overachieving as ordinary. There's a lot to live up to when 
your father is a dentist and your mother is a judge. 
</P>
<P>
	That expectation of greatness is part of the reason Roaf isn't  
satisfied even after five straight trips to the NFL Pro Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	The New Orleans Saints' 37-59 record since the big Louisiana  
Tech tackle was a No. 1 draft pick in 1993 is another reason for 
Roaf's dissatisfaction. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never thought we'd go this long without winning,'' Roaf said  
after wrapping up a second straight 6-10 season. ``It's really 
frustrating.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During his NFL career, Roaf has had a string of personal  
accomplishments. 
</P>
<P>
	Between 1993 and 1996, Roaf had a string of 57 straight starts.  
He has started five straight Pro Bowls, the only player in Saints 
history with such a run. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, I can go another four or five years and go to the  
Hall of Fame,'' Roaf said. 
</P>
<P>
	He'd rather trade the Pro Bowl for a Super Bowl.  
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody wants that,'' he said. ``Everyone thinks they'll  
make it before they quit. I feel that way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roaf, the nearest thing the Saints have had to a star the past  
few years, once again believes New Orleans is on the way up -- in 
part because of their newest celebrity. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're going to have a very good year,'' he said. ``I  
think the addition of Ricky Williams is going to be positive. 
Offensively, we'll hold our own and the defense was already playing 
real good football.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roaf describes his job as simple.  
</P>
<P>
	``I guard the blind side of the quarterback and make sure he  
doesn't get tackled, and I open up holes for the running back,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sounds simple, but it has proven difficult over the past few  
years when the Saints running game has ranked dead last in the 
league and the offense as a whole wasn't far from that, 
</P>
<P>
	This year, the Saints have beefed up Roaf's side of the line  
with Wally Williams, a seven-year pro who was the Baltimore Ravens' 
franchise player prior to the 1998 season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that combination is going to be as tough as it gets,''  
offensive coordinator Danny Abramowicz said. ``I've heard the talk 
that Willie has slumped some lately, but don't believe it. I think 
he's still the best in the league in that spot. Now with Wally in 
there, they should be the dynamic duo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The addition of Williams, the Heisman Trophy running back who  
set 20 records while at Texas, has coach Mike Ditka even more 
dedicated to the running game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ricky's a great football player,'' Ditka said. ``We've got  
other great backs who can run, but there's nobody in the world that 
you run in the National Football League without help. We've got to 
get him all the help we can. So I would say the ball is in their 
court. The offensive line will shoulder the responsibility of being 
the backbone of our offense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roaf is accustomed to responsibility. His parents saw to that a  
long time ago. As a youngster, he worked as a page for then-Gov. 
Bill Clinton in the Arkansas Capitol in Little Rock. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was in seventh grade, and I was a good student,'' Roaf said.  
``My parents knew President Clinton, who was governor then, and 
they were asking for kids from around the state. We mostly ran 
errands and brought messages to the Capitol.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although his mother wasn't completely sold on his being a  
professional football player when he graduated from college, she's 
come around. 
</P>
<P>
	``My parents just always wanted us to do the best we could at  
whatever we did,'' Roaf said. ``They drilled that into us and 
that's what I try to do.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
