<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Mulls More Olympic Hearings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The IOC's top congressional critic is  
considering a second set of hearings into Olympic reforms in the 
wake of the Salt Lake bribery scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Aides said Friday that Sen. John McCain could schedule a  
followup to an April session of the Senate Commerce Committee, 
during which he and other lawmakers criticized the International 
Olympic Committee for creating a ``culture of corruption.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Senator McCain is thinking about scheduling another hearing,''  
Commerce Committee spokeswoman Pia Pialorsi said. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the Arizona Republican met this week with  
representatives of OATH, an Olympic athletes' group created in 
response to the scandal surrounding Salt Lake City's winning bid 
for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is concerned about various aspects of the Olympics raised  
by athletes in this week's meeting,'' Pialorsi said. 
</P>
<P>
	No date for a possible hearing had been set, she said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles Times reported Friday that a mid-October date  
had been tentatively set, with items for discussion to include 
congressional review of Olympic reforms, athlete participation in 
the IOC and anti-doping measures in sports. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC 2000, which is directing the panel's internal changes, is  
scheduled to hold its final meeting Oct. 29-30 and make proposals 
for a special IOC general assembly in December. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Hybl, the U.S. Olympic Committee president and an IOC 2000  
member, said the USOC would cooperate with any Senate hearings ``in 
a positive and affirmative way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCain's committee has pending legislation that would strip the  
IOC's tax-exempt status in the United States, limit the tax 
deductions of IOC sponsorships and -- most forcefully -- direct all 
U.S. TV rights fees to the USOC rather than the IOC, depriving the 
international panel of its single biggest revenue source. 
</P>
<P>
	During a hearing last spring, the Arizona Republican said IOC  
leaders, including president Juan Antonio Samaranch, had allowed a 
corrupt system to flourish and must become more accountable to 
fans, athletes and sponsors. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said that the IOC should adopt the recommendations of a  
USOC-sponsored probe headed by George Mitchell, but agreed with the 
former Senate majority leader to wait until the international panel 
concluded internal reform plans, scheduled for the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview last month, McCain said he would stick with  
Mitchell's request, even though he remained concerned about the 
IOC's actions and criticized Samaranch for failing to communicate 
with his committee. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent weeks, other critics of the IOC have issued  
increasingly positive reviews of the reform plans. Mitchell said in 
June that it appeared the committee was making progress, and 
earlier this month the vice chairman of his inquiry panel, former 
White House Chief of Staff Ken Duberstein, said the IOC ``seemed 
committed to the process of reform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	IOC 2000, meanwhile, has said it would recommend adoption of all  
of the Mitchell commission's proposed changes, including term 
limits for members, membership for athletes and open financial 
records. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
