<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arizona Cuts TE Gedney After Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. (AP) -- The Arizona Cardinals have cut tight end  
Chris Gedney, who underwent surgery to remove his colon July 4. 
</P>
<P>
	Gedney said he was shocked by the team's move because he was  
counting on the team's support as he underwent further surgery and 
mounted a comeback. 
</P>
<P>
	``They talk about family and loyalty and it just came out of the  
blue,'' Gedney said Friday in a telephone interview from his home 
in Phoenix. ``You just feel abandoned without any rhyme nor reason 
to it because it's not a cap issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cardinals general manager Bob Ferguson said Gedney, the leading  
pass catcher among Cardinals tight ends the last two seasons, was 
waived because he failed his physical. Initially, the Cardinals 
declined to further explain their decision. 
</P>
<P>
	But later in the day, Ferguson said the move was made based on  
the organization's failure to be convinced that Gedney is likely to 
play again. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's had a major surgery and he's going to have another one,''  
Ferguson said. ``To say what he's going to be doing next year is a 
little tough for us, so this is the way we decided to go. ... I 
don't believe that in his best interest he should play football 
anymore. This is a major, major thing, and we can't predict what's 
going to happen to him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gedney said he was told of the decision in a three-minute  
telephone conversation with Ferguson after the physical was 
conducted at Cardinals headquarters in Tempe on Thursday. Ferguson 
didn't explain why the decision was made, Gedney said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Really, by the time it sunk in, I was off the phone with him  
and just kind of sat in the kitchen bewildered,'' Gedney said. 
</P>
<P>
	By cutting Gedney, the Cardinals get another $600,000 to use  
under the salary cap, money sorely needed as the team attempts to 
sign its two first-round draft picks and resolve contract 
differences with wide receiver Rob Moore and defensive tackle Mark 
Smith. But Ferguson said money was not a factor in the decision. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cardinals could have placed the tight end on the  
non-football illness or injury list and wouldn't have had to pay 
him anything, but he still would have been a member of the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Gedney said his doctors remain confident that he will be able to  
play in the NFL again. 
</P>
<P>
	``According to my doctors, who rank as the world's best, the  
likelihood of me playing the game again is extremely high,'' Gedney 
said. ``Has anybody ever done it? No. But nobody has ever had 
testicular cancer and won the Tour de France until now either.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quarterback Jake Plummer said the players are disappointed that  
Gedney had to be cut. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes you think as a football player what would happen if  
anything happened to you?'' Plummer said. ``He's a great football 
player and a great example for a Cardinal, to represent this 
organization.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
