<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Is Lions' Rivers the Next Sanders? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNIVERSITY CENTER, Mich. (AP) -- Ron Rivers was feeling the heat  
Friday, and not just the steamy kind that greeted the Detroit Lions 
on the first day of training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	With Barry Sanders' retirement announcement, Rivers comes to  
camp as one of the Lions' hopes for a replacement. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders shocked the football world Wednesday by announcing he  
was getting out after 10 years, even though he is only 1,458 yards 
shy of breaking Walter Payton's NFL career rushing record of 16,726 
yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans are clinging to the notion that Sanders will change his  
mind and return. Rivers doesn't have that luxury. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he does, that's fine and dandy,'' said Rivers, who admitted  
he had trouble sleeping the night before. ``I have to take care of 
myself. If he doesn't come back, then what? See, I have to get 
ready.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He has a long way to go.  
</P>
<P>
	Despite being Fresno State's career rushing leader with 3,743  
yards, and despite setting the Bulldogs' season rushing record with 
1,542 yards in 1993, Rivers has been largely ignored by the NFL. 
Even with those kinds of numbers, nobody drafted him. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivers signed as a free agent with the Lions in 1994, but spent  
most of that season on their practice squad. He was activated for 
only one game, but didn't touch the ball. 
</P>
<P>
	Life's like that when you're the backup to Barry Sanders.  
</P>
<P>
	Over the next four seasons, Rivers never carried the ball more  
than 29 times. His career NFL numbers show him with 85 carries for 
427 yards and three touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	No wonder he's not sleeping well.  
</P>
<P>
	``Oh, I think he's fine,'' Lions coach Bobby Ross said. ``Like  
anything, I think it's just the anticipation of starting camp. But 
I can see how Ron would be a little more excited. The spotlight's 
on him a little more than he's used to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the first workout, the Lions also took a look at rookie  
Sedrick Irvan, a fourth-round draft pick out of Michigan State who 
rushed for over 1,000 yards each of his last three seasons in 
college. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're all in this together,'' Rivers said. ``I'll help Sedrick  
any way I can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chuck Schmidt, the Lions general manager, said the club  
continues to look for veteran tailback help elsewhere -- either by 
trade or by picking up a free agent. Schmidt said, however, he 
didn't expect to sign anyone soon. 
</P>
<P>
	That left players to try to put the best face possible on a  
difficult situation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ron Rivers is definitely more energetic,'' quarterback Charlie  
Batch said. ``He knows he's the No. 1 guy. We have a lot of 
confidence in him, and I know he'll get the job done.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
