<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Excerpts of Nazi Warning Letters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Excerpts from correspondence by U.S. officials, German citizens  
and an unknown informant on Nazi Germany's ``euthanasia'' programs 
-- written months before the systematic killing of mentally ill and 
deformed citizens became widely known: 
</P>
<P>
	--''After weeks of uncertainty, I received the unbelievable news  
of his sudden death and cremation.'' Death notice in a German 
newspaper by the family of an asylum patient. A rash of family 
notices about ``unbelievable'' asylum deaths raised suspicion among 
German citizens and U.S. diplomats. 
</P>
<P>
	--''The dark and deep secrecy surrounding the Castle of  
Grafeneck, entrance to which is strictly forbidden to all except 
the Black Guard man on duty, gradually led the local inhabitants to 
become uneasy and suspicious.'' Cable from the U.S. vice consul in 
Leipzig, Paul Dutko, to the U.S. Embassy in Berlin, concerning the 
Grafeneck mental asylum. 
</P>
<P>
	--''It is still forbidden by law in Germany to prematurely cause  
the death of so-called incurable mental patients. If the Black 
Guards, for whatever veiled reasons, can and are prematurely 
killing mental patients, this cruelty will further impress upon 
many people the complete lawlessness of the National Socialists.'' 
Dutko's cable, which also reached the top levels of the State 
Department. 
</P>
<P>
	--''In the German insane asylums, district nursing homes and  
asylums for idiots thousands of patients are secretly murdered 
monthly. Not only those who are public wards but also the paying 
inmates. Besides the very ill, there are also slightly ill patients 
(loss of mentality due to old age).'' Anonymous German letter sent 
in December 1940 to NBC in New York and passed on to the War 
Department in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	--''There does not seem any reason to doubt the veracity in  
principle of the information transmitted. On the contrary, 
everything points to it being correct, especially as the carrying 
out of these killings conforms with national-socialist 
principles.'' Military intelligence officer Frederick Sharp, 
writing to the acting chief of staff in the War Department about 
the anonymous letter. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
