<DOCNO> APW19990730.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 12:30:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 85.17; Nasdaq Down 0.64 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *PM-Wall Street 3pm,0485    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were lower today, with the Dow Jones  
industrial average languishing behind other market indicators amid 
continuing concerns over rising interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow was down 85.17 at 10,690.61,  
adding to a 180-point plunge Thursday. The blue-chip index fell as 
much as 126 points earlier this afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader market indexes were also lower, although their losses  
were moderate. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 9.01 at 
1,332.02. The Nasdaq composite index was down 0.64 at 2,639.37, 
wavering between positive and negative territory. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares tumbled broadly Thursday after the Labor Department said  
its Employment Cost Index rose 1.1 percent in the second quarter, a 
bigger-than-expected jump. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists say the data, closely monitored by Federal Reserve  
Chairman Alan Greenspan, could encourage the Fed to raise interest 
rates when its policy-making Federal Open Market Committee meets on 
Aug. 24. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed raised interest rates in June and has signaled its  
willingness to do so again in an effort to contain inflation. In 
the meantime, Wall Street players are carefully watching all fresh 
economic data. 
</P>
<P>
	The selling continued today after Commerce Department reported  
that Americans' personal income surged in June and outpaced 
spending, but the nation's savings rate remains near a record low. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate report today, the Commerce Department said sales  
of new single-family homes rebounded in June, rising 3.1 percent to 
a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 929,000 units, better than 
forecast. 
</P>
<P>
	Also today, the National Association of Purchasing Management's  
Chicago branch reported that manufacturing activity in that region 
of the country area accelerated at a faster-than-expected pace in 
July. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond markets, already retreating before the figures came out,  
fell further on the news. Yields on 30-year Treasury bonds rose to 
6.11 percent from 6.07 percent late Thursday. It was the second 
straight day that yields have risen sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial stocks continued to slide today under the threat of  
higher rates. Dow components American Express fell 5 13/16 to 132 3/4 
and J.P. Morgan dropped 2 7/16 to 128 3/16. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bond investors are already jittery and when you give them an  
excuse to sell, they sell,'' said Anthony O'Bryan, a market analyst 
at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis. ``And when bonds are down, 
that throws a wet blanket on the financial sector.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 10-to-9 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 551.90 million 
shares at late afternoon, down from 620.76 million shares at the 
same time Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 2.95 at 627.86, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was up 0.89 at 785.48. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 0.75 to 442.33.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
