<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. McCain Prefers Traditional Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AIKEN, S.C. (AP) -- Cindy McCain told a crowd of veterans Friday  
that if her husband, John, is elected president, ``We won't ever do 
anything to embarrass the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McCain stood in for her husband at the start of a South  
Carolina campaign swing. McCain, an Arizona Republican, was held up 
in Washington for the Senate's vote on a $792 billion GOP tax cut 
bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The 45-year-old former schoolteacher and mother of four talked  
about her husband's military service and how she would want him in 
charge if her children serve in the military. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a full-time mother,'' she said, adding that her top goal  
is to ``raise decent children'' who, she hopes, will serve in the 
military. 
</P>
<P>
	``We understand what it means to serve,'' she said. ``And we  
won't ever do anything to embarrass the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She didn't talk about campaign issues, leaving that to the  
candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always taken a more traditional role in the campaign,''  
she said in an interview with The Associated Press. But she's not 
critical of political spouses who take a more active role in policy 
like Hillary Rodham Clinton. ``That's their choice,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McCain serves on the board of her family business, a beer  
wholesale operation, but doesn't work there on a daily basis. Her 
first priority has been raising her children. 
</P>
<P>
	``I made the choice to stay at home,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	If McCain wins the White House, she said that as first lady she  
would focus on issues like child health care, adoption and 
encouraging youth volunteerism. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McCain lives with her children in Arizona and the senator  
commutes there on the weekend. She said that was a ``quality of 
life'' decision made for her children. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she has been touched by the public's strong reaction to  
McCain when they hear about his military record and 5 1/2 years in a 
North Vietnamese prison. 
</P>
<P>
	She attributes his personal strength to a strong and dynamic  
mother who raised him while his father was serving in the Navy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
