<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tour de France Drug Tests Negative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- All the cyclists in the Tour de  
France passed their drug tests, world cycling's governing body said 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Cycling Union said it tested riders during  
every stage of the three-week race and there were no positive 
results. 
</P>
<P>
	The showcase event was won by Lance Armstrong, whose remarkable  
comeback from cancer was dogged by suggestions in the French media 
he was aided by banned drugs. He was found to have taken an 
approved prescription skin cream for saddle sores. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong, appearing on ``Late Night with David Letterman'' in  
New York on Friday, said the accusations came from ``a few isolated 
journalists.'' He joked that he must have had 
``performance-enhancing chemotherapy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Out of the 2,000 journalists, there were a handful of people  
who never cover cycling,'' he said. ``All they wanted to do was 
cover a scandal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 1998 Tour de France was rocked by a drug scandal that nearly  
forced the race to stop. 
</P>
<P>
	The cycling union also did blood tests on all the riders on the  
first day of racing and tested individual teams on other days to 
measure the level of red blood cells, or hematocrit. 
</P>
<P>
	High levels might indicate that riders have taken the banned  
hormone EPO. There is no test for EPO but riders with a hematocrit 
level above 50 percent must rest two weeks because the level is 
considered dangerous. 
</P>
<P>
	``All the tests were within the levels fixed by UCI, and we are  
pleased to note that the levels tended to fall during the course of 
the race. This is totally natural,'' the organization said. 
</P>
<P>
	The cycling body also took breath samples from all riders to  
test for PFC, hemoglobin that speeds oxygen intake. The results are 
not yet available. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
