<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indians Sign Catcher Levis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Catcher Jesse Levis, who asked Tampa Bay to  
release him earlier this week, signed a contract Friday for the 
remainder of this season with the Cleveland Indians, who traded him 
away in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	To make room for Levis, the Indians designated catcher Pat  
Borders for assignment. 
</P>
<P>
	Levis spent the first seven years of his career in the Indians'  
organization before being traded before the 1996 season. This 
season he spent time in Triple-A Durham and Double-A Orlando in the 
Devil Rays' minor league system. When he became a free agent on 
July 15, Levis' contract allowed him to ask Tampa Bay to let him 
go. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland was where he wanted to be.  
</P>
<P>
	``I know all the coaches,'' Levis said. ``They know me. They  
know my ability and there's a comfort level there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Levis spent last season with the Milwaukee Brewers, but was  
limited to just 22 games after undergoing shoulder surgery to 
repair a rotator cuff. He batted .351 in 22 games -- 13 at catcher -- 
and had four RBIs for the Brewers. 
</P>
<P>
	Indians manager Mike Hargrove said Levis gives his team a  
``different look'' behind the plate while Cleveland awaits catcher 
Sandy Alomar's return from the disabled list. 
</P>
<P>
	Alomar has been out since May 17 after undergoing surgery on his  
left knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Borders was signed to a minor league contract before the season  
and was recently called up by the Indians after beginning the year 
at Triple-A Buffalo. The 36-year-old hit .300 with three RBIs in 
six games. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
