<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asset Allocation Still Crucial / On the Money  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The stock market has hit record highs, inflation  
remains under control and interest rates are low, so who needs to 
bother with asset allocation? 
</P>
<P>
	After all, a number of investors had managed to amass nice  
little nest eggs over the past year or so by putting everything in 
just a few baskets, like blue-chips and technology stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	While that may be true for some, investment advisers stress that  
asset allocation -- the process of developing a diversified 
portfolio by mixing different assets in varying proportions, or 
putting your eggs in different baskets -- shouldn't be abandoned. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, more and more advisers have been pointing out the  
importance of asset allocation these days, even as times remain 
good for the economy. That's especially true now as the stock 
market undergoes some volatility, particularly in the technology 
sector. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you are investing long-term for college expenses or  
retirement, the single most important thing you can do is to make 
sure you understand basic asset allocation,'' money manager Jim 
Jorgensen of Orinda, Calif., noted in his July investor newsletter. 
</P>
<P>
	``Over time stock or mutual fund selection is much less  
important than proper asset allocation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Elkin, a money manager and accountant from  
Hastings-on-Hudson, N.Y., agreed, citing a recent study lead by 
Roger Ibbotson, a Yale University professor and chairman of 
Ibbotson Associates, which provides data on historic market 
performance. 
</P>
<P>
	The study looked at 10 years of monthly returns for 94 balanced  
mutual funds (funds which have both stocks and bonds), and 10 years 
of quarterly returns for 58 pension funds. The result: Asset 
allocation -- rather than individual stock and bond selection -- 
accounted for about 90 percent of the period-to-period variability 
of a portfolio. And that, of course, means earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Asset allocation is still the unquestioned driver of portfolio  
performance (and) ... is the only reason the average investor makes 
any money investing,'' Elkin wrote in his July newsletter. 
</P>
<P>
	But tell that to the average investor who has seen many Internet  
stocks soar through the stratosphere over the past year and the Dow 
Jones industrial average, which is comprised of large ``blue-chip'' 
companies, march through record territory. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you proposed multiple asset classes (to clients), you felt  
pretty beat up,'' said Eleanor Blayney, a partner in Sullivan, 
Bruyette, Speros &AMP; Blayney, a McLean, Va., portfolio management 
firm. ``The only thing that worked in 1998 was a rifle -- if you 
just aimed at the biggest stock or the most glamorous stock, you 
did the best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The basic allocation plan used by Wall Street brokers is known  
as the ``robot approach,'' which consists of placing 55 percent of 
assets in stocks, 35 percent in bonds and 10 percent in 
cash-equivalent savings accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Deciding just how much to allocate into stocks, bonds, cash, or  
other assets, though, usually depends on numerous factors -- like 
one's risk exposure, time horizon, cash-flow needs and tax bracket. 
</P>
<P>
	Often times, asset allocation plans change with age.  
</P>
<P>
	Jorgensen suggests those ages 20 to 40 should have long-term  
growth as their investment goal and put at least 85 percent of 
their money in stocks or stock funds, with the rest in bonds and 
cash. Those ages 40 to 50 should have at least 75 percent in 
stocks, 50 to 65, 60 percent in stocks, and 65 and older ``keep 
what you need in bond or income funds to provide monthly income 
(and) ... what's left over ... should continue to be invested in 
the stock market,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Blayney focused on the importance of asset allocation for  
retirees during the July annual convention of the Institute of 
Certified Financial Planners in Dallas. She said they often insist 
on sticking with lower-risk assets, such as bonds or money-market 
securities. 
</P>
<P>
	``It can be a very exasperating time,'' she said. ``They all  
say, 'Do not spend the principal.' What they may mean is: Don't 
drop below the balance I brought in ... don't spend the gains from 
appreciation. 
</P>
<P>
	``(But) some retirees outlive their money in retirement. You  
have to reach for higher returns. A retiree may need more equities 
than we may have thought.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blayney thinks stocks should make up between 50 percent and 75  
percent of an average retiree's investment portfolio, an amount 
some money managers may dispute as too high. 
</P>
<P>
	Regardless of a person's stage in life, asset allocation should  
be a concern. 
</P>
<P>
	``How you allocate your investments in stocks, bonds and savings  
accounts is more important than what and when you buy or sell along 
the way,'' Jorgensen said. ``The good news is that it's relatively 
easy to allocate your assets. The bad news is that if you don't 
allocate your assets properly as soon as you can, you may cut your 
retirement nest egg significantly.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
