<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 00:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Community Rallies To Preserve Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARNOLDS PARK, Iowa (AP) -- One by one, the children walked across  
the band shell stage and emptied the contents of their piggy banks. 
</P>
<P>
	They sacrificed their little life savings to preserve the pride  
of Arnolds Park -- an amusement park of the same name that has 
charmed residents and visitors since 1889. 
</P>
<P>
	``There wasn't a dry eye in the house,'' said Stephen Kennedy,  
unofficial chairman of the Save the Park committee. 
</P>
<P>
	People here in northwest Iowa were devastated when they heard  
last month that a developer had plans to buy the park property to 
build condominiums, a hotel and shops. 
</P>
<P>
	``All heck broke loose,'' said Kennedy, curator of the Iowa  
Great Lakes Maritime Museum in Arnolds Park. ``We went right to 
war.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The museum's board of directors decided to try to buy the park.  
The developer, Don Dunham of Sioux Falls, S.D., gave them a 
deadline: raise $5.5 million by Aug. 1. If they fail, the current 
owner, Chuck Long of Sergeant Bluff, is to go forward with the deal 
and sell to Dunham. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents have organized bake sales, lemonade stands, a  
cable-access telethon, golf outings and T-shirt sales. And with the 
help of some deep-pocketed donors, they are optimistic they'll 
reach their goal. 
</P>
<P>
	As of Thursday, park backers had raised $4.5 million and were in  
negotiations for $2 million in state tourism money. 
</P>
<P>
	The park opened in 1889 on Lake Okoboji, a summer playground  
near the Minnesota line for the rich and middle-class of Des 
Moines, Sioux Falls and Omaha, Neb. 
</P>
<P>
	Barely a quarter-mile square, all its attractions can be seen in  
a leisurely two-minute walk. But the cool breeze coming off the 
lake, the tall oak trees providing shade and the 1927 wooden roller 
coaster make Arnolds Park incomparable to the modern variety, its 
fans say. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really a priceless piece of Americana,'' said Jim  
Futrell, editor of the National Amusement Park Historical 
Association's newsletter. The association lists Arnolds Park as the 
oldest operating amusement park west of the Mississippi. 
</P>
<P>
	The country used to be filled with parks in rural resort areas.  
Futrell said only three remain: Arnolds Park, Indiana Beach in 
Monticello, Ind., and Conneaut Lake Park in Conneaut Lake, Penn. 
</P>
<P>
	The children's piggy banks netted $750. Retailers have set  
donation jars next to cash registers, and volunteers sell T-shirts 
at Wal-Mart. 
</P>
<P>
	Several businesses have donated a day's earnings to the cause.  
For the last 52 years, the O'Farrell Sisters cafe has never been 
open on a Sunday. Until July 18, when a pancake breakfast raised 
$2,900. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think anybody realized how much the park meant,'' said  
Cheri O'Farrell. 
</P>
<P>
	No one expected the town to raise $5.5 million in a month from  
bake sales and pancake breakfasts. Organizers knew they had to 
target wealthy donors, and they quickly got two anonymous $500,000 
contributions. Several $100,000 donations followed. Of the money 
collected, $2.9 million has come from donations of $5,000 or 
greater. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know some of those people would be thinking, `Why should we  
support this if the local people don't support it?' Well, they 
don't have that excuse,'' Kennedy said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the developer is a little bewildered that anyone  
would want to buy a park that has lost money for several years. 
</P>
<P>
	``It never occurred to me,'' Dunham said.  
</P>
<P>
	By coincidence, Gov. Tom Vilsack is scheduled to visit this  
Sunday -- the Aug. 1 deadline -- to dedicate a new building at the 
maritime museum. 
</P>
<P>
	``That speaks volumes to me,'' Kennedy said. ``If I was the  
governor, I wouldn't come here the day we're going to lose a 
110-year-old park.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
