<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Texas Probing Possible Hate Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EMORY, Texas (AP) -- Authorities aren't sure whether the killing  
of H.W. Walker -- a black man allegedly tied to a tree and burned by 
a white teen-ager -- was a hate crime. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker's family believes it was. So does the NAACP, which  
persuaded federal authorities to investigate. But to some of the 
1,000 people living in Emory, a hate-crime designation doesn't make 
any difference. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't see how someone that age could do something like that  
to an older person. I was always brought up to respect my elders,'' 
said Lexia Alexander, the cashier at an Emory drug store. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even if this is not a hate crime, killing someone and just  
leaving them there to rot like that is terrible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Walker was reported missing in early May and his charred remains  
were discovered June 2. A 16-year-old suspect was arrested the next 
day and remained in custody Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	NAACP officials believe the young man had ties to an area hate  
group called the Day Walkers. But authorities also are 
investigating whether Walker was killed for money -- he had cashed a 
Social Security check the day he was last seen -- or as the result 
of a drug deal. Walker's family strongly denies he was a drug user. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Attorney Mike Bradford is investigating whether to treat  
the killing as a hate crime. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were contacted by the NAACP, and they gave us information  
that led them to believe this was a hate crime,'' he said. ``We 
think there's enough there to warrant a full investigation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas County medical examiner's office said today that an  
autopsy on Walker had not been completed. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Glenn, head of the Greenville chapter of the National  
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, said he believes 
more than one person was involved because Walker was a big man and 
the suspect is relatively small. 
</P>
<P>
	``The area law enforcement and many people are hell-bent on not  
calling this a hate crime,'' Glenn said. ``But the fact is, it 
probably was and the police just stopped investigating.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some residents of rural Rains County, about 50 miles east of  
Dallas, would like nothing more than for the attention to end. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm real sorry this took place in our county,'' said Allen  
Stuart, the local justice of the peace. ``We've never had this kind 
of bad publicity before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But publicity is just what others are seeking. The victim's  
sister, Daisy Walker Robinson, says she and her family have had 
little cooperation from local law enforcement in their attempts to 
get information on what happened. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're here today because we need answers and we want  
justice,'' she said at a news conference Thursday. ``No human being 
is supposed to be burned and chained the way he was.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, a black man was dragged to his death behind a pickup  
truck in Jasper, in eastern Texas. Three white men were charged in 
his slaying. One was convicted of murder earlier this year and 
sentenced to death; the other two are awaiting trial. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
