<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NRA Leader Comments on Ga. Slayings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Gun-rights advocates gathering Friday  
for a collector's show here said no amount of gun control could 
have stopped Mark Barton from the massacre in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a madman,'' Wayne LaPierre, executive vice president of  
National Rifle Association, said at the association-sponsored show. 
``If you try to confiscate all the guns from the good people, the 
crazies and the criminals will still find a way to get 'em.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barton, an investor, fatally shot nine people at two brokerage  
firms on Thursday after killing his wife and two children earlier 
in the week. The office victims were shot with 9 mm and .45-caliber 
handguns before Barton committed suicide. One of his guns was 
legally registered; authorities are unsure of the other. 
</P>
<P>
	The killings came one day before the NRA -- working with a local  
gun collectors group -- opened a three-day show in Kansas City 
devoted to rare and antique firearms. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 350 merchants spread thousands of guns and wartime  
memorabilia across their tables. Buyers filled out identification 
forms, which merchants fed over the telephone to the 
``Insta-Check'' background check system. Some transactions took 
only minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Gun control advocates called for the NRA to cancel the show,  
citing the Atlanta killings and labeling the Kansas City show the 
NRA's biggest since the Littleton, Colo., shootings that left 15 
dead. 
</P>
<P>
	After those shootings at Columbine High School, the NRA scaled  
back its annual convention in Denver in late April and canceled its 
gun show there. 
</P>
<P>
	``These shows are an attempt to make respectable a point of view  
that is finding less and less favor among Americans,'' said Naomi 
Paiss, a spokeswoman for Handgun Control Inc., in Washington. 
``Every unnecessary massacre makes people more and more aware that 
this country is paying for some people's love affair with guns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Few among Friday's visitors to the convention were willing to  
even talk about gun control, though formal discussions on gun 
rights were planned for Saturday, with a seminar and update from 
the NRA's legislative arm. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gun control is a much-overworked subject, and the laws that  
are on the books are not being obeyed and, in most cases, are not 
being enforced,'' said Frank Gow, a retired Tulsa, Okla., gun shop 
owner who now sells antique firearms at shows once a month. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's insanity from the start. If someone, who hasn't done  
something before, decides to do something, how do you stop them? By 
taking all the rights away from everybody else? That hardly seems 
to be fair,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's discussions are expected to center on the 2000  
elections and efforts to promote laws allowing concealed weapons, 
NRA officials said. Missouri voters rejected such a law earlier 
this year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
