<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 14:10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM To Make Decision on Saab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp., facing increased  
competition on the luxury car front at home and in Europe, is 
expected to exercise its option to take full ownership of Swedish 
automaker Saab Automobile AB within the next six months. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lord knows, they need some luxury brands,'' analyst Gary  
Lapidus of Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co. said Friday. ``It's as simple 
as that. Everyone agrees that Saab is probably best-served by being 
100 percent-owned by General Motors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	GM bought a 50 percent stake and management control of Saab in  
December 1989 for $600 million and made a $100 million investment 
in Saab's operations. Since then, Saab has lost money every year 
except 1994 and 1995, though it's on target to break even this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal, GM has six months from Sunday to exercise its  
option to buy the remaining half of Saab from Swedish holding 
company Investor AB. GM president G. Richard Wagoner Jr. said this 
week that a decision will most likely come later this year rather 
than sooner. 
</P>
<P>
	The negotiations with Investor add to GM's already full plate of  
issues. 
</P>
<P>
	At home, the No. 1 automaker is trying to reverse its long,  
steady slide in market share. Like other global automakers, GM's 
also patiently waiting for a turnaround in the potentially huge 
growth markets of Asia and South America. 
</P>
<P>
	It's negotiating new national contracts and trying to avoid  
strikes with the United Auto Workers and Canadian Auto Workers 
unions. And it's appealing an astonishing $4.9 billion 
product-liability verdict returned by a Los Angeles jury earlier 
this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The pressure on GM to expand its presence in the highly  
profitable luxury vehicle market has increased since rival Ford 
Motor Co. bought Sweden's other automaker, Volvo, earlier this 
year. No. 2 Ford's luxury lineup now includes four makes: Lincoln, 
Volvo, Jaguar and Aston Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	By being fully under GM's control, Saab will benefit from  
sharing manufacturing, distribution, research and development 
resources with the world's largest automaker. GM has invested 
relatively little in Saab over the past decade because of the 
half-ownership situation. 
</P>
<P>
	Once it gains full control, GM's expected to expand Saab's  
modest model lineup that now consists of only two primary models: 
the 9-3 coupe and sedan and the 9-5 sedan and wagon. 
</P>
<P>
	GM's big luxury division, Cadillac, has been struggling to  
maintain market share in the United States and has had little 
success getting Europeans to buy its cars. Cadillacs are perceived 
as too big with too soft a ride for European tastes. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts agree GM will find it easier to develop a global  
strategy for Cadillac and Saab if it has full ownership of the 
Swedish automaker. But some argue that GM is too far behind other 
automakers to expect much from Saab, at least in the next decade. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there's a lot of growth opportunity for Saab,  
primarily because Saab has waited too long to start to broaden its 
lineup,'' said independent analyst Susan Jacobs, who studies the 
luxury market. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacobs argues that Saab's quirky cars appeal to a rather narrow  
niche of U.S. luxury buyers she calls ``young affluents,'' a group 
that she sees shrinking over the next decade. The luxury market 
here already is becoming more concentrated among 50-and-older 
drivers, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Saab is not a strong enough brand to easily move upmarket to  
grab older affluents,'' she said. ``And they don't have the product 
lineup to bring in younger, twenty-something buyers, the kind that 
Audi targets with its A4.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cadillac, meanwhile, is trying to reposition itself from the  
other direction; it's typical buyer is in the 60s or 70s. Ford is 
in the same dilemma with Lincoln and Volvo. Lincolns appeal to 
older drivers, Volvo to those in their 30s and 40s. Both are 
developing new models aimed at the market in between. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lincoln already is there with some product to carve out of  
position for itself in 45- to 65-year-old category,'' Jacobs said. 
``It's ahead of Cadillac in doing that and Volvo will be ahead of 
Saab. Volvo will get an SUV sooner than Saab, and there's more 
potential for Volvo to get a minivan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There's little doubt that Investor would like to shed Saab: The  
conglomerate's recent strategy has been to focus more on industries 
that hold the promise of bigger profits. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a question at what price,'' Lapidus said.  
</P>
<P>
	Though the 1989 deal reportedly set a fixed price for the  
remaining half of Saab, the deal still is subject to negotiation in 
light of changes in currency-exchange rates and Saab's recent 
financial improvement. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 13:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jags' Coach Focuses on Mental Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- No sunglasses. No kneeling. No sitting  
on your helmet. All those rules are passe compared to the newest 
directive at Camp Coughlin 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	No laterals.  
</P>
<P>
	Any player who laterals the ball during Jaguars training camp  
will be fined. It's one way coach Tom Coughlin is trying to send 
the message that mental mistakes, like the one that crippled 
Jacksonville in its playoff game at New York last season, will not 
be tolerated. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's going to be more attention to detail at this camp than  
ever before,'' Coughlin said. ``More attention paid to assignments, 
assignment errors, penalties, that sort of thing. As far as 
pressure for people to perform well, we will never let up from a 
mental standpoint.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While offsides penalties and missed assignments can slowly chip  
away at a team's effectiveness, the kind of mistake the Jaguars 
made in last year's 34-24 playoff loss to the Jets can end a 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Midway through the second quarter, safety Chris Hudson, who is  
no longer with the team, intercepted and returned the ball into 
Jets territory. 
</P>
<P>
	Inexplicably, he tried to lateral to a teammate. The ball  
bounded around and was recovered by the Jets. New York stayed on 
offense, drove for a touchdown and controlled the ball for more 
than 14 minutes of that decisive second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mental errors are one reason we haven't been able to get to  
the next level,'' Coughlin said. ``More players are aware of that. 
They have to work among themselves and put peer pressure on people 
in order to not be a mistake or error guy. The more that happens, 
the better off we're going to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By moving some of the focus to the mental side, several players  
have noticed a subtle downshift in the amount of physical toil they 
endure in Coughlin's camp, once known as the toughest in the 
league. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, the team won't practice in full pads until next  
Monday, letting four practices go by in shells and shorts. Coughlin 
isn't as stringent about a rules list that bordered on ridiculous 
five years ago, when discipline was the best way to find out who 
could play for his first-year expansion team. 
</P>
<P>
	And Coughlin hasn't totally dismissed shortening some practices  
if the temperatures, which have been in the high 90s for two weeks, 
don't let up. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's real surprising,'' said cornerback Dave Thomas, who has  
been present for all five Jaguars camps. ``The first year we 
started, we're in Wisconsin, it's 103 degrees out and we're in full 
pads every day. I'd say there's a big contrast from then to now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quarterback Mark Brunell says he's noticed a difference, too.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if easy is the word,'' Brunell said. ``But I'd  
say we're being smart the first two days. We're not going to go 
right out there and kill ourselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Any slackening on the field is being made up for in the meeting  
rooms. Coughlin said the Jaguars faced too many 2nd-and-12 
situations last year for a team with 11 victories. He wants to 
eliminate the illegal procedure penalties that cause them. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the defense has to learn a new system with new  
terminology under coordinator Dom Capers. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, Coughlin wants to give the players plenty to work on.  
And he doesn't think the new structure will diminish his reputation 
as a drill sergeant. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a gentler Tom,'' Coughlin said. ``I don't know who  
came up with that one. We've just adjusted accordingly. The mental 
part of camp will be just as tough as any camp, just as demanding 
as any camp we've had.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
