<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Architect Learned Stonework on Nile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Long before Richard Morris Hunt designed the  
pedestal for the Statue of Liberty and others for statues in 
Washington, he learned something about stonework as one of the 
first Americans nearly 150 years ago to view the ruins of ancient 
Egypt. 
</P>
<P>
	Today the American Architectural Foundation opens ``A Voyage of  
Discovery,'' a show devoted to Hunt's pioneering trip, taken from 
more than 15,000 of his drawings and records in its files. Hunt 
depicted Egypt in lively colored sketches -- fruit vendors and snake 
charmers, rather than crumbling walls and columns. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of his drawings show how interested he was in the way  
stones were put together,'' said William Stapp, the exhibit's 
curator. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunt, 28 at the time, made the trip from Europe with three young  
American friends. He had spent nearly 10 years in Europe and was 
the first American admitted to the architectural section of the 
Ecole des Beaux-Arts, the leading French art school. 
</P>
<P>
	The 555-mile jaunt up the Nile River took seven weeks in a  
passenger sailboat called a dehabeah, the largest of its type. They 
got as far as Philae -- a major sightseeing center. The next day 
they turned around and took another month to get back to Cairo. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a kind of early frat party,'' Stapp said in an  
interview. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Hunt's drawings, early photographs taken on waxed  
paper by younger brother and lawyer Leavitt Hunt, who had made a 
similar trip a year earlier, help illustrate the show. 
</P>
<P>
	Egyptian architecture had little influence on Hunt, who Stapp  
said felt much more comfortable when he reached Greece after 
traveling through today's Israel, Jordan and Syria. He returned to 
the United States the next year, and one of his first jobs was to 
help enlarge the Capitol. Later he designed the pedestal for the 
nearby statue of President James Garfield. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunt also designed the U.S. Naval Observatory, now the vice  
president's official residence. When he finished the 154-foot 
pedestal for the Statue of Liberty in 1886, it was the world's 
largest single concrete structure. 
</P>
<P>
	His reputation as one of the foremost U.S. architects of the  
1800s comes in large part from mansions built for the wealthy of 
the ``gilded age'' toward the end of the century. Among them are 
Cornelius Vanderbilt's summer cottage called The Breakers, at 
Newport, R.I., and George Washington Vanderbilt's Biltmore Estate 
near Asheville, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	----------	 
</P>
<P>
	``A Voyage of Discovery: the Nile Journal of Richard Morris  
Hunt'' will be on view through Jan. 2, 2000 at the Octagon House, 
where president James Madison lived after British troops burned the 
White House in 1814. Admission is $3 for adults, $1.50 for 
children, students and seniors. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
