<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) -- A Paraguayan human rights group Friday  
called on the United States to make public its files on former 
dictator Alfredo Stroessner. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin Almada, president of the Asuncion-based group Moral  
Tribunal Against Impunity, urged the U.S. government to declassify 
whatever paperwork the American embassy compiled during 
Stroessner's 34-year rule. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be the only way of totally knowing the violations and  
crimes committed by Stroessner,'' Almada said. 
</P>
<P>
	Almada said he hoped the release of the documents could help  
with his group's efforts to bring the 85-year-old former general to 
justice. Stroessner, who lives in exile in neighboring Brazil, 
ruled Paraguay until 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	In June, the CIA released thousands of once-secret government  
documents on Chile's former dictator, Augusto Pinochet. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) -- Soldiers and police were sent to  
protect the Rio Platano Biosphere Reserve in northeastern Honduras 
from illegal logging, the government said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Environmental prosecutor Elmer Lizardo said men have given  
chainsaws to more than 100 peasants so they can cut wood to export 
to the Caribbean. 
</P>
<P>
	``The loggers, who are protected by some government officials  
and politicians, have been operating in the zone for six months 
with modern communication equipment and dozens of men armed with 
AK-47 rifles,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The reserve, declared a U.N. World Heritage Site in 1973, is  
known for its natural diversity and archaeology. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The mayor of the border city of Reynosa,  
accused of corruption, has fled to the United States, Mexican media 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Luis Gerardo Higareda, who has requested a leave of absence,  
crossed the bridge into Hidalgo, Texas, on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	State authorities have obtained an arrest warrant charging  
Higareda in the embezzlement of $870,000 from the city's water and 
sewer commission, which Higareda headed in 1997-98. 
</P>
<P>
	Higareda has maintained his innocence and obtained a federal  
injunction preventing his arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- Cuba's health minister Friday praised the Clinton  
administration's decision to let a drug company with U.S. offices 
work with Cuban researchers on tests for a meningitis vaccine for 
possible future use in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision ``is a just move in favor of children, the  
principal victims of this illness,'' Health Minister Carlos Dotres 
told Cuba's Prensa Latina news agency. 
</P>
<P>
	SmithKline Beecham obtained approval last week from the U.S.  
Treasury Department to test the vaccine against meningitis B. The 
approval is an exception to the 37-year-old U.S. trade embargo 
against Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	SmithKline is a British firm but its testing laboratories are  
owned by a U.S. subsidiary subject to the embargo. 
</P>
<P>
	The vaccine, developed in 1989 in Havana, is 83 percent  
effective, say Cuban investigators. Cuba has sold the vaccine in 
Latin America. Under this new agreement, the vaccine could also be 
sold in the United States and Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico (AP) -- The Chiapas state  
legislature has approved a law granting greater autonomy to Indian 
communities -- a key issue raised by Zapatista rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure was passed Thursday over the objections of  
opposition legislators, who say the government is still failing to 
meet its commitments under a 1996 preliminary accord with the 
rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	Peace talks collapsed shortly after the agreement was signed,  
with the Zapatistas accusing the government of not meeting its 
obligations. The rebels staged a brief uprising in January 1994 in 
the name of Indian rights and greater democracy. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the law passed Thursday, Indian communities would be  
allowed to follow their traditions in choosing their local 
government leaders and would have authority to punish those who 
violate their laws. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
