<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Car Bomb Kills 4 in Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- A powerful car bomb ripped through the  
Medellin offices of the army's anti-kidnapping squad Friday, 
killing at least four people and injuring 20 others. 
</P>
<P>
	The bomb, a truck packed with at least 100 pounds of explosives,  
went off at 3:15 p.m. in a residential neighborhood of Medellin, 
155 miles northwest of the Bogota, said Medellin police spokesman 
Haten Dasuki. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not immediately clear whether the dead were soldiers or  
civilians, or both. The blast leveled the offices of the 
anti-kidnapping squad known by its Spanish initials, GAULA. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a powerful bomb, like the ones that went off during  
Pablo Escobar's time,'' Dasuki said. 
</P>
<P>
	During the 1980s, Colombia's second-largest city was constantly  
rocked by bomb explosions, as the now-defunct Medellin cocaine 
cartel, led by Pablo Escobar, waged a terrorist campaign against 
the government. 
</P>
<P>
	Local television images showed the shattered facades of at least  
a half dozen houses, and vehicles flipped onto their sides by the 
blast -- the second explosion in Medellin in less than two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	On Jan. 19, a Renault sedan packed with explosives was set off  
by suspected leftist rebels in front of the offices of a large 
cement company. There were no deaths, but a night watchman was 
injured. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
