<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> World Leaders Pledge Balkan Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- President Clinton and the  
leaders of some 40 nations pledged today to push economic and 
democratic reforms for the war-torn Balkans in the hopes of 
creating an undivided Europe ``where war becomes unthinkable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The stability pact for Southeast Europe was launched to ensure  
the horrors this city suffered in recent years will definitely 
belong to the past,'' said Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari at a 
conference in this city that's a symbol of war and recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	``The stability pact envisions a Europe at long last undivided,  
prosperous and free -- a Europe where war becomes unthinkable,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton issued a statement stressing that NATO's victory in  
Kosovo will be hollow without a concerted international effort to 
bolster Balkan nations economically. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot say our job is finished when refugees are returning  
to shattered lives,'' Clinton said. ``The transformation and 
integration of this region cannot be achieved piecemeal, one 
province, one country, one crisis at a time. ... The pace will 
certainly vary but we have to move forward together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the session closed, Clinton spoke to Serb, Muslim and  
Croat students who will attend high school together this fall. 
Their school was heavily damaged in the Bosnian war. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is time to build the peace. The war is over,'' Clinton told  
the cheering students, who climbed on chairs to get a better view 
as he arrived. ``We have to build a better peace for Bosnia and all 
of Southeast Europe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the one-day summit, the major powers committed to help  
poor Balkan nations move beyond ancient ethnic hatreds that have 
torn the region many times since World War I. 
</P>
<P>
	The leaders endorsed a pact to promote a healthier future for  
the Balkans. Goals include creating mature democracies and vibrant 
market economies, combating corruption and organized crime and 
preventing fresh wars and refugee crises. 
</P>
<P>
	But none of the economic assistance should go to Serbia as long  
as Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic is in power, Clinton said, 
hoping the conference would further isolate Milosevic and show Serb 
people their best hopes lie with a new leader. 
</P>
<P>
	``We regret that we were not able to invite the Federal Republic  
of Yugoslavia to be present today,'' a closing statement from 
Clinton and the other leaders said. The leaders appealed to 
Serb-led Yugoslavia ``to embrace democratic change and work 
actively for regional reconciliation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The leaders also offered incentives to Montenegro, Serbia's  
western-leaning junior partner in the rump Yugoslav federation. The 
summit participants ``will consider ways of making the republic of 
Montenegro an early beneficiary of the pact and reaffirm their 
support of all democratic forces.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton pointed to progress in rebuilding Sarajevo as an example  
of a Balkans comeback. ``We have a lot more to do, but those who 
are overly critical should come here to see,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton proposed creating a Southeast Europe Trade Initiative  
that would grant duty-free status to many of the region's exports 
to the United States, including footwear, glass products and ball 
bearings. The initiative would cost the United States between $50 
million and $80 million over five years in lost tariff collections. 
The administration intended the duty-free trade privileges as a 
challenge for the European Union to do more in the area of trade 
benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	``What is needed now is that we show in practice the solidarity  
that all who have been participating here have shown,'' Ahtisaari 
said after the sessions ended. 
</P>
<P>
	Ahtisaari and others said the turbulent region was ready for  
democratic change after a decade of ethnic conflict that most 
recently prompted the 78-day NATO bombing over Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Having won the war, we have got to win the peace,'' British  
Prime Minister Tony Blair said. 
</P>
<P>
	In prepared remarks, German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said  
the Stability Pact needed Yugoslavia to be truly successful. But, 
he added: ``It would be a disservice'' to the Yugoslav people ``if 
we now strengthen the regime in Belgrade.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We will be the first to welcome this great country within a  
modern Europe...'' once there is a democratic Yugoslavia, French 
President Jacques Chirac said. 
</P>
<P>
	Milosevic, under indictment as a war criminal, was not invited.  
His political opponents were. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians urged a relaxation of a U.S.-backed ban on all but  
humanitarian aid to the Yugoslavia government because of its 
central position within the Balkans. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin said the world should  
not punish 10 million Yugoslavians by linking aid to Milosevic's 
continued rule. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not happy with the strict linkage to Milosevic,'' he  
said he told other leaders, but he had no ``serious apprehensions'' 
about signing the pact. 
</P>
<P>
	Bodo Hombach, Balkan coordinator for the European Union,  
emphasized the benefits of the Stability Pact. ``Regional 
cooperation is the key theme,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ante Jelavic, one of Bosnia's presidents, said the gathering of  
leaders ``will undoubtedly be motivation for further development of 
democracy, protection of human rights, confidence, stability and 
peace in the region.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, in an earlier meeting with Bosnia's three presidents,  
Jelavic, Zivko Radisic, and Alija Izetbegovic, praised their 
efforts to restore peace and begin economic reforms. Since he last 
came to Sarajevo in December 1997, he said a lot of the city had 
been rebuilt following four years of Serb shelling. ``It doesn't 
even look like the same place I visited two years ago,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	About 4,000 international peacekeepers were deployed to protect  
the leaders. Numerous streets were closed to traffic, and most 
businesses were closed. On roads from the airport, residents were 
directed to stay off their balconies. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the intense security, a gunshot rang out as Croatia's  
president, Franjo Tudjman, was entering the city. A NATO spokesman, 
Lt. Commander David Scanlon, said the round was apparently fired 
accidentally by a peacekeeper's weapon. 
</P>
<P>
	Scanlon said the firing was under investigation and may have  
been caused by mechanical failure. No one was injured. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
