<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  NASA Has Shuttle Fuel Leak Theory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- A loose pin shot out of one of space  
shuttle Columbia's engines moments before liftoff last week and 
probably caused the ship's hydrogen fuel leak, NASA said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The gold-plated, 1-inch pin is the chief suspect, but the space  
agency was continuing its investigation to be certain nothing else 
was to blame, said Bill Gerstenmaier, a senior shuttle manager. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia leaked hydrogen fuel all the way to orbit last Friday.  
The shuttle, commanded by Air Force Col. Eileen Collins, was 
carrying five astronauts and the world's most powerful X-ray 
telescope. 
</P>
<P>
	A larger leak could have caused the damaged engine to shut down  
and forced NASA's first female commander to attempt an 
unprecedented emergency landing. 
</P>
<P>
	Engineers believe the force of engine ignition 6 1/2 seconds before  
liftoff knocked the pin from a tube and down through the combustion 
chamber of the right main engine. The pin -- which was serving as a 
plug in a damaged oxygen-injection line, and resembled a tapered 
nail -- likely slammed against the nozzle. 
</P>
<P>
	By then, the pin would have been traveling at well above Mach 1,  
which is the speed of sound. Engineers have yet to determine its 
precise speed. 
</P>
<P>
	The pin would not have created the three small holes found in  
three side-by-side hydrogen-circulating tubes inside the nozzle. 
Rather, it would have weakened the stainless steel tubes so much 
that they could no longer hold pressure and consequently ruptured, 
Gerstenmaier said. 
</P>
<P>
	The holes were discovered in the right engine nozzle immediately  
after Columbia landed Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Gerstenmaier said the damage -- if it was, indeed, caused by the  
pin -- was on ``the high side'' for such a small object. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia's right engine had two of these pins jammed into  
oxygen-injection tubes as plugs, to keep the liquid oxygen from 
entering the damaged lines. The other pin held. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a rudimentary repair -- plugging damaged oxygen-injection  
tubes -- is not uncommon in older shuttle engines like this one. 
It's the first time, however, that a plug came loose during flight, 
said George Hopson, head of NASA's shuttle main engine program. Of 
the newer engines, only one is plugged. 
</P>
<P>
	Gerstenmaier said it's too soon to know whether the problem will  
delay the next space shuttle flight, a radar-mapping mission by 
Endeavour in September. 
</P>
<P>
	``We really need some more time to look at this and see what the  
implications are,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The broken nozzle tubes have been sent for analysis to  
Rocketdyne in Canoga Park, Calif., where the engines are made. 
</P>
<P>
	Technicians, meanwhile, will search the launch pad in an attempt  
to find the missing pin, which is seven-eighths of an inch long and 
one-eighth of an inch in diameter. It may well be in pieces, 
shattered by the impact. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like looking for the proverbial needle in a haystack,''  
Gerstenmaier said. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA's oldest space shuttle also sustained a momentary short  
circuit five seconds after liftoff, which knocked out the prime 
computers for two of the three main engines. Technicians hope to 
locate the electrical short in the next few days. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 08:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Old National Bancorp Buying ANB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EVANSVILLE, Ind. (AP) -- Old National Bancorp is buying ANB Corp.  
for $212.4 million in stock, the companies announced today. 
</P>
<P>
	ANB shareholders would receive 1.25 shares of Old National for  
each share of ANB they hold. The deal, which must be approved by 
shareholders and regulators, is expected to close early next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The addition of ANB's $784 million in assets will bring Old  
National's total assets to approximately $7.7 billion, and ANB's 24 
offices will give Old National a total of 143 in Indiana, Illinois 
and Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	ANB is the holding company of American National Bank and Trust  
Co. of Muncie, Peoples Loan &AMP; Trust Bank of Winchester, and Farmers 
State Bank of Union City, Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	Old National said it expects to reduce the combined operating  
expenses of the two bank holding companies by 20 percent next year. 
</P>
<P>
	It said it would take a one-time, after-tax charge to 1999  
earnings of approximately $7 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Risinger, Old National's chairman and chief executive, said  
the company will make Muncie the home of the headquarters for its 
eastern Indiana region. 
</P>
<P>
	``We expect ANB to join us without a hitch, just as 38 other  
financial institutions have done since we embarked on the merger 
trail in 1985,'' Risinger said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 13:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Offers Plan for Cutting Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Refusing to cede the issue to the  
Republicans, Vice President Al Gore proposed a more modest tax cut 
Friday aimed at helping middle-class families pay for education and 
retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic presidential candidate called the $792 billion  
GOP plan rolling through Congress ``reckless, unaffordable and 
fundamentally unfair.'' Any tax cut, he said, must be fiscally 
responsible, fair and targeted to working families. He said he 
envisioned a tax cut in the range of $250 billion to $295 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore proposed a new ``401(j)'' program for educational expenses  
that, similar to the current 401(k), would allow families and 
employers to contribute up to $2,500 a year that can be saved and 
withdrawn tax-free. He would give families earning up to $40,000 an 
extra dollar of tax relief for every $2 they contribute. 
</P>
<P>
	To address the tax code's ``marriage penalty,'' a Republican pet  
peeve, Gore proposed doubling the standard deduction for all joint 
filers and increasing the amount a low-income couple can earn and 
still receive the Earned Income Tax Credit. 
</P>
<P>
	He proposed making permanent the tax credit for private  
business' research and development expenses. And, like President 
Clinton, advocated the creation of Universal Savings Accounts, 
allowing individual tax-free retirement savings. Gore didn't say 
how he would pay for the cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	By arguing for narrow tax relief, Gore hoped to lock himself  
into a debate with GOP front-runner George W. Bush without offering 
any plan so deviant from Clinton's policies that it would alter the 
current course of economic prosperity. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't squander the surplus and also keep our economy  
strong. You can't have your cake and eat it, too. Come to think of 
it, it sounds a little like 'compassionate conservatism,''' Gore 
said, poking at Republican presidential front-runner George W. 
Bush's campaign slogan. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore said he would fight to ``keep our prosperity going''  
without punishing those who are doing well. 
</P>
<P>
	The alternative to his plan is a GOP plan that would ``repeat  
the trickle-down tragedies of the past, with a risky, $3 trillion 
tax scheme,'' Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican National Committee chairman Jim Nicholson said Gore  
was trying to ``reinvent'' his record. ``The last time candidate 
Gore promised a tax cut -- during the 1992 campaign -- he turned 
around and socked families with the largest tax increase in 
American history,'' Nicholson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Will Marshall, president of the Progressive Policy Institute, a  
Washington think tank allied with Clinton, said Gore's tax plan was 
designed to hold together the coalition that twice elected Clinton 
-- middle-class suburbanites plus the Democratic party's traditional 
urban base. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Gore campaign clearly wants to start setting the terms of  
the policy debate after several weeks of unflattering stories of 
disarray within the campaign,'' Marshall said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a reference to Bush and Democratic presidential rival Bill  
Bradley, Gore said, ``I believe that it is time for all who seek to 
lead the world's most powerful economy to stand up and be 
counted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Senior Bradley adviser Anita Dunn said the former New Jersey  
senator would not be rushed into outlining a tax policy. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have not been running a campaign that makes its plans in  
reaction to what the vice president's camp does,'' Dunn said. 
</P>
<P>
	Through 18 years in the Senate, and as a chief architect of the  
1986 tax overhaul, Bradley has stood for ``the lowest possible rate 
for the most American workers, with the fewest loopholes and the 
least amount of corporate welfare and special-interest tax breaks 
in the code,'' Dunn said. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan-based Republican pollster Bob Teeter said it made no  
sense -- especially this early in the 2000 campaign -- for Gore to 
put out a tax-cut plan while the White House is waging a tax battle 
with congressional Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	``This sounds to me like Gore, who's behind and losing some  
ground to Bradley, is lunging around for a strategy,'' said Teeter. 
</P>
<P>
	Tax cuts are a Republican issue that would naturally be won by  
Bush, Teeter added. 
</P>
<P>
	But surveys show that with the economy healthy, voters are not  
as interested in tax cuts as improving education and health care. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Carrick, a California-based Democratic consultant, said  
Gore's early pro-tax-cut talk could still buttress his record 
against charges in next year's general election that he is a 
tax-and-spend liberal. 
</P>
<P>
	``What he's doing is more an immunization thing rather than a  
real opportunity for voters to rally around the cause of this 
particular collection of tax cuts,'' Carrick said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
