<DOCNO> APW19990730.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 09:52:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASA Has Shuttle Fuel Leak Theory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- A loose pin in an engine likely  
caused hydrogen fuel to leak during space shuttle Columbia's launch 
last week, NASA said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Engineers believe the force of engine ignition 6 1/2 seconds before  
liftoff knocked the pin out of its tube and down through the main 
combustion chamber, said Bill Gerstenmaier, a senior shuttle 
manager. The pin -- nearly 1 inch long and one-eighth of an inch in 
diameter, and resembling a small gold nail -- then slammed against 
the engine nozzle. 
</P>
<P>
	The pin would not have created the three small holes found in  
three side-by-side hydrogen-circulating tubes inside the nozzle of 
the right engine. Rather, it would have weakened the stainless 
steel tubes so much that they could no longer hold pressure and 
consequently ruptured, Gerstenmaier said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gerstenmaier cautioned that the pin is the leading suspect. A  
couple more weeks of analyses will be needed to verify exactly what 
happened; the broken tubes have been sent to Rocketdyne in Canoga 
Park, Calif., where the main engines are made. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is still a work in progress,'' Gerstenmaier told  
reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia, carrying five astronauts and the world's most powerful  
X-ray telescope, leaked hydrogen fuel all the way to orbit last 
Friday. About 5 pounds of hydrogen seeped out of the three holes 
each second of the 8 1/2-minute climb to orbit. 
</P>
<P>
	If there had been more holes and therefore more leakage, the  
engine could have shut down and NASA's first female space 
commander, Eileen Collins, may have faced an unprecedented 
emergency landing. 
</P>
<P>
	The holes were discovered in the right engine nozzle immediately  
after Columbia landed Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia also sustained a momentary short circuit five seconds  
after liftoff, which knocked out the prime computers for two of the 
three main engines. Technicians hope to locate the electrical short 
once they get inside the shuttle later today. 
</P>
<P>
	Gerstenmaier said it's too soon to know whether either problem  
will delay the next shuttle flight, a radar-mapping mission by 
Endeavour in September. 
</P>
<P>
	The right engine of Columbia had two of these pins jammed into  
liquid oxygen-injection tubes as plugs, to keep oxygen from 
entering the damaged tubes. One pin held; the other fell out. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a rudimentary repair -- plugging damaged oxygen-injection  
tubes -- is not uncommon in older shuttle engines like this one. 
It's the first time, however, that a plug came loose during flight, 
said George Hopson, head of NASA's shuttle main engine program. Of 
the new-style engines, only one has this sort of plug. 
</P>
<P>
	Technicians will search the launch pad today in an attempt to  
find the missing pin, which is made of nickel alloy and plated in 
gold. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like looking for the proverbial needle in a haystack,''  
Gerstenmaier said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 19:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  United States 2, Germany 0 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GUADALAJARA, Mexico (AP) -- For the second time this year, the  
United States upset Germany, the European champion. And this time, 
it wasn't in a lowly exhibition game. 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans didn't even use some of their top players.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're very happy with the result,'' U.S. coach Bruce Arena  
said after Friday night's surprising 2-0 win, which put the 
Americans in the semifinals of the FIFA Confederations Cup. ``We 
prepared well, and we had a great game. I'm proud and satisfied 
with my players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ben Olsen scored in the 23rd minute and Joe-Max Moore in the  
49th as the Americans (2-1) advanced to a Sunday matchup against 
Mexico in Mexico City. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we'll have trouble with Mexico, because it's one of  
the favorites,'' Arena said. ``But we're going to prepare ourselves 
well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coming off a 1-0 loss to Brazil on Wednesday night, the  
Americans rested goalkeeper Kasey Keller, midfielder John Harkes 
and forward Cobi Jones. Forward Brian McBride, one of the few 
bright spots as the U.S. team finished last among 32 nations at the 
World Cup, played only the final 15 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	For the Germans, three-time World Cup champions, it was yet  
another loss in a shockingly bad year. Last summer, they hammered 
the Americans 2-0 in their World Cup opener, but in February they 
lost 3-0 to the United States in an exhibition game. 
</P>
<P>
	Back home, there were calls for massive changes.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm hurt that we weren't able to prepare ourselves better,''  
said German coach Erich Ribbeck, who left start forward Oliver 
Bierhoff back home. ``The so-called little teams can beat us if 
they're better prepared.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Olson scored off a pass from Marcelo Balboa, send it to the left  
of goalkeeper Jens Lehmann. Moore scored on a free kick that went 
into the top right corner of the goal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 19:31:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Dan Marino Reports for 17th Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAVIE, Fla. (AP) -- It's a Miami Dolphins tradition, like the  
pre-game invocation, Don Shula tributes and a lousy running attack. 
When Dan Marino reports to training camp, cameras cluster around 
his locker and he speaks optimistically about the team's chances of 
winning the Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	The annual ritual was repeated Friday. Marino is 0-for-16, walks  
with a limp and could easily opt for the hottest trend in 
professional sports -- retirement. But he'd rather try again for an 
NFL title. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's why you're playing -- to have a chance to win a  
championship,'' he said. ``My position is no different from anybody 
else in this locker room. If it is different, they probably won't 
be here long.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He turns 38 in September, so the ritual -- like Marino -- may be  
on its last legs. But he's back for his 17th training camp, and the 
way things are going around the NFL, that's big news. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry Sanders retired this week at age 31. John Elway quit in  
April at 38. But while they can start working on their Hall of Fame 
speeches, Marino will stick with a familiar refrain. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody on the team is real excited,'' he said. ``This is  
the time of year you have to be. We just have to work hard and turn 
it loose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marino admits this could be his last chance. Despite poor  
mobility because of nine operations on his knees, right ankle and 
right Achilles' tendon, he has started 44 consecutive games. But he 
realizes retirement could be a sack away. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd love to play as long as I possibly can, but who knows?''  
Marino said. ``At this point in my career you have to take it one 
year at a time. You never know what your health situation and 
circumstances around the team are going to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Elway's retirement, Marino is the lone active quarterback  
remaining from the esteemed Class of 1983. Todd Blackledge quit in 
1989, Tony Eason in 1990, Ken O'Brien in 1993 and Jim Kelly in 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Each was a first-round draft pick. Only Elway won an NFL title.  
</P>
<P>
	The Dolphins lost in the Super Bowl in 1984, Marino's second  
season, and haven't been back since. Jimmy Johnson touts this 
year's team as by far the best in his four years as coach. 
</P>
<P>
	``The last couple of years we've had more talent and higher  
expectations,'' Marino said. ``We'll just have to see what 
happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As Marino's 47-page biography in the Miami media guide notes, he  
holds 25 NFL passing records, including career marks for touchdowns 
(408), yardage (58,913) and completions (4,763). 
</P>
<P>
	His right arm shows few concessions to age. Last year, despite  
Johnson's efforts to emphasize the run over the pass, Marino ranked 
seventh in the NFL in touchdowns (23) and yardage (3,497). 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't really see any letup,'' said receiver Tony Martin, who  
was with the Dolphins in 1990-93 and rejoined them this year. 
``He's still throwing the ball with a lot of velocity and still has 
that quick release, and you still have to get your head turned 
around if you don't want it knocked off. He's telling the receivers 
all the time, `I want to see your head spin around like Linda Blair 
in `The Exorcist.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Throwing footballs is still fun, but Marino admits the drudgery  
of training camp becomes more difficult each year. He stood in the 
hot sun for four hours Friday, occasionally taking a snap and often 
looking bored. 
</P>
<P>
	Practice finally ended, and Marino walked swiftly off the field,  
hoping he's headed for the Super Bowl. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 19:31:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
