<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 14:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sharp Eyes IRL Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DOVER, Del. (AP) -- Scott Sharp, a victory short of becoming the  
first Indy Racing League driver to win five times in his career, 
isn't getting many surprise packages. 
</P>
<P>
	And that's good, because he doesn't want any. The 1996 IRL  
co-champion is hoping for a carryover of momentum from a victory 
two weeks ago at Atlanta Motor Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	``You expect the car to roll off the truck fast,'' Sharp said  
Friday after he was third-fastest of 23 cars in practice for the 
MBNA Mid-Atlantic 200. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharp will defend his race title Sunday, when the IRL cars  
tackle difficult Dover Downs International Speedway for the second 
time. A win would break his tie with reigning Indianapolis 500 
champion Kenny Brack and the retired Arie Luyendyk. 
</P>
<P>
	Earning that victory might be difficult, considering the  
practices of IRL points leader Scott Goodyear and Eddie Cheever. 
</P>
<P>
	``The track was very fast, and much better than it was last  
year,'' said Goodyear, whose lap of 182.315 mph was fastest of the 
day. ``We ran in some close contact and the car seems OK.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That was somewhat of a relief to Goodyear, the only two-time  
winner on the circuit this year. He had to make a change early into 
the morning practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``The car we initially came here to run, unfortunately, I had  
problems with it,'' he said. ``It didn't feel right on the first 
two or three warmup laps.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He pitted twice, making chassis adjustments both times to his  
Aurora-powered G Force. 
</P>
<P>
	``We looked for things and couldn't find them, so we had to put  
the backup car out, and only got about 10 minutes in the early 
session,'' he said. ``But things went well in this last session, 
and we're quite pleased.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He should be, insisted Cheever, the wisecracking 1998  
Indianapolis 500 champion. Standing within earshot of Goodyear -- 
whose fastest lap was clocked in 19.746 seconds -- Cheever couldn't 
resist needling him. 
</P>
<P>
	``We spent a few laps running behind Scott,'' he said. ``Once  
again, he's found a way to circumvent the rules. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got the car to beat.''  
</P>
<P>
	Cheever's Infiniti-powered Dallara wasn't far behind. He got  
around in 19.773, at 182.066. Sharp was just four-thousandths of 
second slower, clocking a fast lap of 182.030. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite being one of just two drivers on the lead lap last year  
at Dover, and his move in Atlanta to second place in the series 
standings, Sharp wasn't sure he would be so good again on The 
Monster Mile. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think you address each weekend as a brand new start,'' he  
said. ``Yet I don't think the team could be coming in here with a 
better frame of mind coming off Atlanta.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Speed was contagious for Kelley Racing on a hot, humid  
afternoon. Sharp's teammate, Mark Dismore, was fourth, turning a 
lap of 181.938. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifth was the Dallara-Aurora of rookie points leader John  
Hollansworth Jr., who went 181.378. 
</P>
<P>
	With rules changes reducing rpms from 10,500 to 10,000 and the  
temperature expected to be close to 100 degrees -- making the track 
slicker -- no qualifying record is expected Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Tony Stewart, now the rookie sensation of the NASCAR Winston Cup  
circuit, went 185.204 last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The cars were more stable that a year ago, when bumps in the  
surface -- hardly a factor for the heavier NASCAR machines -- wrought 
havoc to the field. Only 10 of 22 cars were running at the end. 
</P>
<P>
	The high spots have been milled down, and there were no major  
complaints about the track. Greg Ray, whose rear wing came loose, 
was the lone near casualty in practice. 
</P>
<P>
	His Dallara got sideways, but he saved it from hitting the wall.  
</P>
<P>
	``The big man up there helped me out,'' Ray said.  
</P>
<P>
	Eliseo Salazar received multiple fractures when he hit the wall  
in practice last year, and missed the final six races. Robby Unser 
broke his foot, and Steve Knapp wound up with a concussion from a 
rash of crashes that took eight cars from that race. 
</P>
<P>
	``The track is a lot nicer than last year,'' said Jeff Ward, who  
as the eight-place finisher in 1998 wasn't so sure that was good 
for him. ``I didn't have any trouble with it last year, but this 
will probably help some of the guys whose cars didn't get the right 
setup.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
