abilities is being counted on by the Titans to play just one 
position quick enough to revive a dormant pass rush. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will get the job done,'' he promises.  
</P>
<P>
	``I hope he picks it up real quick to help out his coach,'' said  
Jim Washburn, hired as the Titans' new defensive line coach in the 
offseason. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-4 Kearse, who has 4 percent body fat on his 265-pound  
frame, had 16 1/2 sacks in three seasons at Florida, including 7 1/2 in 
1998, splitting time between outside linebacker and end. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee drafted Kearse with the 16th pick in April convinced  
that he can gain about 10 pounds and still retain his speed. Coach 
Jeff Fisher has slotted him at left end, planning to turn him loose 
on opposing quarterbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Titans desperately need someone to pile up some sacks.  
</P>
<P>
	Only Chicago and Cincinnati had fewer sacks than Tennessee's 30  
in 1998. Kenny Holmes, the team's No. 1 pick in 1997, has yet to 
pile up the sacks expected of him. In two seasons, he has 9 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	The Titans also feature some new tackles in veterans Jason Fisk  
and Mike Jones and rookie John Thornton in an attempt to stiffen 
the pass rush. 
</P>
<P>
	But it all starts with Kearse, who now is working in training  
camp learning how to play on the line. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's never really rushed the passer a great deal,'' Washburn  
said. ``You can see him go through a thought process instead of 
just reacting. It's a pretty drastic change from stand-up 
linebacker to a guy down over 300-pounders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kearse hasn't had to think much up until now. He earned his  
nickname at Florida when coaches quickly realized he was too quick 
and big to play safety and switched him to linebacker. 
</P>
<P>
	That was where he picked up his nickname due to an 86-inch arm  
span and hands that stretch 12 inches from thumb to pinkie. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got arms as wide as a pterodactyl and hands as big as  
Andre the Giant,'' said offensive lineman Zach Piller, a teammate 
both at Florida and now with the Titans. ``I've seen him vertical 
jump 40 1/2 inches and run a 4.40 on grass.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To play every down, Kearse also must improve his defense against  
the run. Washburn isn't too worried after seeing him do something 
in that pursuit drill he hadn't seen in his 23 seasons as a coach. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was phenomenal to see a big guy run that fast. But what  
we've got to do is translate all that good athletic ability and 
speed into playing,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	For his part, Kearse is eager to learn and is ready for the  
pressure being heaped on him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love it. I love to have people depend on me,'' Kearse said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 16:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jets Surrounded by Optimism, Urgency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) -- After coming within one bad quarter of  
the Super Bowl last season, the New York Jets opened training camp 
Friday hoping they'll take the next step in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jets began two-a-day practices in the sweltering heat at  
Hofstra University, their first time on the field since the Denver 
Broncos erased New York's 10-0 lead with 20 straight third-quarter 
points en route to a 23-10 victory in the AFC Championship game. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Jets coach Bill Parcells hopes his players focus on the  
accomplishments of last season's 12-4 campaign as they open camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``To go down the stretch like we did last season, that matures  
your team,'' Parcells said of the Jets' five-game winning streak to 
end the regular season, that included wins at Miami and Buffalo. 
``If there's one thing we can carry over from last season, that 
would be it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As usual, Parcells was all business on the first day, reminding  
his team about their much tougher schedule, warning veterans that 
they still had a lot to prove and even cutting a player, 
second-year defensive end Terry Day, after he arrived at camp out 
of shape. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first month of the season is pretty important,'' said  
Parcells of the schedule that has the Jets facing New England, 
Buffalo, Washington, Denver and Jacksonville in their first five 
games. ``I told the team that I wouldn't put the whole season on 
it, but we're playing four playoff teams and we could dig a hole 
for ourselves real quick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Jets' heightened optimism comes with heightened pressure.  
After adding safety Steve Atwater and tight end Eric Green in the 
offseason, and with the retirement of the Broncos' John Elway, New 
York is a favorite to emerge from the AFC. 
</P>
<P>
	But Parcells made it clear that every player needs to be focused  
on winning jobs and not the Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	``I need to see something from everyone,'' he said. ``At some  
point during training camp, if you're a veteran, you need to show 
me you can still do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One potential headache for Parcells are the legal difficulties  
of offensive tackles Jumbo Elliott and Jason Fabini, who were 
arrested along with Cincinnati lineman Matt O'Dwyer after a bar 
fight on Long Island three weeks ago. Elliott and Fabini were 
charged with several misdemeanors. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't condone it, and depending on what happens with the  
judicial system, we'll take our own action, but I'm going to let 
this play out,'' Parcells said. 
</P>
<P>
	Elliott chose not to discuss the incident in depth.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not worrying about it,'' Elliott said. ``I'm worrying  
about concentrating on football, and having a great year, and 
helping the team get into the playoffs. I think everybody feels bad 
about the whole thing. It's one of those things that happened, it 
was very fast, but I don't want to go into any detail.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Parcells said he was encouraged by the Jets' depth at  
linebacker, and for a few hours, he even had a Hall of Fame 
linebacker in camp. Lawrence Taylor, who will be inducted into the 
Hall on Aug. 7 in Canton, Ohio, stopped by at the beginning of 
practice for a visit with his former Giants coach. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's the greatest player I've ever coached,'' Parcells said.  
``I have a tremendous relationship with him and continue to do so. 
I know I wouldn't be here without guys like him and a few others. 
He's like one of my own children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bryan Cox, competing for playing time at linebacker with a crowd  
that includes Mo Lewis, Marvin Jones, James Farrior, Chad Cascadden 
and Roman Phifer, said the Jets will be viewed differently by 
opponents this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because we won last year, we have to understand that no one's  
going to hand us anything,'' Cox said. ``Now we're the hunted. 
Teams are going to come in saying this is the team we have to beat 
for the AFC Championship.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
