<DOCNO> APW19990730.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 19:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stephens Cut by Steelers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LATROBE, Pa. (AP) -- Offensive tackle Jamain Stephens reported to  
the Pittsburgh Steelers' training camp out of shape. Now he's out 
of work -- and, for now, star running back Jerome Bettis is out of 
practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours after Stephens couldn't complete a series of 40-yard runs  
on a 94-degree day, the Steelers on Friday night cut the 1996 
first-round draft choice, who started 10 games at right tackle last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Steelers also got a jolt when Bettis, who has rushed for  
more than 1,000 yards in each of the last three seasons, reported 
to camp with an undisclosed left knee injury. He was injured 10 
days ago while working with track coach Bob Kersee in St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Bettis is expected to be ready for the Sept. 12 opener against  
Cleveland, but the Steelers still placed him on the list for 
players with non-football related injuries. He will miss some 
practice time, but the Steelers are not yet certain how long he 
will be sidelined. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephens may have been the first Steelers player of note to be  
cut on the first day of camp. Coach Bill Cowher clearly was 
disgusted when linebacker Levon Kirkland almost pleaded with 
Stephens to finish a series of 14 40-yard runs -- known as gassers -- 
that every other player completed. 
</P>
<P>
	A few hours later, Cowher and director of football operations  
Tom Donahoe decided Stephens had to go. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were several factors involved in Jamain Stephens'  
release,'' Cowher said Friday night. ``It was obvious he lacked the 
commitment to compete in this camp. I had no choice but to release 
him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If nothing else, Cowher sent the message that, coming off a 7-9  
season and a five-game losing streak, the Steelers cannot tolerate 
complacent players. 
</P>
<P>
	A few hours before, with the on-field temperature at a steamy  
St. Vincent College practice field hitting 138 degrees, a visibly 
spent Stephens barely completed the series of dashes that were run 
a minute apart. 
</P>
<P>
	He jogged through several runs, then plopped down on a Gatorade  
cooler, his white T-shirt soaked with sweat. He wanted to skip his 
final few runs, but the other Steelers wouldn't leave the practice 
field until the 330-pound right tackle finished. 
</P>
<P>
	With Kirkland standing over him, yelling words of encouragement,  
the 1996 first-round draft pick finally struggled off his makeshift 
seat and ran -- it was more of a brisk walk -- one more 40-yarder. 
</P>
<P>
	``A couple of guys struggled, but we run as a team -- and die as  
a team,'' safety Lee Flowers said. ``You want guys you can rely on 
and who won't give up even if it's 110 degrees. That 7-9 team you 
saw last season? That wasn't us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Steelers considered cutting Stephens before last month's  
minicamp to create some room under the salary cap, and Friday's 
performance hastened his departure. 
</P>
<P>
	``He certainly isn't where he was last year,'' Cowher said.  
``It's disappointing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Stephens gone and former starter Justin Strzelczyk out for  
the season with an injured knee, Anthony Brown, rookie Kris Farris 
and Chris Conrad will compete at right tackle. Brown is a former 
Cincinnati Bengals backup. 
</P>
<P>
	Cowher also was disappointed with first-round draft pick Troy  
Edwards, the former Louisiana Tech wide receiver who also appeared 
out of shape. By the end of his sprints, he was finishing 10 yards 
behind the other four players in his group. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
