<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 23:30:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady More Excited About Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BATH, N.Y. (AP) -- Prospective Senate candidate Hillary Rodham  
Clinton says she is ``more and more excited about the prospect'' of 
running and is ``very committed to following through on this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coming about as close as she's come to declaring her candidacy  
since forming her Senate exploratory committee on July 6, Mrs. 
Clinton said at a ``listening event'' at a Bath library Friday that 
she was ``having a very good time'' on the campaign trail. 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady scoffed at an editorial in Friday's Wall Street  
Journal predicting she would skip the race and perhaps find an 
easier job to win, such as head of the World Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm interested in pursuing this very exciting possibility of  
considering a run for the Senate from right here in New York and it 
is the only thing I'm interested in and I get more excited about it 
every day,'' Mrs. Clinton told reporters after talking to local 
residents about their concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the only job I'm interested in right now and the only job  
that I'm pursuing,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, Mrs. Clinton refused to say flatly that she was in  
the race to stay and maintained that she wanted ``to spend more 
time listening to the people of New York'' before announcing her 
candidacy. But she also said she was ``very committed to following 
through on this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Recent polls have shown Mrs. Clinton's once-hefty lead over her  
strongest potential Republican rival, New York City Mayor Rudolph 
Giuliani, vanishing. She now either trails him or is running even 
in the polls with the mayor. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton refused, as she has in the past, to directly attack  
Giuliani. Asked if she felt the mayor was taunting her by traveling 
to Arkansas this week to dramatize the fact that she's never lived 
or worked in New York, she said she was ``not going to comment on 
anyone else's campaign tactics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wading into a controversial area for politicians, the first lady  
did say that while sexual abstinence must be stressed in combatting 
teen pregnancies, especially among young teen-agers, ``we should 
also answer children's questions honestly'' about contraception and 
other issues involving sexuality. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's almost tragic that we have to think about this in terms  
of very young teen-agers, but the fact is whether we like it or 
not, we do,'' she said. ``We have very young teen-agers who are 
often taken advantage of by older boys or men, who don't know how 
to protect themselves, who don't know how to fend off those 
advances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton is on a summer-long ``listening tour'' of New York  
as she considers running for the Senate seat being vacated next 
year by fellow Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan. 
</P>
<P>
	She was winding up her latest foray into New York with a  
discussion of farm issues at Cornell University in Ithaca. She 
returns to the state next week for visits to Jamestown, the 
Buffalo-Niagara Falls area and Rochester. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 22:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  U.S. Women Hoopsters Beat Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Only the outcome brought any  
satisfaction for the U.S. women's basketball team in its Pan 
American Games opener. 
</P>
<P>
	In a game long on effort but short on style, reserves Amy Herrig  
and Michelle Marciniak gave Team USA the lift it needed to get past 
Argentina 63-55 Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just OK,'' said Marciniak, a former Tennessee standout.  
``It was by no means acceptable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The young Americans, most of whom have little international  
experience, shot only 39 percent and committed 24 turnovers. They 
trailed by a point at halftime and led by only three midway through 
the second half before finally grinding down the Argentines. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just not playing good basketball right now,'' said coach  
Nell Fortner, who had just 13 days to get her team ready and 
substituted constantly trying to find the right combination. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to start executing better, we've got to play smarter  
defense,'' she said. ``I think we will, but we've got to start 
doing it soon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Herrig made 11 of 12 free throws while scoring 15 points and  
grabbing nine rebounds. Marciniak scored 13 points and made her 
presence felt early. Entering the game at 15:46 of the first half, 
Marciniak twice grabbed a rebound and drove the length of the court 
for baskets to inject some life into a struggling offense. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a lot of pent-up energy,'' Marciniak said. ``I get  
really anxious sitting on the bench, so when I get in there, I want 
to make something happen. Sometimes it's good, sometimes it's 
bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Far more satisfied with their effort were the American men in  
water polo. By beating Cuba 11-7, they earned the only available 
berth in the 2000 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Humbert of Lodi, Calif., playing with a fever of 101,  
scored five goals. 
</P>
<P>
	``This week hasn't been a lot of fun. We had to quarantine all  
the sick guys,'' Humbert said. ``We've had a lot of coughing, nasal 
congestion and headaches. We've come through some adversity and 
this feels good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Canada beat the U.S. women 8-6 for the gold medal, building a  
3-0 lead and holding on. It was the third straight loss to Canada 
for the Americans. Waneek Horn-Miller scored a hat trick for the 
hosts. 
</P>
<P>
	Michele Smith had a perfect game into the seventh inning for the  
U.S. women's softball team. But she couldn't match teammate 
Danielle Henderson's perfecto of Thursday, yielding a hit to the 
Netherlands Antilles in a 5-0 win. 
</P>
<P>
	Things were bad at the track, on the hockey field and on the  
volleyball court for the United States. Still, the United States 
lengthened its lead in the medals count. 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans have 62 golds, 59 silvers and 38 bronzes for 159  
overall. Canada is at 28-29-38 for 95, with Cuba at 32-27-28 for 
87. 
</P>
<P>
	No American won on the final night of track and field, while  
Cubans took five of the 10 events. High jumper Javier Sotomayor won 
his fourth Pan Ams gold. 
</P>
<P>
	``Spectacular ... fantastic,'' Sotomayor said. ``This is  
great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not so great were U.S. relay teams, which were blanked. Jamaica  
had the year's fastest time in the men's 1,600 and women's 400 
relays. 
</P>
<P>
	When Argentina's men beat the United States 4-1 in field hockey,  
it ended any chances of the Americans qualifying for the Olympics. 
And there'll be no medal for the men's volleyball team, which was 
knocked out when it lost to Venezuela 25-21, 28-26, 25-22. The U.S. 
women could win a bronze, but their shot at gold ended with a 
three-set sweep by Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	Things went better in the ring on the opening night of boxing.  
</P>
<P>
	Flyweight Jose Navarro of Los Angeles started off with a 14-4  
decision over Carlos Valcarcel of Puerto Rico in the new format of 
four two-minute rounds. Welterweight LeChaunce Shepherd of 
Milwaukee, Wis., dominated Isaac Caballero of Nicaragua, stopping 
him in the first round. Caballero received three standing-8 counts 
to end the bout. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first bout is always the hardest,'' Shepherd said. ``I was  
a little anxious.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Americans did win the premier rowing event, the men's eight with  
cox. The U.S. team took control at 500 meters and won by nearly 
three seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	``We made a big move about three minutes into the race and that  
sealed it,'' said Nick Anderson of Omaha, Neb. 
</P>
<P>
	An official from the International Baseball Association told  
several reporters that two Cuban baseball players had defected. But 
Canadian immigration officials and sources close to the Cuban team 
said the official was wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball continues Saturday with the quarterfinals. The United  
States plays Panama and needs to win that game and its semifinal 
match to secure a berth in the 2000 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	The other baseball quarterfinals are Canada vs. Guatemala, Cuba  
vs. the Dominican Republic, and Nigaragua vs. Mexico. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 14:58:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Scared Straight!' Is Remade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WOODBRIDGE, N.J. (AP) -- Kevin Stout came to East Jersey State  
prison 22 years ago. Convicted murderers spit profanities in his 
face, pushed him around and told him never to come back. 
</P>
<P>
	``At that time, you couldn't have told me nothing,'' said Stout,  
who was 15 when he became one of the earliest participants in the 
Lifers' Program, which, first documented in the film ``Scared 
Straight!,'' is meant to keep juvenile delinquents like him out of 
prison. 
</P>
<P>
	He came back to the same prison three years later, a murderer  
and robber, in for life. For years, he kept away from the Lifers. 
</P>
<P>
	Then he woke up one day and thought, ``I don't want anybody to  
be like me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stout, 37, is one of a new group of Lifers who appear in  
``Scared Straight! '99,'' an MTV remake of the gritty documentary 
that shocked the world in 1979 with convicts' expletive-filled, 
intimidating tirades about life in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	This ``Scared Straight!,'' which airs Sunday at 10 p.m. EDT, has  
a new cast of prisoners (those from 1979 are either dead, released 
or transferred), new delinquents, and, since this is MTV, a rock 
soundtrack. 
</P>
<P>
	MTV recruited Arnold Shapiro to make the sequel for an ongoing  
anti-violence campaign. Shapiro, who produced the original film, 
won an Academy Award for best documentary as well as an Emmy. 
</P>
<P>
	He was hesitant at first to take on the new project, worried  
about confusion with another ``Scared Straight!'' film he produced 
for UPN that aired in April. 
</P>
<P>
	But he realized he could reach a generation too young to  
remember the original film, while re-creating the tense 
confrontation between young criminals and the hardened convicts who 
want to stop them before it's too late. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not only is this great television, but it's great sociology,''  
Shapiro said. 
</P>
<P>
	History appears to repeat itself for much of ``Scared Straight!  
'99.'' Twelve boys, ages 12 to 17, walk in cocky and walk out 
shaking, vowing never to return after convicts scream about prison 
rape, filth and lack of freedom. 
</P>
<P>
	``You see the stars at night. I ain't seen the stars in 20  
years,'' one prisoner screams. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will eat you alive,'' warned ``Crazy Chris, the Nightmare  
Man,'' who is serving a double life sentence for murder. 
</P>
<P>
	But while they are younger -- the youngest delinquent in the 1979  
film was 15 -- these kids seem a bit tougher. Not one shed a tear. 
</P>
<P>
	And the inmates are louder, a bit over-the-top and, if possible,  
more profane than in 1979. (MTV plans to air the expletives uncut, 
with warnings.) 
</P>
<P>
	When a bald, muscular inmate grabs the smallest 12-year-old in  
the group and screams, ``Look at me, little boy. What ... you doing 
in my house today?'', it's powerful. But not as powerful as an 
inmate who brought a kid to tears in 1979 by quietly, methodically 
explaining how he'd like to rip out one of his eyes. 
</P>
<P>
	About 50,000 youths have come through ``Scared Straight!'' since  
it was founded 23 years ago. Officials say they can't track success 
rates because juvenile crime records are confidential. Shapiro 
found that 15 of his original 17 delinquents from 1979 stayed 
straight. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1999 film, 10 out of 12 stayed clear of arrests for three  
months. 
</P>
<P>
	But some criminologists say the program doesn't work. Rutgers  
University's Jim Finckenauer conducted a study that showed that 
some delinquents reoffend at a higher rate after going through 
``Scared Straight!'' The inmates' brash performances may actually 
encourage some of the youths, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The message, verbally, to them is don't be like me,''  
Finckenauer said. ``But at the same time there's this undercurrent 
of here's a guy who really got his act together, knows who he is, 
tough guy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Youths who participated in MTV's special said the two-hour visit  
changed them. 
</P>
<P>
	A counselor took Brian Potanovic, 17, of Yonkers, N.Y., to  
prison after he was arrested for graffiti vandalism. Asked on film 
what he would do if he knew he wouldn't get caught, Potanovic said, 
``Kill everyone I had a beef with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At a screening of the film at the prison earlier this month,  
Potanovic appeared chastened, smiling for cameras and politely 
fielding questions from reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not a bad kid,'' he said, ``and I don't intend coming back  
here anytime soon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But one of the boys who was rearrested after three months for  
assault had carved the initials S.U.K. into his arm, which he said 
stood for Serious Untouchable Killer. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the way I am,'' said Melvin, 14. ``They can't change  
me.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	LIVE `DREW': This November, ``The Drew Carey Show'' will  
continue its nontraditional tradition with a live, partly 
unscripted storyline calling for the cast to play improvisational 
games. Airing on ABC Wednesday at 9:30 p.m. EDT, the show will be 
performed three times, once for each time zone (Eastern/Central, 
Mountain and Pacific). The series has featured innovative elements 
before, including elaborate dance numbers, April Fool's contests, a 
guest-starring appearance by Daffy Duck and an episode filmed in 
mainland China. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 22:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  U.S. Women Hoopsters Beat Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Only the outcome brought any  
satisfaction for the U.S. women's basketball team in its Pan 
American Games opener. 
</P>
