<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Interbrew To Get S. Korean Brewery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A South Korean joint venture of  
Belgian brewing giant Interbrew won the court auction Friday of the 
country's ailing Jinro-Coors Brewery Co. for $378.4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The auction ended a battle between Interbrew and Adolph Coors  
Co. of the United States to take over Jinro-Coors, which controls 
20 percent of South Korea's beer market, valued at about $2 billion 
in annual sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Interbrew's South Korean joint venture, Oriental Brewery Co.,  
now will begin discussing details of the takeover with creditor 
banks of Jinro-Coors and likely will sign an agreement next week, 
court officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, Adolph Coors filed for a court injunction  
against Friday's auction, accusing Oriental Brewery of violating 
auction rules. 
</P>
<P>
	The court rejected the charge Thursday and called the auction as  
planned on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Oriental Brewery, South Korea's largest brewery, was the sole  
bidder in Friday's auction. 
</P>
<P>
	Jinro-Coors started out in 1992 as a joint venture between  
Adolph Coors and Jinro, South Korea's 22nd largest conglomerate. 
</P>
<P>
	After Jinro went bankrupt in 1997, Adolph Coors sold its stake  
to Jinro and then tried to take over the whole brewery, which now 
runs under court receivership. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
