<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> All-Tech a Large Day-Trading Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	All-Tech Investment Group Inc., where Mark O. Barton bought and  
sold stocks, is one of the largest companies in the country for day 
traders, investors who attempt to cash in on daily market swings. 
</P>
<P>
	The company based in Montvale, N.J., has 1,500 active trading  
accounts and 22 offices in 15 states. It was formed from an earlier 
company in 1988 as day trading was in its infancy. 
</P>
<P>
	Harvey Houtkin, who joined All-Tech in 1991 and has been the  
chairman and chief executive since 1993, calls himself ``father of 
electronic day trading'' and spreads his message through books and 
seminars. 
</P>
<P>
	Day traders buy and sell stocks, bonds or other securities on a  
moment-to-moment basis, usually using computer terminals linked to 
vast trading networks. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike most investors who hold stocks for the long term, day  
traders try to capitalize on the daily ups and downs of the market, 
using rapid-fire buying and selling. 
</P>
<P>
	At All-Tech, each day trader puts up at least $50,000 in equity  
to open an account, and most paid $5,000 to attend All-Tech's 
30-day training course. 
</P>
<P>
	They trade with their own money and all pay a commission of  
about $25 per 1,000-share trade, or $50 to buy or sell the same 
shares. For instance, someone who buys 1,000 shares for $141.50, 
then sells them at $141.75, would net $200 after commissions. 
</P>
<P>
	But it's also easy to lose money as a day trader. All-Tech  
employs a corporate psychotherapist to help traders deal with the 
daily stresses. 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses said Barton talked about market dips Thursday during a  
shooting spree that left 12 people dead in the Atlanta area. He 
later killed himself. 
</P>
<P>
	The Web site for All-Tech carries this statement: ``Warning:  
Active electronic stock trading is risky. Participants should be 
aware of, and capable of assuming the inherent risks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All-Tech has run afoul of regulators in at least one state for  
allegedly making inflated promises of quick and easy riches. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, the company agreed to pay $278,000 to the Massachusetts  
Investor Protection Fund and investors to settle claims that it 
used deceptive advertising and made unauthorized transfers of 
customers' funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Matthew Nestor, director of the Massachusetts Securities  
Division, said regulators began investigating the company because 
of its ads and literature. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were really concerned that a rosy scenario was being  
created when in fact the vast majority of day traders lose money,'' 
he said. ``Day trading is speculation; it's not investing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the settlement, the company is prohibited for two  
years from having a branch office in Massachusetts and soliciting 
customers from Massachusetts, said Nestor. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Association of Securities Dealers, the parent  
company of the Nasdaq Stock Market, approved a rule Thursday 
requiring firms that promote day-trading strategies to disclose to 
customers -- before they open accounts -- the risks associated with 
that type of trading. The risks include the loss of their entire 
investment. Those using borrowed money to trade could lose that as 
well, the ruling said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
