<HEADLINE> Trade Figure Gave to NRCC, DNC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Several recent big donors to the Democrats and  
Republicans are watching the current congressional session closely: 
They have high interest in legislation under consideration. 
</P>
<P>
	A case in point: The U.S. Chamber of Commerce, which helped lead  
the successful fight in the House earlier this week to approve 
normal trade relations with China. The chamber contributed $37,500 
to the National Republican Congressional Committee during the first 
six months of 1999, according to Federal Election Commission 
records released Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Rifle Association, the nation's leading supporter  
of gun owners' rights, gave $64,000 to the NRCC. The 
Republican-controlled House earlier this year defeated efforts to 
expand requirements for background checks of weapons purchasers at 
gun shows. 
</P>
<P>
	And Bernard Schwartz, chairman of Loral Corp., contributed  
$95,000 to the Democratic National Committee. In May, a 
congressional committee reported that Loral and another U.S. 
satellite manufacturer, and Hughes Electronics, provided China with 
information that could help make China's nuclear missiles more 
reliable. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest giver to both the House Republicans and the DNC  
during the first six months of 1999 was Carl Lindner, whose 
Chiquita brand bananas are at the center of a trade dispute between 
the United States and Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindner and his American Financial Corp. contributed $375,000 to  
the National Republican Congressional Committee and $250,000 to the 
DNC. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton administration officials have been fighting for years  
against European Union rules they say unfairly discriminate against 
bananas grown in Latin America by Lindner's Chiquita Brands 
International and Dole Food Co. In April, the World Trade 
Organization supported the U.S. position and authorized $191 
million in tariffs on European goods in retaliation. 
</P>
<P>
	But Democrats are divided on the issue. In the House, some  
Democrats have introduced legislation that would stop the United 
States from imposing tariffs on European products as part of the 
fight. Their bill, introduced in March, has gone nowhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, the Democratic National Committee reported raising  
$24.5 million, including $9.7 million in soft money, in the first 
six months of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Despite the Republican Party's best attempts to bankrupt the  
DNC through dozens of partisan, taxpayer-funded investigations, the 
Democratic Party is in strong financial shape,'' Democratic 
National Chairman Joe Andrew said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican National Committee reported raising $30 million,  
with $8 million in ``soft money'' -- unregulated contributions from 
corporations, labor unions and individuals that do not fall under 
federal limits. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our fund-raising success is a sure sign that Republicans are  
energized and excited about our ideas and candidates,'' Republican 
National Chairman Jim Nicholson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The NRCC reported raising nearly $28 million through June 30,  
$9.8 million of it in soft money. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee, meanwhile,  
raised $17 million, including $9 million in soft money. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
