<DOCNO> APW19990730.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 19:31:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Eddie DeBartolo Gives Up 49ers Stake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STOCKTON, Calif. (AP) -- Eddie DeBartolo gave up his stake in the  
San Francisco 49ers on Friday, leaving the club in his sister's 
control and resolving a feud over the family's billion-dollar 
financial empire. 
</P>
<P>
	The tentative agreement divides the assets of the Youngstown,  
Ohio-based Edward J. DeBartolo Corp. and allows DeBartolo and his 
sister, Denise DeBartolo York, to go their separate financial ways. 
</P>
<P>
	Once the deal is signed, lawsuits filed by the siblings against  
each other will be dismissed, according to a source close to the 
negotiations. The suits, filed in federal court in Ohio, are on 
hold. 
</P>
<P>
	Sam Singer, a spokesman for the corporation, confirmed Friday a  
tentative deal had been reached. It still must be approved in 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	Rick Rice, a spokesman for Eddie DeBartolo, said some details  
still needed to be worked out. 
</P>
<P>
	``They may be close to an agreement but any announcements are  
premature at this moment,'' Rice said. 
</P>
<P>
	The tentative deal ends a messy battle between the DeBartolos  
that arose from Eddie DeBartolo's entanglement in a Louisiana 
gambling fraud scandal, which led to a guilty plea for failing to 
report a felony. He was also serving a year-long suspension imposed 
by NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue last March. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a sad occasion. We just have to move,'' 49ers general  
manager Bill Walsh said following the team's training camp workout 
in Stockton. ``We've all been observing and watching, and finally 
an agreement has been made.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The siblings owned equal shares of the corporation, which was  
the nominal owner of the 49ers. 
</P>
<P>
	Denise DeBartolo York had said for some time that she wanted to  
divide the family holdings because she and her brother had 
radically different business philosophies. 
</P>
<P>
	Under terms of the agreement, Denise Debartolo York and her  
husband, John York, now the 49ers executive vice president, have 
control of the team. The couple also retained three racetracks and 
the corporate offices and name. 
</P>
<P>
	In Friday's agreement, Eddie DeBartolo acknowledged owing the  
corporation $94 million. He received stock and real estate holdings 
and interest in some development projects, Singer said. 
</P>
<P>
	DeBartolo, who is in the process of selling his Atherton home  
and moving to Florida, wasn't immediately available for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could see this coming. All of us did,'' Walsh said. ``I wish  
Eddie well. There will be no changes except for tightening certain 
aspects of the business but certainly not shortchanging players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the deal kept the team in the family, it ends Eddie  
DeBartolo's 22-year association with the club. A flamboyant, 
demanding owner, DeBartolo was known as a free spender who lavished 
money on his players and expected championships in return. 
</P>
<P>
	The club won five Super Bowls with DeBartolo in charge, the last  
coming in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Denise DeBartolo York co-owned the team during most of that time  
but was a silent partner to her brother. 
</P>
<P>
	There are no plans to sell the club.  
</P>
<P>
	``The Yorks have always said that if they were to get the crown  
jewel of the corporation, and the 49ers are the crown jewel, that 
they would keep the team, and keep the team in San Francisco,'' 
Singer said. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal was completed Friday during a telephone call with Judge  
Daniel Polster, a federal judge in Ohio, who held several hearings 
with the sides during the past two months and had urged them to 
settle. 
</P>
<P>
	Final court approval could take several months.  
</P>
<P>
	The NFL suspended DeBartolo through February 2000 and fined him  
$1 million for his role in a Louisiana gambling and bribery case. 
DeBartolo pleaded guilty to failing to report a felony. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, York sued her brother in San Francisco, charging him  
with reneging on a $94 million debt to the family company and 
cutting an improper side deal with a prospective developer on a 
stadium-shopping mall project. 
</P>
<P>
	DeBartolo responded with a lawsuit in Ohio, accusing her of  
breach of contract. 
</P>
<P>
	In San Francisco, the feud has stalled the stadium project  
approved by voters in June 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0288 </DOCNO>
