<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 17:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hatch Urges Straw Poll Vote Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch, citing  
persistent reports of campaign mischief, asked Iowa Republican 
leaders Friday to tighten ballot security for next month's straw 
poll. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even the merest hint of such activities, true or not, threaten  
the integrity of the straw poll,'' Hatch wrote Iowa Republican 
Party executive director Dee Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch, who wants the Republican presidential nomination, said  
participants in the straw poll should be required to produce a 
photo ID. He also told Stewart that all of the presidential 
campaigns should be challenged to sign an affidavit that they 
aren't paying anyone to vote or ``coercing people'' for support. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been hearing some rumors'' of coercion, Hatch told  
reporters as he opened a five-day campaign swing in Iowa, where 
precinct caucuses launch the nominating season. ``That kind of 
undermines the integrity of the process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Competition has been intense heading into the state's Aug. 14  
straw poll. There have been occasional reports of campaign 
misbehavior, generally leaked by rival campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Gov. George W. Bush used $50,000 in unregulated ``soft''  
money to lease space and buy tickets for the event, but replaced it 
with campaign money after news accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	And publisher Steve Forbes has been accused of seeking to hire  
temporary workers to vote for him. He vehemently denied the 
allegation, which led to the firing of the head of the state's 
Christian Coalition. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch argued for some limits on what campaigns can do to get  
backers to Ames for the straw poll. While it's understood that 
campaigns will provide many free tickets, direct payments are out 
of line, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately, in this election it looks to me like some  
people are trying to buy it,'' said Hatch. ``The rumors are that 
George Bush is going to spend something like $4 million on this. I 
don't know how he can do it without buying votes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``In order to protect the integrity of the straw poll, I urge  
you to take measures to ensure that no voting participants in the 
straw poll are being paid or coerced to attend and vote for any 
particular candidate,'' Hatch said in his letter. 
</P>
<P>
	State Republican officials have limited voting to Iowans, and  
said they'll demand photo identification. They also say strict 
ballot security measure are being employed, but won't discuss them 
publicly. Making the security measures public would give campaigns 
time to devise a method around them, officials argue. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to buying $25 tickets for backers, most campaigns  
are organizing bus caravans to bring backers to Ames, and plan 
giant parties with food and entertainment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 18:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Baseball Team 2 Wins From Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- With a whacky four-game round-robin  
series finally over, the U.S. baseball team must now navigate its 
way to Sydney. The road might not be as difficult as expected. 
</P>
<P>
	In the win-or-go-home portion of the Pan American Games that  
begins Saturday, the Americans expected to confront talented teams 
from Cuba, Canada and the Dominican Republic. None will be in the 
opposite dugout in either the quarterfinals or semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	And if the Americans get to Monday's finals, they also get a  
ticket to the 2000 Olympics next September. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody could have drawn the tournament up this way. Cuba,  
Canada and the Dominican would all have to play each other,'' said 
John Patterson, the U.S. starter Saturday night in the 
quarterfinals against Panama. 
</P>
<P>
	Using minor leaguers in international play for the first time,  
the United States needs two victories to qualify for the Olympics. 
If the Americans can get by Panama in the quarters, they would face 
either Mexico or Nicaragua in the semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need two games to qualify and three to take the gold,''  
Patterson said. ``Our sights are set on the gold. And that's the 
way we're looking at it. We're not just trying to qualify.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Host Canada won all four games in the opening pool series,  
beating both the United States and Cuba. The Canadians face winless 
Guatemala in the quarters. 
</P>
<P>
	World champion Cuba, shadowed by rumors of defection, split its  
first four games and is pitted against the Dominican in the 
quarterfinals. The United States is more than glad to miss the 
Dominican, which beat the Americans twice in a warmup tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Not that it seems to matter who the opponent is.  
</P>
<P>
	If there is one thing the Americans have learned from their  
brief taste in the international forum, it's that anything can 
happen. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a different avenue,'' said third base coach Jackie Moore,  
who at age 60 has been around baseball all his life. 
</P>
<P>
	``No matter how long you're in the game, you always see  
something new. The other night the players from Brazil were 
cheering and singing in their dugout. That's what baseball is all 
about. 
</P>
<P>
	``And the teams here are better than I thought they would be.''  
</P>
<P>
	The United States opened pool play with a crushing 7-6 loss to  
Canada in 11 innings. The Americans led 6-3 in the top of the 11th 
before Canadian manager Ernie Whitt held the game up for 30 minutes 
arguing and protesting the number of trips he was allowed to make 
to the mound. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada, also with a roster of minor leaguers, then scored four  
runs after two were out in the bottom of the 11th. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States came back to beat Mexico 5-1 and it was  
manager Buddy Bell's turn to question the rules. He twice came out 
of the dugout, wondering why a Mexican pitcher who had two 
spit-covered baseballs taken away from him by umpires wasn't 
ejected. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell was thrown out of the next game for arguing in the ninth  
inning against Cuba with the game tied 5-5. Minutes later, Marcus 
Jensen hit a three-run homer to spark a 10-5 U.S. victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Then the Americans struggled mightly against winless Brazil, the  
only team in the nine-country tournament not to quality for the 
quarters. The United States eked out a 3-2 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are quite a few things different,'' Bell said. ``The  
interpretation of the rules here is a little different than what we 
are used to. We're used to bottom line stuff where there really is 
no negotiating.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Bell, who played 18 years in the major leagues and also  
managed there for 2 1/2, has no complaints so far about the unique 
experience. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we've all enjoyed it,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't matter who you play. The intensity of this thing  
has been incredible. I think we would all agree with that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 08:08:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Holds More in Sect Crackdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Chinese police today detained at least 20 people  
and beat one man outside the compound where China's leaders live 
and work, while authorities stepped up a campaign to crush a banned 
meditation sect. 
</P>
<P>
	Two police officers, one wielding a wooden pole and the other  
using his fists, beat the man outside the northwest gate of the 
tightly guarded leadership compound, known as Zhongnanhai. 
</P>
<P>
	The man, who was eventually pulled onto a bus by police, had  
fought back with his fists. One police officer had blood on his 
neck and the man's face appeared swollen following the beating. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 20 other detainees were held in a bus outside the  
red-walled leadership compound, the focus of earlier protests by 
the Falun Gong, which last week was banned as a threat to the 
government. Later, the detainees were transferred to smaller vans 
and driven away. 
</P>
<P>
	The detentions came a day after China issued an arrest warrant  
for the U.S.-based leader of the meditation group on charges of 
spreading superstition. 
</P>
<P>
	The warrant for Li Hongzhi was read out on state television. It  
wasn't clear whether China would seek to extradite Li, a former 
Chinese government clerk who now lives in New York City. State 
media, however, reported that China would seek unspecified 
cooperation from member countries of Interpol, the international 
police agency. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. State Department said it would not extradite Li because  
the two countries have no extradition treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 2 million confiscated Falun Gong publications, videos  
and cassettes were destroyed Thursday by dozens of provinces and 
cities nationwide, the state-run Xinhua News Agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	Falun Gong is one of many schools of qigong, a traditional  
practice intended to improve health through exercise, mediation and 
attempts to channel unseen forces. Falun Gong's teachings draw on 
martial arts, Buddhism and Taoism. 
</P>
<P>
	Official estimates had put the group's membership as high as 70  
million -- 9 million more than the Communist Party -- although the 
government has since said the group has just 2 million members. 
</P>
<P>
	The crackdown was precipitated by protests that began with a  
silent vigil on April 25 by more than 10,000 Falun Gong devotees 
outside the leadership compound in central Beijing. The group said 
it was protesting official harassment. 
</P>
<P>
	Li, who founded Falun Gong in 1992, has denied government  
accusations of having political ambitions. He also has denied 
organizing the April gathering or other protests and has told 
reporters he didn't even know about them in advance. 
</P>
<P>
	China's arrest order accused Li of organizing demonstrations  
without required permits, Xinhua said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Public Security Ministry also said Li ``spread superstition  
and malicious fallacies to deceive people, resulting in the deaths 
of many practitioners,'' Xinhua said. It claimed the group was to 
blame for 743 deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	Li has denied any connection to deaths of members who he said  
might already have been ill or unstable. 
</P>
<P>
	Falun Gong treats illness as a result of evil in a past life and  
discourages the use of medicines. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 07:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Malcolm X Grandson Closely Watched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) -- A Family Court judge has ordered tighter  
security around Malcolm X's grandson, who has escaped three times 
from juvenile detention after being sent there for setting a fire 
that killed his grandmother. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is a proven risk for being absent without leave,'' County  
Attorney Alan Scheinkman said in court Thursday of Malcolm Shabazz. 
</P>
<P>
	Shabazz, 14, set a fire two years ago that killed his  
grandmother, Betty Shabazz, who was Malcolm X's widow and a civil 
rights leader herself. He pleaded guilty to the juvenile 
equivalents of manslaughter and arson and has been in detention 
ever since. 
</P>
<P>
	Since February he has escaped repeatedly. On Wednesday, he fled  
Woodfield Cottage -- a juvenile facility on the grounds of the 
county jail in Valhalla. He was missing for three hours before a 
policeman spotted him in a taxicab nearby. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Janet DiFiore approved ``secure detention,'' but would not  
grant Scheinkman's request that Shabazz be kept indoors. She said 
she would leave it up to Woodfield Cottage to ``take the steps 
necessary to keep the young man safe and secure.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 14:50:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fullback Evans Fits in With Ravens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WESTMINSTER, Md. (AP) -- Most of the Baltimore Ravens have spent  
the first few days of training camp adjusting to a new coach and a 
vastly different offensive scheme. 
</P>
<P>
	Chuck Evans, however, has been hustling through practice as if  
he's been doing these same drills throughout his entire NFL career. 
</P>
<P>
	As a matter of fact, he has.  
</P>
<P>
	Evans, the Ravens' new starting fullback, and coach Brian  
Billick both left the Minnesota Vikings for Baltimore during the 
offseason. Billick was hired in December, and three months later 
Evans severed his six-year relationship with the Vikings by signing 
as a free agent. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been the only offensive coordinator I've had my whole  
career, and now he's the head coach,'' Evans said Friday. ``How 
much better can it get?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Evans should find life even more enjoyable once the regular  
season begins. After being selected by the Vikings in the 11th 
round of the 1992 draft, he was used almost exclusively in 
Minnesota as the lead blocker for the halfback. That will be his 
primary role in Baltimore, with one important exception. 
</P>
<P>
	``He will carry the ball more here, sort of like Leroy Hoard did  
for us in Minnesota,'' Billick said. ``I know that's one of the 
reasons Chuck came here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Actually there are plenty of reasons that Evans chose Baltimore,  
where he will replace the little-used Roosevelt Potts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We played this team last year and I know they have a good  
young defense and a lot of talented players. It's going to be a 
good team,'' Evans said. ``Plus, knowing the coach, I can hit the 
ground running. 
</P>
<P>
	``Playing here gives me a chance to get a few more carries. But  
I come from a system where there are a lot of stars and just one 
football.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When he did get his hands on the ball in Minnesota, he never  
lost it. 
</P>
<P>
	In 207 career touches (receiving, running and returning) Evans  
has never fumbled. His career numbers -- 118 carries for 364 yards 
and 78 catches for 531 yards -- are not overly impressive. But his 
value to a team cannot be measured by mere statistics. 
</P>
<P>
	Evans, 32, paved the way for Robert Smith to run for 1,187 yards  
and six touchdowns last year. He'd like to see the end zone himself 
a few times this year, but he knows his main job is to make sure 
that Priest Holmes has a hole to run through. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a fullback. It would be nice to get the ball on a carry or  
a catch, but I like to block for the guys too,'' Evans said. ``If 
Priest is breaking runs for touchdowns, then that means I'm doing 
something right. It may be unsung or unseen, but the football 
people know what I did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Evans put up some good numbers at Clark Atlanta University,  
where he ran for 871 yards and 15 touchdowns as a senior. He was 
drafted by Minnesota as a halfback, but because the Vikings were 
loaded with ball carriers Evans was almost immediately shifted to 
fullback. 
</P>
<P>
	He's been working with Billick ever since, and so his unofficial  
role in this training camp is as a liaison between the coach and 
players who have yet to become fully acquainted with Billick's 
practice regimen, offensive system and idiosyncrasies. 
</P>
<P>
	``He knows how our camps work and he knows what my expectations  
are,'' Billick said. ``I can check with Chuck to see how we're 
doing, how they're absorbing it and how they're feeling. He's a 
great asset for the players, and for me as well.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
