<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Personal Income Soars in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans' personal income galloped ahead  
faster than spending in June, the government said Friday. New home 
sales, meanwhile, rose 3.1 percent as buyers rushed to beat slowly 
rising mortgage rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Both reports, economists said, were an outgrowth of a healthy  
U.S. economy, a low unemployment rate, a strong stock market and 
benign inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither report was expected to raise eyebrows at the Federal  
Reserve, which nudged up interest rates June 30 in a pre-emptive 
strike against inflation, economists said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the Fed would view them as neutral,'' said First Union  
economist Mark Vitner. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets have been jittery, however, about the  
possibility of further rate increases. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department said personal income, which includes  
wages, interest and government benefits, rose a 
faster-than-expected 0.7 percent last month. It was the biggest 
income gain since a 0.9 percent rise in November and marked the 
first time since January that income growth outpaced the rise in 
spending. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, income rose 0.3 percent, while spending went up 0.6  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	June's income growth reflected gains in wages and salary as well  
as from interest and dividends. A surge in farm income, stemming 
from federal subsidy payments to farmers, boosted overall income 
growth. Still, excluding these payments, income would have gone up 
0.5 percent, economists said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Americans tempered their spending somewhat.  
Spending went up just 0.3 percent in June, a little less than many 
analysts had expected. That too was the smallest increase since 
November, when spending rose 0.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Consumers are still in a buying mood but not as aggressive,''  
said Gary Thayer, chief economist with A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists attributed the moderation in spending to a number of  
factors including a recent rise in interest rates and a decline in 
mortgage refinancing. People who refinance homes end up with extra 
money which leads to higher spending, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	Because consumer spending has outpaced incomes repeatedly, the  
nation's savings rate -- saving as a percentage of after-tax income 
-- has set a string of record lows this year. 
</P>
<P>
	In June, the savings rate was minus 1.0 percent, better than the  
record low of negative 1.4 percent set in May. 
</P>
<P>
	A major reason for the negative savings rate, economists say, is  
that the strong stock market is boosting Americans' net worth and 
making them feel more comfortable about dipping into savings to pay 
for the spending spree. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate report, sales of new single-family homes rose in  
June to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 929,000 units, better 
than forecast, the Commerce Department said. In May, new-home sales 
fell 4.1 percent to 901,000 units, not so bad as the government 
previously estimated. 
</P>
<P>
	``Despite rising interest rates, home sales have remained strong  
because home buyers are rushing to lock in current interest rates 
in the fear that rates might climb higher,'' said Merrill Lynch 
economist Karen Dexter. 
</P>
<P>
	The average interest rate on a 30-year fixed rate mortgage this  
week was 7.70 percent, up from 7.52 percent last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase in sales pushed prices up as well. The median price  
for a new home -- meaning half of all homes sold in June for less 
and half for more -- rose 4.7 percent to $157,000, up from May's 
median price of $149,900. June's price was the highest since 
February's record of $159,900. 
</P>
<P>
	``When people buy homes, they also buy things to put into  
them,'' said Vitner. 
</P>
<P>
	Spending on nondurable products, such as food and fuel,  
increased 0.4 percent in June, less than the 0.5 percent increase 
the month before. 
</P>
<P>
	But spending on durable goods -- big-ticket manufactured items  
expected to last at least three years, such as washing machines and 
cars -- was flat in June, following a sharp, 2.2 percent gain in 
May. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
