<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ahanotu Signs 6-Year Deal with Bucs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Tampa Bay's Chidi Ahanotu became one of the  
NFL's highest-paid defensive ends Friday when he signed a six-year 
contract worth about $5 million per season. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, which included a signing bonus of more than $5  
million, continued the club's pattern of locking its players into 
long-term contracts rather than pursuing high-profile free agents 
from other teams. 
</P>
<P>
	The Buccaneers designated Ahanotu, 28, as their franchise player  
in February, making a tender worth just under $4 million that the 
seventh-year pro could have accepted as a one-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
	If the 6-foot-2, 285-pound end opted to play for the tender, the  
entire $3.95 million would have counted against this season's 
salary cap. By accepting a multiyear deal, it cleared room to sign 
the club's remaining unsigned rookie draft picks. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's flashier and spicier to be able to go out and get  
somebody else's player and bring him in here and say we've got 
somebody new,'' general manager Rich McKay said. ``But for us, we 
felt we should stick to our plan of trying to sign our guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ahanotu had a career-best 10 sacks in 1997, helping Tampa Bay  
earn a playoff berth for the first time in 15 years. When efforts 
to sign him to a contract extension failed after that season, the 
Bucs turned their attention to working out a long-term deal with 
fullback Mike Alstott. 
</P>
<P>
	Re-signing Ahanotu became a priority again last fall, despite a  
shoulder injury that forced him to sit out all but four games in 
1998. He had started at least 10 games in each of his first five 
NFL seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``A year and a half is a long time to go not knowing what your  
future is going to be,'' Ahanotu said, adding that his shoulder is 
fine and he's ``chomping at the bit'' to play again. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal makes Ahanotu the second highest-paid player on the  
Bucs behind defensive tackle Warren Sapp, who signed a contract 
worth $6 million per season last year. It also placed him in the 
top five among defensive ends. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great day in Tampa Bay,'' the defensive lineman said  
before McKay interrupted to add: ``For Chidi Ahanotu.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The deal clears the way for the Bucs to sign first-round draft  
pick Anthony McFarland and second-round pick Shaun King before the 
start of training camp Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	McKay met with McFarland's agent, Karl Bernard, this week and  
the two sides could be close to an agreement. The general manager 
expects to sign King this weekend, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't expect anybody to be late,'' McKay said. ``We clearly  
have (salary cap) room to do it now, and I think we have the 
necessary rookie pool to do it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
