<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Mostly Mixed; Down Vs. Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar slipped to its lowest level against  
the yen in five months Friday as another decline on Wall Street 
caused concerns that demand for the dollar could fall if investors 
pull funds out of U.S. markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was quoted at 114.48 Japanese yen in late New York  
trading, down from 115.40 yen late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks fell for a second day running Friday on continued fears  
that wage growth data could lead Federal Reserve Chairman Alan 
Greenspan to consider higher interest rates in order to curb 
inflation pressures. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was mixed against other currencies. The euro was  
quoted at $1.0705, down from $1.0730 late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4907 Swiss francs, up from  
1.4889, and 1.5046 Canadian dollars, down from 1.5060. The British 
pound rose to $1.6221 from $1.6189. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Friday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8272 German 
marks, up from 1.8228, and 6.1275 French francs, up from 6.1125. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
