<DOCNO> APW19990730.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 13:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Display Spans Centuries of Black Art </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A painting by a free black artist of a white  
family in a slave state almost 200 years ago highlights a display 
of African-American work that opens Saturday at the Corcoran 
Gallery of Art. 
</P>
<P>
	Little is known about the artist, Joshua Johnson, who called  
himself a ``self-taught genius.'' He painted in Baltimore from 1797 
to 1825 and is the first known black artist in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``He painted both blacks and whites and advertised his services  
in the newspapers,'' said Renee Ater, the Corcoran's assistant 
curator of American Art, discussing the exhibit Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Corcoran owns his portrait of Mrs. Hugh McCurdy and her two  
young daughters, one of about 80 known paintings by him -- many of 
them featuring prosperous Baltimore families. 
</P>
<P>
	At the other end of the two centuries of work depicted in the  
show is a huge controversial silhouette of cut black paper on 
white, called ``Roots, Links, Inc.,'' done in 1997 by 28-year-old 
Kara Walker. 
</P>
<P>
	The picture has roused criticism in the black community, Ater  
said, because ``its subjects of slavery and racial and sexual 
taboos are considered by some as presenting too negative an 
image.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``My work reveals images that I too am shocked to encounter in  
the dark alleys of my imagination,'' Walker has said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Aaron Douglas' ``Into Bondage,'' hazy blue figures with  
bright orange handcuffs look toward shave ships in the background. 
Douglas, a key figure in the ``Harlem Renaissance'' of the 1920s, 
painted it for the Texas Centennial Exposition of 1936. 
</P>
<P>
	Henry O. Tanner, an expatriate who lived in Paris, alludes to  
the religious background of much African-American life in his ``The 
Good Shepherd.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Colescott's ``Auvers-sur-Oise -- Crow in the Wheatfield''  
refers to modern art with its distorted but recognizable portrait 
of Vincent van Gogh, a bandage over the ear he tried to cut off in 
a moment of insanity. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Celebrating the Legacy'' will be at the Corcoran Gallery of  
Art through Sept. 22. The gallery suggests a donation of $3 for 
adults, $1 for seniors and students and $5 for groups of any size. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
