<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Mixed; Gold Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was mixed against other major  
currencies in European trading Friday morning. Gold rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0703, up from $1.0673 Thursday. Later  
in afternoon trading in New York, the euro traded at $1.0684. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday  
included 115.04 Japanese yen, down from 115.20; 1.4921 Swiss 
francs, down from 1.4957; 1.5036 Canadian dollars, down from 
1.5112. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6206, up from $1.6066.  
</P>
<P>
	In afternoon trading in New York, the dollar bought 114.75 yen,  
and the pound was worth $1.6192. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8274 German marks, down from 1.8325; 
6.1287 French francs, down from 6.1459; 2.0590 Dutch guilders, down 
from 2.0648; 1,809.09 Italian lire, down from 1,814.18. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold dealers in London fixed a recommended price of $256.75 bid  
per troy ounce at midmorning, up from $254.80 on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Zurich the bid price was $256.55, up from $254.05.  
</P>
<P>
	Gold rose $2.30 in Hong Kong to close at $256.95.  
</P>
<P>
	Silver opened in London at $5.39 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$5.32. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
