<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Pay Fine in Contempt Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- After five years of court battles and  
almost $1 million in remuneration from President Clinton, it's now 
up to Paula Jones' legal team to decide whether to push for more or 
put an end to her claims. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's lawyers say the president is willing to comply with a  
federal court order Thursday to pay about $90,000 in penalties for 
giving false testimony about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	But some in Mrs. Jones' camp, who had sought nearly $500,000,  
say they may appeal for more. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel the court vastly underestimated the reasonable amount  
of time'' spent working on perjury and obstruction-of-justice 
issues, the Dallas-based law firm of Rader, Campbell, Fisher &AMP; Pyke 
said in a statement. ``In sum, we continue to assert that Ms. 
Jones' attorneys are entitled to the full amount of fees claimed, 
if not more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Lavallee, administrator of Clinton's legal fund, said the  
trustees wouldn't consider whether they could use the money they've 
raised for legal fees to pay the president's fine unless Clinton 
tells them he wants them to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	The award by U.S. District Judge Susan Webber Wright was on top  
of $850,000 Clinton paid to Mrs. Jones to settle the sexual 
harassment lawsuit she brought against him. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's testimony in the case led to his impeachment by the  
U.S. House and eventual acquittal in a Senate trial. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge in April issued a historic contempt ruling against  
Clinton and said she would order him to pay for costs that resulted 
from ``false, misleading and evasive answers'' in his January 1998 
deposition in Mrs. Jones' lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	The president's lawyers argued that a reasonable sanction should  
be in the range of $12,300 to $33,737. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Jones' lawyers, meanwhile, had requested $496,358 to cover  
costs incurred after Clinton's deposition. 
</P>
<P>
	In her order, Wright said the lawyers' claims were ``excessive  
and must be reduced.'' She denied compensation for various news 
conferences held by Mrs. Jones' lawyers, as well as attorney 
expenses associated with Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's probe 
of Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge limited the sanctions to the costs most directly  
associated with Clinton's testimony about Ms. Lewinsky, beginning 
after a written statement he gave on Dec. 23, 1997. The judge said 
about 20 percent of Clinton's Jan. 17, 1998, deposition dealt with 
Ms. Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas firm said Thursday that it could have sought more  
than $1 million, ``so the fees we requested are clearly fair and 
reasonable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Whitehead of the Rutherford Institute, a conservative group  
in Charlottesville, Va., that also represented Mrs. Jones' team, 
said he was pleased that Clinton was penalized but might appeal the 
amount. 
</P>
<P>
	John DiPippa, a constitutional law professor who has closely  
watched the case, said Mrs. Jones' lawyers should consider $90,000 
a victory and put an end to the case. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that the Jones attorneys come out better here in the  
end than the president,'' said DiPippa of the University of 
Arkansas at Little Rock. ``(The judge) took a more generous view 
than the president's attorneys and did so as a way to send a 
message to the president's lawyers and other attorneys that they 
shouldn't act like this in deposition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wright wrote in her order that she took ``no pleasure in  
imposing contempt sanctions'' against Clinton, but they were 
necessary to ``redress the president's misconduct and to deter 
others who might consider emulating the president's misconduct.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas law firm was awarded $79,999 and the Rutherford  
Institute $9,485. The judge also ordered Clinton to pay the court 
$1,202 for her trip to Washington at the president's request to 
preside over his deposition. 
</P>
<P>
	In her lawsuit, Mrs. Jones claimed that Clinton made an unwanted  
sexual advance in a Little Rock hotel room in 1991 while he was 
Arkansas governor and she was a state employee. Wright dismissed 
her suit on April 1, 1998, but Clinton agreed to the $850,000 
settlement after Mrs. Jones appealed the dismissal. Clinton 
admitted no wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Jones lawyers' drew Ms. Lewinsky into the case in an  
attempt to show a pattern of sexual misconduct by Clinton. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
