<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Officials Enforce Ignored Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- No blood, no foul? Not this summer.  
</P>
<P>
	Whistles are blowing and players are grumbling in the NBA's  
summer leagues, where officials are using a by-the-book approach to 
experimental rules aimed at boosting offense. Long-ignored rules 
are being enforced. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're calling the rules very literally. That's their job  
right now,'' said Portland coach Mike Dunleavy, watching his team 
of rookies and regular-season bench-warmers at the Rocky Mountain 
Revue. 
</P>
<P>
	A defender who uses a hand check or a forearm is immediately  
whistled for a foul. Likewise, an offensive player who moves while 
setting a screen will get tagged with a foul. 
</P>
<P>
	Another experimental rule bars defenders from impeding offensive  
players cutting through the lane. 
</P>
<P>
	Try guarding Shaquille O'Neal in the low post without a forearm  
in his back, or stop Allen Iverson off the dribble without a hand 
check. 
</P>
<P>
	``Players are used to putting their hands on people and moving  
them around,'' Sacramento coach Rick Adelman said. ``If they're not 
allowed to do that, it's going to make it much harder to guard 
people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One rule seeks to make illegal defense guidelines more  
understandable. Another sets the shot clock at 14 seconds after 
fouls or out-of-bounds plays in the frontcourt, rather than the 
usual 24 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	NBA director of officiating Ed Rush said the changes are  
intended to reinvigorate the plodding offenses of the 1990s, 
returning the league to the 100-point games that were the norm in 
earlier decades. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have the best athletes in the world,'' Rush said from the  
NBA offices in New York. ``Quickness and pure athleticism are big 
parts of basketball. We want to make sure our athletes have the 
chance to showcase their talents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But it backfired last week as play during some Salt Lake City  
games was agonizingly slow. 
</P>
<P>
	The Utah Jazz summer team had 49 fouls in one 40-minute game,  
the typical total in an NBA game for both teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Rush stressed no decision has been made on using the rules in  
the regular season. A 16-member committee of past and present 
players, coaches and front-office officials will meet before the 
season to evaluate the experiment. 
</P>
<P>
	``Will it make a difference if they call it like this during the  
regular season?'' Antonio Daniels of the San Antonio Spurs asked. 
``Without question. I think you'll see a lot of guys in foul 
trouble. A lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Daniels found a silver lining.  
</P>
<P>
	``On defense, you have to play with your feet and do more than  
using your hands,'' he said. ``Offensively, if you're quicker than 
somebody who's guarding you, it gives you a huge advantage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coaches and players at the Rocky Mountain Revue were reluctant  
to publicly criticize the experiment, but most agreed there's been 
plenty of griping in the locker room. 
</P>
<P>
	``Better to try it out here than in the regular season,''  
Adelman said. ``Everybody's going to complain. Players and coaches 
just have to adjust.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Daniels agrees players will have to deal with any changes.  
</P>
<P>
	``This takes you back to the fundamental way basketball is  
supposed to be played,'' Daniels said. ``Whether you like it or not 
is irrelevant. If they change the rules, you deal with it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 00:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Federal Judge Nominees Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A friend and former aide to the Senate  
Judiciary Committee chairman and the sister of a well-known New 
York real estate developer are among the latest nominees for 
federal judgeships approved by the panel. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. envoy to a regional multinational organization also is  
among the group, whose nominations advanced Thursday to the full 
Senate for consideration. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House only this week announced it had chosen Ted  
Stewart to be a U.S. District judge in Utah. He is an aide to the 
state's governor and friend and former employee of Sen. Orrin 
Hatch, R-Utah, the committee's chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart is opposed by some Democrats and environmentalists, and  
Hatch had stalled action on President Clinton's judicial nominees 
for months because of a deadlock with the administration over 
Stewart's selection. Hatch resumed confirmation hearings in June 
after saying Clinton had assured him that Stewart would be 
nominated. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Stewart, three candidates for the federal appeals  
court and four for district court vacancies in New York and 
California won approval Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee voted 10-8 to elevate U.S. District Judge Richard  
Paez of Los Angeles -- first nominated in January 1996 -- to the 9th 
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals. 
</P>
<P>
	The other seven nominations were approved by voice votes. All of  
the names moved to the Senate, but action there was not likely 
before the August recess. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven judicial nominations were pending in the Senate in advance  
of Thursday's committee votes, bringing the total awaiting final 
confirmation to 15, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine judges have been confirmed this year, compared with 33 by  
this time last year, said Sen. Patrick Leahy of Vermont, the 
committee's senior Democrat. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still remain well behind the pace of last year, but over  
the last few weeks we have been making progress,'' Leahy said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, a lawyer, served on Utah's Public Service Commission  
and was executive director of its Commerce and Natural Resources 
departments. At the resources agency, he criticized environmental 
groups and opposed federal land policies. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents cited the fact that Stewart never has tried a case and  
is listed as ``inactive'' by the Utah State Bar. His defenders say 
he gained judicial experience during his seven-year stint at the 
public service commission. The American Bar Association found him 
qualified to be a federal judge. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those who know Ted know he will continue to serve the public  
well,'' Hatch said Thursday at an earlier hearing on seven of the 
nominations. 
</P>
<P>
	Paez's nomination also has been controversial.  
</P>
<P>
	A Hispanic, Paez angered conservatives with his outspoken  
opposition to two California ballot initiatives that ended many 
state affirmative action programs and excluded many illegal 
immigrants from government benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	The other nominees approved are:  
</P>
<P>
	--U.S. District Judge Maryanne Trump Barry of New Jersey to the  
3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals. She is the sister of real estate 
mogul Donald Trump. 
</P>
<P>
	--Raymond C. Fisher of California to the 9th U.S. Circuit Court  
of appeals. A lawyer, Fisher has been an associate U.S. attorney 
general since 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	--Victor Marrero of New York to be a U.S. District judge for the  
Southern District of New York. A native of Santurce, Puerto Rico, 
and a former Fulbright Scholar, Marrero is U.S. ambassador to the 
Organization of American States. 
</P>
<P>
	--U.S. Magistrate Naomi Reice Buchwald of New York to be a U.S.  
District judge for the Southern District of New York. A former 
assistant U.S. attorney, Buchwald became a magistrate in 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	--U.S. Magistrate David N. Hurd of New York to be a U.S. District  
judge for the Northern District of New York. He has been a 
magistrate since 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	--M. James Lorenz of California to be a U.S. District judge for  
the Southern District of California. He is a former U.S. attorney. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
