<DOCNO> APW19990730.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 16:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tax Bill Has Special-Interest Terms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Companies that produce electricity from  
poultry waste, Vermont maple syrup tappers and Alaskan fishermen 
and others would benefit if special-interest provisions of the 
Senate tax bill become law. 
</P>
<P>
	As with most tax bills, lawmakers add language to help  
constituents and promote favorite causes, some that didn't make it 
as individual pieces of legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republicans' $792 billion tax cut package that passed the  
Senate on Friday and now goes to a House-Senate conference 
committee is no exception. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a presidential hopeful, issued his  
traditional statement criticizing special-interest provisions, 
although he liked enough of the bill to vote for it. 
</P>
<P>
	``How can we justify giving a $33 million tax break next year to  
companies producing electricity from chicken waste?'' McCain asked, 
when some working Social Security recipients have trouble making 
ends meet. 
</P>
<P>
	The poultry-waste electricity tax credit was added to the bill  
by Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	Individuals with foreign addresses would be exempt from paying a  
7.5 percent air passenger ticket tax on frequent flier miles, a 
provision McCain said would cost $238 million over 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, successfully attached provisions to  
help fishermen in his state through difficult harvest periods. 
</P>
<P>
	About five million Americans who are self-employed could deduct  
100 percent of their health insurance premiums as of next Jan. 1 
under a provision sponsored by Sen. Christopher Bond, R-Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	Vermont Sens. Patrick Leahy, a Democrat, and James Jeffords, a  
Republican, co-sponsored language to help a much smaller group: 
maple syrup foresters in Vermont. They would benefit from a change 
in the threshold for paying unemployment tax. 
</P>
<P>
	Only a handful of nonprofit organizations would benefit from an  
environmental cleanup tax break sponsored by Sen. Jim Bunning, 
R-Ky. It would give relief to nonprofits forced to clean up 
hazardous waste on property they owned before the Superfund cleanup 
law took effect. At least one and possibly two Kentucky 
organizations would benefit, along with a handful in other states. 
</P>
<P>
	In an effort to ease estate taxes, Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., had  
a provision attached to expand tax breaks for land kept from 
development. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Restaurant Association praised a provision to  
extend the Work Opportunity Tax Credit for five years. One in four 
restaurants utilize the program to employ and train former welfare 
recipients, the organization said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 15:07:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> British Newspaper Deal Worth $1.98B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Trinity has won the battle for the Mirror Group,  
reaching a deal to acquire the publisher of the tabloid Daily 
Mirror for $1.98 billion in stock and cash 
</P>
<P>
	The new company, to be called Trinity Mirror, will be Britain's  
largest regional newspaper company, with 155 newspapers that have a 
weekly circulation of more than 15.3 million and a daily 
circulation of 2.3 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``The merged group will have enhanced scale and financial  
strength providing a strong platform for future expansion,'' 
Trinity chairman Peter Birch said. 
</P>
<P>
	The union is expected to yield annual cost savings of $24  
million by the end of 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal appears to shut the door on a potential third bid for  
Mirror, by an ousted former chief executive of Mirror Group, David 
Montgomery, who said last week he was trying to arrange backing for 
an offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Trinity will pay the equivalent of $4.34 per Mirror share, well  
above the roughly $3.20 offered by rival bidder Regional 
Independent Media. Trinity shareholders will own 48.4 percent of 
the new company, with Mirror investors holding 51.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Trinity chief executive Phil Graf will become head of the new  
group, while Trinity's finance director, Mike Masters, will be 
responsible for regional newspapers. Mirror's head of national 
newspapers, Roger Eastoe, will keep that role in the new business. 
</P>
<P>
	``The strategic fit between our two businesses enables us to  
build further on our market-leading positions,'' Mirror Chairman 
Victor Blank said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State for Trade and Industry Stephen Byers approved  
the deal last week on condition that Trinity sell off its four 
newspapers in Northern Ireland, where Mirror Group already owns 
several titles. Byers said he was concerned that there needed to be 
a diverse ownership of newspapers in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition still needs approval from shareholders and  
British regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	Trinity's papers include the Western Mail, the Liverpool Echo  
and Daily Post and the Newcastle Journal. Mirror Group owns 
Scotland's Daily Record and Sunday Mail along with the Daily 
Mirror. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
