<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ray, Calkins: Fitness Key at Dover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DOVER, Del. (AP) -- Even if the fastest car wins the MBNA  
Mid-Atlantic 200 at Dover Downs International Speedway, Indy Racing 
League drivers Greg Ray and Buzz Calkins are convinced the fittest 
driver will be a contender. 
</P>
<P>
	``When it's hot and you test here, you're whipped after 40  
laps,'' said Ray, one of a growing number of physical culturists on 
the circuit. ``On Sunday, we've got to run 200, and that's going to 
be tough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unless the current weather pattern of excessively high heat and  
humidity on the East Coast changes unexpectedly, IRL drivers will 
battle fatigue and its chief derivative -- lack of concentration -- 
as well as each other on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ray, who got his lone IRL victory last month in Fountain, Colo.,  
has a strict workout regimen he says is invaluable in maintaining 
stamina in the race car. The day before he won at Pikes Peak 
International Raceway, Ray took an 18-mile hike through the 
mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	That helped him combat the effect of the mile-high altitude in  
the foothills of the Rocky Mountains. But the temperature was not 
flirting with the century mark, as it had been for the last week in 
Dover. 
</P>
<P>
	``You get tired much more easily,'' said Ray, a Texan who knows  
plenty about heat and humidity. ``When you are overcome by fatigue, 
you make mistakes. Those two things go hand in hand.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ray, who tries to jog several miles every day, gets no argument  
from Calkins -- perhaps the best runner among all the world's 
drivers. He competed this year in the New York City Marathon, 
posting a middle-of-the-pack finish in just above 4 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	``Your heart rate in a race car under green conditions is about  
150-160 beats per minute,'' said Calkins, who won the inaugural IRL 
race and shared the first championship in 1996 with defending Dover 
race champion Scott Sharp. ``It's about the same for a marathon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Calkins says people who don't race are surprised by that. Also  
points out that the battle between gravity and centrifugal force on 
the body on a banked track cannot be realized in a passenger 
vehicle on a flat roadway. 
</P>
<P>
	And Calkins insists that the sleek open-wheel cars used in the  
IRL are designed for nothing more than speed. There is no comfort. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people envision it like a street car, with power  
steering, with springs and shocks that absorb the bumps real 
well,'' he said. ``We don't have that. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're basically taking shots, and in the corners of  
high-banked tracks like this we're subjected to about 4 Gs with 
5,000 pounds of downforce.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Calkins says there is virtually no time to relax because much of  
the one-mile surface is comprised of turns banked at 24 degrees. 
Most of a 19-second lap at better than 180 mph is spent setting up, 
running through and exiting these turns. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mentally and physically, a place like this really taps you,''  
Ray said. ``The guys who are the best qualifiers might not be the 
guys you'll see running for it at the end.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Calkins plans to be one of them. He can't predict race  
circumstances, but says he won't lose because he isn't ready for 
the physical demands. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the beginning of the race there's considerable stress with  
so many cars on the track,'' he said. ``Later, after attrition 
takes its toll, that stress becomes a battle with fatigue. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I want to do is stay out of trouble and be there at the  
end.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ray hopes for the same scenario, but says that a narrow track  
with such high banking and sharp turns presents a set of problems 
not common to most layouts on which the IRL races. With that in 
mind, he has trained especially hard for his appointment with The 
Monster Mile. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're not interested in defeating The Monster when you  
work out, then The Monster will eat you up,'' Ray said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
