<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lions Enlist Sanders' Father Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Barry Sanders' father said late Friday he would  
encourage his son to meet with Detroit Lions vice chairman William 
Clay Ford Jr. in the executive's efforts to talk the star running 
back out of retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	But even to William Sanders, the prospect of a meeting remained  
uncertain Friday night, given that Barry Sanders was touring Europe 
and his father was unable to immediately reach his son. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders, 31, shocked the football world Wednesday by announcing  
his retirement after 10 years, although he's just 1,458 yards shy 
of breaking Walter Payton's NFL career rushing record of 16,726 
yards. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement released by his lawyer and agent, Sanders said:  
``My desire to exit the game is greater than my desire to remain in 
it'' for what would be the third year of a six-year, $36 million 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Those stunned by Sanders' move included Ford, who called  
Sanders' father at his Wichita, Kan., home Wednesday morning and 
sought his help in arranging a meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told him I'd do everything I can,'' the elder Sanders said.  
</P>
<P>
	``The guy really seemed like he was on the up-and-up, a man of  
his word,'' William Sanders said Friday night. ``Just in talking to 
him, he seemed awfully impressive. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to try to change his mind. But I will ask him to  
contact Mr. Ford. I think that's only fair.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lions spokesman Bill Keenist on Friday night acknowledged that  
Ford spoke with the elder Sanders on the day Barry Sanders 
announced his retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bill and Mr. Sanders did speak on the phone Wednesday morning,  
but that's the extent of what I can tell you,'' Keenist said. 
``Bill suggested that if there was anything he could do, that he 
would be available, and Mr. Sanders acknowledged that, and that was 
the extent of the discussion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders' retirement is not final, at least not technically. The  
Lions have put him on the reserve-did not report list, which would 
allow him to rejoin the team this season. Sanders also has not 
filed retirement papers with the league office. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's still possible (Sanders could return), and that's the  
basis of placing Barry in the category that we did,'' Lions coach 
Bobby Ross said. ``We've got to proceed as though he's not going to 
be here, but I'd be very happy if he came back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked Wednesday at London's Gatwick Airport whether he might  
change his mind, Sanders said: ``I don't think that's going to 
happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But his father said he believes his son will meet with Ford.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think he'll listen to me. He has nothing to lose. The odds  
are in Mr. Ford's favor,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no way of reaching him. In fact, I don't think he wants  
to be reached,'' William Sanders said of his son. ``I think he 
wants to just do his own thing.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 22:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Wins Water Polo Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Chris Humbert was so sick with an ear  
infection he couldn't even play in the first two games of the water 
polo competition at the Pan Am Games. 
</P>
<P>
	And when he came to the gold medal game against Cuba on Friday  
night, he was still ailing. His temperature was 101. 
</P>
<P>
	So what did the 6-foot-7 former California prep basketball star  
do to make him and his teammates, who have also been under the 
weather, feel better? 
</P>
<P>
	He scored five goals as the United States rolled to an 11-7  
victory, clinching a berth in the Sydney Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``This week hasn't been a lot of fun. We had to quarantine all  
the sick guys,'' said Humbert, regarded as one of the world's best 
water polo players, manning the two-meter post. ``We've had a lot 
of coughing, nasal congestion and headaches. We've come through 
some adversity and this feels good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Humbert, who once scored 46 points in a high school game, got  
his first goal 30 seconds into the game Friday night. The Americans 
led 2-1 after one period and then swam away. 
</P>
<P>
	Christopher Oeding and Humbert got behind the Cuban defense and  
took long passes from goalie Daniel Hackett for easy scores within 
40 seconds of one another to open the second period. The United 
States led 6-2 at the half and 10-3 after three periods, using 
their superior swimming ability and strength. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just wanted to get on them early and make it clear to them  
they were not going to be competitive,'' Humbert said. 
</P>
<P>
	With Humbert out early in the tournament, the United States had  
beaten Cuba just 6-4. That's how big a difference the big 
left-hander makes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Half our team has been sick,'' U.S. coach John Vargas said.  
``But we were confident going in that if we played our game, no 
team would be able to stay with us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United States has not won an Olympic water polo medal since  
claiming silver in 1988 at Calgary. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 09:00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Driver Waltrip To Retire Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Darrell Waltrip, a three-time Winston Cup  
champion who has not won a race in seven years, plans to retire 
after stock car racing's 2000 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Waltrip has scheduled a news conference for next Thursday in  
Indianapolis to make a formal announcement, The Atlanta 
Journal-Constitution reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's sad to see (Waltrip) retire, but I guess it's good when  
someone can call it quits on their own terms,'' Phillipe Lopez, 
Waltrip's crew chief, told the paper. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is just at a point where he wants to see and do other  
things in life, especially be at home more with his family. 
</P>
<P>
	Travis Carter, co-owner of Waltrip's No. 66 Ford Taurus, said,  
``Time waits for no man; (it's) time to move on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Waltrip, 52, of Franklin, Tenn., leads all active Winston Cup  
drivers with 84 career victories but has not won a race since 
Darlington in September 1992. He finished 25th at last week's 
Pennsylvania 500 at Pocono Raceway. 
</P>
<P>
	Waltrip sold his team last year after owning it for eight years,  
citing continuing disputes with sponsors and other financial 
reasons. At the time, he said the 1999 season would be his last. 
</P>
<P>
	He changed his mind after signing a two-year sponsorship deal  
with Kmart at the end of last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Waltrip's team is making preparations for a farewell tour next  
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are going to do everything in our power to make sure  
Darrell goes out with a bang at each and every race,'' Lopez said. 
</P>
<P>
	Waltrip has indicated a desire to enter broadcasting after  
retiring. He has done race commentary for The Nashville Network. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990730.0331 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 13:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amy Carter Gives Birth to Boy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Amy Carter has given birth to a baby boy, the  
10th grandchild of former President Jimmy Carter, 74, and his wife 
Rosalynn. 
</P>
<P>
	Hugo James Wentzel was born Thursday about 9 p.m., weighing 7  
pounds 13 ounces and measuring 20 inches. 
</P>
<P>
	Both mother and child were doing fine, Carrie Harmon, a  
spokeswoman for the Carter Center, said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter, 31, and her husband of three years, James Wentzel, live  
in Atlanta near the Carter Center, where she was elected to the 
board of councilors in March 1998. 
  	   	
</P>
