<DOCNO> APW19990730.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 14:40:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Prices Dip; Grain Prices Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Crude oil futures slid sharply towards the close of trading  
Friday and other energy futures also gave back recent gains. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, grain futures posted strong gains and coffee  
fell. 
</P>
<P>
	The crude oil market was sluggish much of the day until the  
close of trade approached. Then the price of the September contract 
got as high as $21.10 a barrel, flirting with a 21-month high, 
before dropping as low as $20.48 in the last hour, said Tim Evans, 
an analyst with the Pegasus Econometric Group in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't seen a whole lot of news. Sometimes it just  
happens,'' said George Beranek, an analyst with Petroleum Finance 
Co. in Washington. ``Sometimes later on Fridays the trading thins 
out and things can happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	September crude oil futures prices had hit a 21-month spot  
contract high of $21.12 a barrel during trading on Thursday, driven 
in part by the strength of gasoline. 
</P>
<P>
	Gasoline prices have been on an upward trend this year, driven  
in part by reduced oil production by the Organization of the 
Petroleum Exporting Countries and helped by rising demand during 
the peak summer travel season. 
</P>
<P>
	Natural gas has received a lift from the recent heat wave.  
Electric utilities often fire up their natural gas units in times 
of peak demand. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Unleaded gasoline and natural gas both gave back  
gains posted earlier in the week. 
</P>
<P>
	Evans said there was little news to drive the market Friday.  
Rather, he believed market participants were anticipating the 
expiration of the August contract at the close of Friday's session. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe this run up this week was the August contract reaching  
expiration rather than how tight the gasoline market is,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude for September delivery fell 44 cents to $20.53 a barrel;  
August heating oil fell 0.56 cent to 52.17 cents a gallon; August 
unleaded gasoline rose 0.15 cent to 65.13 cents a gallon; September 
natural gas fell 0.26 cent to $2.543 for each 1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, North Sea Brent Blend crude oil for delivery in  
September fell 43 cents to $19.37 a barrel at the International 
Petroleum Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Grain futures prices were higher Friday on the Chicago Board of  
Trade as the Midwest continued to bake under stifling heat and 
humidity. 
</P>
<P>
	Grains started higher on follow-through from Thursday's strong  
showing, and mostly maintained the gains through the close. 
</P>
<P>
	Both corn and wheat posted gains, shaking off news that more  
favorable weather may be in store for heat-addled growing regions. 
September and December wheat contracts, which represent the fall 
harvest, hit their highest levels of the month. 
</P>
<P>
	``This week we went through a critical time frame with corn,''  
said Don Roose, president of Iowa-based U.S. Commodities Inc. ``For 
the areas that didn't get the rain, this heat really took a toll.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The heat, which reached the high 90s and triple digits in key  
growing states Friday, could bake parched crops and reduce yields. 
</P>
<P>
	Gains were limited by the more favorable weather forecasts for  
this weekend and next week. Forecasters are calling for rain and 
cooler temperatures throughout the region. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean prices were mixed Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	``The soybeans can withstand the heat a lot better than the  
corn,'' Roose said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 6 1/4 cents to $2.79 3/4 a bushel;  
December corn rose 3 1/4 cents to $2.14 1/2 a bushel; December oats fell 
4 3/4 cents to $1.11 3/4 a bushel; November soybeans fell 1/4 cent to 
$4.33 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures were mixed and pork higher Friday on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle fell 0.10 cent to 64.22 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose 0.17 cent to 76.87 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs rose 0.67 cent to 48.27 cents a pound; August pork bellies 
rose 3.0 cents to 52.12 cents a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee prices fell Friday when the end of a truckers strike in  
Brazil eased shipping concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee for September delivery fell 4.0 cents to 91.10 cents a  
pound on the Coffee, Sugar &AMP; Cocoa Exchange in New York, the lowest 
price since Jan. 3, 1996. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
