<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FTC Wants Online Pharmacies Watched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- To help state authorities monitor how well  
online pharmacies are complying with the law, the Federal Trade 
Commission wants Congress to force Internet sites that sell 
prescription drugs to disclose more information about their 
businesses and doctors. 
</P>
<P>
	In making the recommendations, the FTC recognized the limits of  
its own authority in monitoring online pharmacies and the 
challenges state officials face because of jurisdictional problems 
and the lack of adequate identifying information on the Web sites. 
</P>
<P>
	``State authorities appear to have laws that are substantively  
adequate to stop irresponsible prescribing and dispensing of drugs 
via the Internet,'' Jodie Bernstein, director of the FTC's Bureau 
of Consumer Protection, said. ``The real challenge lies in dealing 
with the logistical difficulties of identifying responsible parties 
and enforcing laws across states boundaries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bernstein was to testify today before the House Commerce  
subcommittee on oversight and investigations about the need for new 
laws covering Internet pharmacies. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC says the sites should contain the name, address and  
phone number of the pharmacy that will dispense the drugs and where 
that pharmacy is licensed to do business. Similar information also 
should be provided about physicians who prescribe drugs over the 
Internet, as well as the states where that physician is licensed or 
authorized to practice medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	There should also be information about any Internet operator --  
separate from the doctor or pharmacy -- that is offering the drugs 
for sale, including the principal owners of the business. 
</P>
<P>
	The site should tell consumers the states from which it will  
accept orders. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission says such disclosures are needed because of the  
new problems posed by Internet pharmacies, even as consumers enjoy 
the cost-savings and convenience. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, a consumer might go to a Web site and have an  
online consultation with an unknown doctor who then prescribes 
drugs for the pharmacy to dispense. 
</P>
<P>
	Prescriptions could be issued without adequate review of a  
patient's medical history, posing serious health threats, Bernstein 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	It is illegal for doctors to prescribe for patients in a state  
where they are not licensed to practice. Licensed doctors also must 
meet standards of care that in most states require a patient 
relationship to prescribe drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Some online pharmacies stress they operate with the same  
standards as a traditional pharmacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Customers at drugstore.com, for example, must already have  
prescriptions from their doctors, which must be either mailed or 
faxed to the store, said Peter Neupert, the company's president and 
chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must be careful to distinguish between safe, legitimate  
online pharmacies and profiteers using the Internet to engage in 
illegal activities with willing participants,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that the company has applied for approval from an  
online certification program established by the National 
Association of Boards of Pharmacy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
