<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Katzenberg Gets New DreamWorks Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Fresh from settlement of a bonus dispute with  
his former employer, Jeffrey Katzenberg has some new bosses -- at 
the DreamWorks SKG studio, where he is a principal owner. 
</P>
<P>
	Katzenberg said Thursday he is taking over as interim head of  
production at DreamWorks, the studio he founded with Steven 
Spielberg and David Geffen. He replaces Robert Cooper, who is 
forming his own production company. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseeing day-to-day film development, Katzenberg will report  
to Spielberg and feature-film chiefs Walter Parkes and Laurie 
MacDonald, while technically remaining one of Parkes and 
MacDonald's bosses. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm back where I was in 1981 and glad to be there,'' said  
Katzenberg, referring to his time as a production executive at 
Paramount before he went to Disney in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	Katzenberg this month settled a three-year legal fight with  
Disney over bonus money owed him from his tenure as studio chief. 
With that behind him, and DreamWorks' plans for a Los Angeles 
studio at Playa Vista fallen through, Katzenberg had time to take 
on the extra work when Cooper announced he was leaving, MacDonald 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``When all this came up, there was no one we felt was right who  
could come in immediately,'' MacDonald said. ``Rather than make an 
impulsive decision, the decision was to try to work it out 
internally.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Katzenberg will remain in the job until DreamWorks finds a  
long-term replacement for Cooper, MacDonald said. She said it was 
unknown how long that would take. 
</P>
<P>
	While taking a subordinate role on live-action films, Katzenberg  
said he will retain control over DreamWorks' animation and 
television operations. Final live-action film decisions will remain 
in Spielberg's hands, MacDonald said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Could there possibly be anybody better to work for in  
live-action film than Steven Spielberg? I don't think so,'' 
Katzenberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	After agreeing to the setup, Katzenberg assured MacDonald and  
Parkes he would have no problem taking a back seat on production 
decisions and that he would not try to overrule them, MacDonald 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Traditional studio hierarchies do not apply at DreamWorks,  
MacDonald said. Spielberg, Katzenberg and Geffen founded DreamWorks 
in 1994, saying it would be a studio that would minimize 
bureaucracy and leave more control in the hands of the artists. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no ego problems with dividing up the work in different  
ways,'' MacDonald said. ``It's always better to figure out what 
each individual's gifts are and make the company work around the 
gifts, rather than try to work around the traditional structures.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cooper had been at DreamWorks for two years. The first two films  
scheduled for release under Cooper's supervision are ``American 
Beauty'' with Kevin Spacey and Annette Bening and ``Galaxy Quest'' 
with Tim Allen and Sigourney Weaver. Both are due out this year. 
</P>
<P>
	A former Tristar Pictures president, Cooper will continue his  
association with DreamWorks as a producer. Some of the projects he 
has in the works were films he began developing as DreamWorks' head 
of production. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bob's creativity, energy and intelligence are reflected in the  
projects he championed, and we are happy he will continue to be 
part of our team through his new role as a producer,'' Spielberg 
said in a news release. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
